<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Five Chileans convicted in the 1989  
kidnapping of a leading businessmen should be allowed to complete 
their sentences in their home country, their spokesman said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Breno Altman, president of the Committee to Free Political  
Prisoners, said by phone the release was authorized last Friday by 
the Justice Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry confirmed the authorization but gave no further  
details. 
</P>
<P>
	The five Chileans were sentenced along with two Argentines, two  
Canadians and a Brazilian to 28 years in prison for abducting 
Abilio Diniz, owner of Brazil's largest supermarket chain along. 
Police rescued Diniz after six days, unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Late last year their sentences were reduced to between 15 and 18  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	On Nov. 16, the 10 went on a hunger strike to pressure the  
government to release them, and four days later, Canadians David 
Lamont and Christine Spencer were transferred to a Vancouver prison 
under a prisoner-transfer treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brazilian was sent home and placed on work-release, but the  
transfer of the Chileans and Argentines was delayed ``because of 
bureaucracy,'' Altman said. He said the Argentines are expected to 
be transferred in about two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A man accused of raping and trying to kill a  
14-year-old girl was transferred to the northern state of Chihuahua 
Tuesday after prosecutors said he may be linked to as many as six 
murders in Ciudad Juarez. 
</P>
<P>
	Chihuahua State Attorney General Arturo Gonzalez Rascon said the  
man, Jesus Manuel Guardado Marquez -- a former bus driver -- may hold 
the key to the mystery surrounding the six-year string of killings. 
</P>
<P>
	In a pre-trial statement, Guardado said he had consensual sex  
with the 14-year-old and tried to kill her in June 1998, but denied 
involvement in any of the other killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Guardado was arrested over the weekend in the neighboring state  
of Durango, after he allegedly beat his pregnant wife. He also 
allegedly tried to beat the 14-year-old victim to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say about 100 women, mostly teens, have been killed since  
1993 in Ciudad Juarez, across the border from El Paso, Texas. 
Independent groups say the number could be as high as 192. The 
victims were raped or sexually brutalized in 54 cases. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico City's grand central plaza, the  
Zocalo, is to be transformed into a center of blooming trees under 
a renovation design selected by city officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning model, by architect Cecilia Cortes Contreras, will  
reroute the traffic that now rings the huge square in order to 
focus visitors' attention on surrounding historic buildings such as 
the Metropolitan Cathedral and the National Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	The renovation, proposed by Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in 1998,  
is to cost an estimated $15 million and be completed by the end of 
the year, the daily Reforma reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The design unveiled by Mexico City officials Tuesday night would  
have rows of purple-blossomed jacaranda trees and mimosas planted 
along one side of the Zocalo. 
</P>
<P>
	It also calls for 18 light poles each 65-feet high which would  
generate sounds with the wind, and an alley of shorter light poles 
to light the way toward the ancient ruins of the Templo Mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the plaza will remain clear, in keeping with its  
traditional use as a center for union rallies and political 
protests. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Interpol agents in Mexico have arrested the  
former interior minister of Ecuador, Cesar Verduga, who is wanted 
on embezzlement charges for allegedly misusing $5.3 million in 
state funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Verduga was arrested late Monday at his home in the upscale  
Mexico City neighborhood of Polanco, Mexico City newspapers 
reported Wednesday. He was taken to a prison pending Ecuador's 
formal request for extradition. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Pablo Guerrero, said Wednesday that Verduga would  
request political asylum in Mexico because he believes the case 
against him is politically motivated, the government news agency 
Notimex reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Verduga, who was former Ecuadoran President Fabian Alarcon's  
right-hand man from February 1997 to April 1998, claims the money 
in question was used for a study, which he says he burned along 
with receipts for reasons of national security. 
</P>
<P>
	Verduga fled to the United States in April 1998 just before a  
court order for his arrest was issued. He later settled in Mexico 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook villages  
in southern and central Costa Rica but apparently caused no damage 
or injuries, the National University Seismological Observatory 
reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The magnitude 6 quake struck at 11:54 p.m. Tuesday, about 125  
miles south of Punta Burica near the border with Panama. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake, which was felt in the capital, caused alarm in the  
coastal towns of Golfito and Puerto Jimenez, Red Cross spokesman 
Marvin Hidalgo said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Guatemala's Supreme Court has upheld death  
sentences against three men convicted of kidnapping a woman in 1996 
and killing her. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruling, issued Tuesday, supported lower court  
decisions against Elver Alvarado, Luis Cetino and Tomas Cerrate. 
</P>
<P>
	The three are to die by lethal injection for the killing of  
Isabel Bonifasi de Botran. No date for execution was set. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonifasi de Botran was kidnapped in southern Guatemala City on  
Nov. 16, 1996, and her body was found two months later near a 
village outside the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
