<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Futures' Investors Get Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investors thinking of sinking their money into  
oil futures or pork bellies now have an online option to check out 
the background and disciplinary information on some 50,000 
companies and salespeople in the commodity futures industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Internet database, unveiled Wednesday, ``provides  
investors with a valuable tool to protect themselves against fraud 
and abuse,'' Brooksley Born, chairwoman of the U.S. Commodity 
Futures Trading Commission, said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Named BASIC, for Background Affiliation Status Information  
Center, it is available on the Web site of the National Futures 
Association at www.nfa.futures.org. The information comes from the 
self-regulatory association, the Commodity Futures Trading 
Commission and the nation's 14 futures exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The database, includes, for example, enforcement cases filed by  
the CFTC since 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	A futures contract obligates a trader to buy or sell a commodity  
at a fixed price at a specific time in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The database is similar to the national repository of data on  
stockbrokers' disciplinary and legal history that is jointly 
operated by the National Association of Securities Dealers and 
state securities regulators. Investors are encouraged to look up 
those records before hiring a broker or making an investment with 
one they don't know. 
</P>
<P>
	The new database on futures dealers or companies also can be  
used by investors to file complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The CFTC, which regulates the nation's futures markets, recently  
issued consumer advisories urging people to watch out for 
fraudulent futures schemes and to take precautions before they 
invest. 
</P>
<P>
	Born noted that in addition to TV, radio and print ads,  
fraudulent futures investment schemes increasingly are being 
promoted in Internet e-mail and ``chat rooms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, for example, the hottest new telemarketing fraud  
played on people's vague awareness of Asian economic turmoil and 
hunger for hefty returns to get them to invest in risky 
foreign-currency futures. 
</P>
<P>
	The investment schemes -- modeled after legitimate  
currency-market trading done by financial institutions -- were just 
a come-on and none of the money handed over was actually invested, 
according to state regulators. Investors around the country lost 
thousands of dollars, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the new database, Marc Beauchamp, a spokesman for  
the North American Securities Administrators Association, which 
represents state regulators, said that with rising numbers of 
investors going online, ``It makes great sense to make this 
information available 24 hours a day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested that investors could use the database, for example,  
to check out a salesman pitching a futures investment over the 
telephone ``while you've got him on the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The database lists salespeople and companies that are registered  
with the CFTC. If a particular person or firm isn't listed, or is 
listed as having had their registration revoked, they are 
unregistered and are likely selling futures investments illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	The database does not include criminal background information,  
such as felony convictions, for salespeople and companies. 
Investors must file a Freedom of Information Act request for that 
information with the CFTC. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14 U.S. futures exchanges involved are the Chicago Board of  
Trade; the Chicago Mercantile Exchange; the New York Mercantile 
Exchange; Amex Commodities Corp.; Cantor Financial Futures 
Exchange; Citrus Associates of the New York Cotton Exchange; the 
Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange; the Commodity Exchange; the 
Kansas City Board of Trade; the Mid-America Commodity Exchange; the 
Minneapolis Grain Exchange; the New York Cotton Exchange; the New 
York Futures Exchange and the Philadelphia Board of Trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
