<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Three U.S. Soldiers May Be Captured  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three U.S. Army soldiers were missing in  
Macedonia near the Yugoslav border Wednesday night after possibly 
being captured by members of the Serb military or police while on a 
reconnaissance mission, the Pentagon and NATO officials said. An 
immediate search and rescue mission was launched, involving teams 
from several NATO countries. The team had been on a daytime 
reconnaissance mission when they reported receiving ``small arms 
fire and said they were surrounded,'' according to NATO. The 
missing team was one of several Army units guarding the 
Yugoslav-Macedonia border during the ongoing NATO airstrikes 
against the Serb military in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Expands Yugoslavia Bombardment  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO widened its air assault on  
Yugoslavia Wednesday, vowing there would be ``no sanctuary'' for 
Yugoslav forces trying to rid Kosovo of ethnic Albanians. With the 
air campaign against President Slobodan Milosevic's forces entering 
its second week, Western officials acknowledged that NATO's 
missiles and bombs had so far failed to stop Belgrade's offensive 
in the province. Thousands more refugees from the province poured 
across the frontier into neighboring countries. At least 118,000 
ethnic Albanians have fled to Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, 
the U.N. says. 

</P>
<P>
	Canada Celebrates New Territory  
</P>
<P>
	IQALUIT, Nunavut (AP) -- Inuit chefs prepared a huge feast  
Wednesday to celebrate the creation of Nunavut, Canada's newest 
territory. Stretching deep into the Arctic, with only 25,000 
residents in an area as large as Western Europe, Nunavut is the 
product of the largest land-claims settlement in Canada's history 
and gives its Inuit majority their long-sought chance at 
self-government. Nunavut is being created out of the eastern 60 
percent of the Northwest Territories, culminating more than 20 
years of lobbying by Inuit leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! To Acquire Broadcast.com  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. has agreed to acquire Broadcast.com  
Inc. for $5.6 billion in stock, according to a source. 
Broadcast.com is the Internet's leading supplier of radio and video 
programs. The transaction will be announced Thursday. Yahoo! is one 
of the premier destinations on the Internet. The company's stock 
has risen 264 percent in the past 12 months. This is Yahoo!'s 
second major deal this year. The company announced the $4.58 
billion acquisition of GeoCities in January. 

</P>
<P>
	Comic Gary Morton Dies at 74  
</P>
<P>
	RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Gary Morton, the Borscht Belt comic  
who married Lucille Ball and became her executive producer, has 
died. He was 74. Morton died Tuesday at Eisenhower Memorial 
Hospital, said John Caranci of Wiefels &AMP; Son Funeral Directors in 
Palm Springs. The cause of death wasn't disclosed, but Daily 
Variety reported he died of lung cancer. Morton, a stand-up comic, 
married Miss Ball after she divorced Desi Arnaz, her ``I Love 
Lucy'' sidekick. Morton and the actress were married for 29 years; 
Miss Ball died in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
	David Kelley Shows Win Peabodys  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two prime-time series produced by David E.  
Kelley, Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' and ABC's ``The Practice,'' on 
Wednesday won Peabody Awards for broadcast and cable excellence. 
One-third of the 33 awards went to programs that aired on PBS 
stations or to a PBS executive. The awards, chosen from among 
nearly 1,300 entries, are administered by the University of 
Georgia's Henry W. Grady College of Journalism and Mass 
Communications. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Share Prices Advance  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rebounded Thursday morning on  
continued buying from foreign investors. The Nikkei Stock Average 
gained 265.48 points to close the morning session at 16,102.07. In 
New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,786.16 
points Wednesday, down 127.10 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Australia Shuffles Games Torch Job  
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian IOC member Phil Coles was  
removed from his role as the Sydney 2000 Olympics torch relay chief 
Thursday. The SOCOG organizing board has decided to replace Coles 
with Anna Booth as chair of the torch relay committee. Coles is 
under investigation by the IOC for accepting excessive hospitality 
from the Salt Lake bidders that won the 2002 Winter Games. He is 
also being investigated following his ex-wife's claims that he took 
jewelry from a Greek businessman associated with Athens' failed bid 
for the 1996 Summer Games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
