<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Bush Raises $6M for Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush, seeking to bolster his  
front-runner standing in the polls, announced today he has raised 
more than $6 million for a possible Republican presidential 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's presidential exploratory committee has raked in cash at a  
rate of nearly $2 million a week since opening its bank account on 
March 4 and finance chairman Don Evans said contributions still are 
being tallied. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee said the $6 million was raised without  
fund-raising events, relying on mailings and ``friend-to-friend'' 
contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great start, but I recognize that we have a lot of  
work ahead,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am honored and humbled that so many friends throughout Texas  
and America are donating to my exploratory effort to encourage me 
to run for president,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and other presidential hopefuls must file reports with the  
Federal Election Commission on April 15, covering donations from 
Jan. 1 through March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's total appears to have well outpaced other Republicans.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, a spokesman for Dan Quayle, who served as  
vice president under Bush's father, said Quayle was expected to 
have around $2 million raised when campaigns file reports on April 
15. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who had a fund-raiser last week in  
New York; conservative activist Gary Bauer; and Rep. John Kasich of 
Ohio, who is spending the week raising money on the West Coast, 
also are expected to disclose at least $1 million in contributions 
for the period Jan. 1 through March 31, campaign officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush this week said he is considering forgoing federal matching  
funds, taxpayer assistance to candidates who agree to spending 
limits. That would allow him to compete better against millionaire 
publisher Steve Forbes, whose self-financed candidacy has no 
spending restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Political experts estimate that Bush would have to raise around  
$50 million to be able to go that route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
