<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Widens Yugoslavia Campaign  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Widening its air assault on  
Yugoslavia, NATO pounded targets today near a major Kosovo city and 
vowed there would be ``no sanctuary'' for Yugoslav forces trying to 
rid Kosovo of ethnic Albanians. With the air campaign against 
President Slobodan Milosevic's forces entering its second week, 
Western officials acknowledged that NATO's missiles and bombs had 
so far failed to stop Belgrade's offensive in the province. Ethnic 
Albanian refugees arriving today in northern Albania said that NATO 
airstrikes in southern Kosovo have been ineffective so far. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton OKS $50M Aid for Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, moving to stem a  
humanitarian crisis after more than 100,000 refugees left Kosovo 
for Macedonia and Albania, today offered $50 million in food and 
supplies that will be delivered by U.S. military airlift. ``They 
are fleeing a murder machine,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon 
said of Serb forces. The Clinton administration says President 
Slobodan Milosevic risks losing international support for his claim 
to the Serb province. 

</P>
<P>
	McDougal's Story Corroborated  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A witness today corroborated Susan  
McDougal's story that she was pressured to cooperate in Kenneth 
Starr's Whitewater investigation of President Clinton and his wife. 
Testifying in McDougal's criminal contempt trial, Claudia Riley 
said that on one occasion she overheard a prosecutor telling 
McDougal that Starr's office could ``get you out of'' a California 
embezzlement case and a federal income tax investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Verdict Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The judge in the Microsoft antitrust case  
today promised to resume the marathon trial in mid-May, which would 
delay any verdict until late summer or early fall. The extended 
recess provides Microsoft and the government more time to try to 
negotiate a settlement, although one round of talks ended 
unsuccessfully late yesterday after only two hours. In those 
negotiations at the Justice Department Microsoft's top legal 
negotiators couldn't reach common ground with government lawyers, a 
person close to the discussions said. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Expect To Meet Y2K Deadline  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly all federal government agencies have  
fixed and tested their ``mission-critical'' computer systems and 
should be ready to accurately process data come Jan. 1, 2000, 
Clinton administration officials said today. The President's 
Council on Year 2000 Conversion reported that 92 percent of the 
government's 24 largest agencies are Y2K compliant. The Y2K bug 
occurs because many computers programmed to recognize only the last 
two digits of a year won't work properly beginning Jan. 1, 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Rev. Lyons Sentenced to 5 1/2 Years  
</P>
<P>
	LARGO, Fla. (AP) -- The Rev. Henry Lyons was sentenced to 5 1/2  
years in prison today for swindling more than $4 million while 
president of one of the nation's largest and most influential black 
denominations. The minister was also ordered to repay almost $2.5 
million. Lyons was convicted Feb. 27 of bilking companies wanting 
to sell cemetery products, life insurance policies and credit cards 
to members of the National Baptist Convention USA. He was also 
found guilty of stealing money donated to rebuild burned Southern 
black churches. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Cops Charged in Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four white police officers who killed unarmed  
African immigrant Amadou Diallo in a fusillade of 41 bullets were 
charged with second-degree murder in an indictment unsealed today. 
All four officers appeared in state court in the Bronx and entered 
innocent pleas. They could get 25 years to life in prison on the 
murder charges. 

</P>
<P>
	Your Ad on Mark McGwire's Sleeve?  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Seeking a new way to increase revenue,  
major-eague baseball is considering selling advertisements on the 
sleeves of uniforms, according to published reports. Under the 
tentative plan, teams would sell 1- to 1 1/2-inch patches of ads as a 
way to increase revenue to offset rising player salaries, according 
to the March 29 edition of Sports Business Journal. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 127.10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices retreated on Wall Street today, dousing  
an early rally in technology stocks. The Dow Jones industrial 
average fell 127.10 to 9,786.16. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 
1,661-1,422. The Nasdaq was down 18.57 to 2,461.72. 

</P>
<P>
	Georgia Hires Jim Harrick  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Jim Harrick was hired today as basketball  
coach at Georgia after guiding UCLA to a national championship in 
1995 and spending the past two seasons at Rhode Island. After 
winning the national title at UCLA, Harrick was fired for his 
involvement with a recruiting dinner involving more players than 
allowed by NCAA rules. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
