<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Expands Yugoslavia Target List  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO expanded its air campaign against  
Yugoslavia with a widened list of targets that could include top 
government buildings in central Belgrade, diplomatic sources said 
today. The sources would not say specifically that the Yugoslav 
Defense Ministry or Interior Ministry in Belgrade would be 
targeted, but one source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 
that kind of government building or headquarters is now at least a 
potential target. The alliance has been faced with a faltering 
effort to halt Yugoslavia's campaign to drive ethnic Albanians from 
Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Powell Sees Limitations in Air War  
</P>
<P>
	BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) -- Retired Gen. Colin Powell said yesterday  
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will continue to have an 
advantage during the conflict with NATO unless ground troops are 
used. ``The challenge of just using air power is that you leave it 
in the hands of your adversary to decide when he's been punished 
enough,'' Powell said. ``So the initiative will remain with 
President Milosevic.'' But Powell, who was chairman of the Joint 
Chiefs of Staff during the Gulf War, declined to give his opinion 
on when ground troops should be used against Milosevic. 

</P>
<P>
	High Court To Mull States' Rights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Supreme Court increasingly sensitive to how  
individual states' authority fares when pitted against the federal 
government's power is studying an overtime-pay dispute from Maine 
that could yield a key states-rights ruling. After hearing 
arguments today, the justices must decide by late June whether 
state governments can be sued in state courts by employees seeking 
to enforce a federal labor law. ``Surprisingly, in over two 
centuries of Supreme Court precedent, the issue has never been 
squarely presented and resolved -- until now,'' said Douglas Kmiec, 
a Pepperdine University law professor who studied the Maine case. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Industry Must Pay $81M  
</P>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- In the biggest liability verdict ever  
against the tobacco industry, a jury ordered Philip Morris to pay 
$81 million to the family of a man who died of lung cancer after 
smoking Marlboros for four decades. Although no smoking liability 
verdict has survived on appeal, Wall Street analysts had been 
watching this case closely to see if huge damage awards against Big 
Tobacco were now a trend. A San Francisco jury awarded $51.5 
million last month to a Marlboro smoker who has inoperable lung 
cancer. 

</P>
<P>
	Singapore Lawmaker Tried Over Book  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- An opposition politician pushing for greater  
freedoms in tightly controlled Singapore was convicted today of 
selling his book on dissidents without a license. Chee Soon Juan, 
36, head of the Singapore Democratic Party, paid a fine of $350 and 
charged that authorities discriminated against him. The trial that 
began yesterday was Chee's latest run-in with authorities in this 
city-state. He as been imprisoned twice in the past six weeks for 
giving political speeches without a police permit. He says 
regulations stifle Singapore's constitutional guarantees of free 
speech, association and assembly. 

</P>
<P>
	Swanson Revives TV Dinner  
</P>
<P>
	CHERRY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- When a young poultry processing  
executive proposed freezing surplus turkey and selling them as ``TV 
dinners,'' his bosses considered it a risky venture. C.A. Swanson 
and Sons initially only ordered 5,000 dinners when it introduced 
its first complete frozen meal in 1954. But the gamble paid off -- 
the company sold 10 million the first year. Recently, sales have 
declined. Last year, Americans consumed more than 160 million 
Swanson dinners, down from a peak of about 175 million in 1994. 
Now, forty-five years after transforming the industry, Swanson is 
trying to make a comeback by sprucing up its meals and spending 
millions in advertising for the first time in a decade. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Finish Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks closed lower today on profit-taking  
following recent strong gains as the Nikkei shed 22.53 points to 
close the day at 15,836.59. In New York on yesterday, the Dow 
industrials fell 93.52 to 9,913.26 as financial markets showed 
little reaction to the Federal Reserve's decision not to change 
interest rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Jordan May Be Hornet Player  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Michael Jordan is considering returning to  
the NBA as a player for the Charlotte Hornets, Fox Sports News 
reported last night. It was already known that Jordan had 
preliminary talks with the Hornets and NBA officials about 
purchasing a 50 percent share of the team. The possibility of him 
playing for the Hornets is a new twist. Fox Sports, citing 
anonymous sources close to Jordan, said one possible scenario would 
involve Jordan playing one full season for the Hornets while his 
ownership shares were held in a trust or otherwise deferred. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  

</P>
</TEXT>
