<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Friend Corroborates McDougal Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- A longtime friend of Whitewater figures James  
and Susan McDougal testified Wednesday that she heard McDougal 
pressuring his ex-wife to cooperate with Kenneth Starr's office. 
The witness also said she heard prosecutors offer Mrs. McDougal a 
deal if she helped their investigation of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Testifying in Mrs. McDougal's criminal contempt trial, Claudia  
Riley said she overheard a conversation between the McDougals at 
her house after the two were convicted of fraud in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim burst into the house and grabbed Susan by the arm and  
said, `I want to talk to you.' He appeared to be in a manic phase. 
He wanted her to cooperate with the independent counsel,'' said 
Mrs. Riley, who often nursed the late McDougal through 
manic-depression. 
</P>
<P>
	``Susan said, `Jim, I wish you well. Do what you have to do. I  
understand, but I can't do this.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim said, `You do this or I'll never speak to you again,'''  
Mrs. Riley said. ``He was very, very angry. That may have been the 
first time that Susan ever said 'No' to Jim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal and her ex-husband were business partners of  
Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the Whitewater 
real estate venture. The McDougals were convicted of fraud in 1996, 
along with then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker, in a Whitewater-related trial. 
</P>
<P>
	After the trial, McDougal cooperated with prosecutors but Mrs.  
McDougal refused to answer questions about the Clintons before a 
grand jury in September 1996 and again last April. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to her indictment on criminal contempt and obstruction  
of justice charges. Her trial is in its fourth week. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has testified at trial that she refused to answer  
the questions because she feared Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr 
would charge her with perjury if she didn't say what he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her ex-husband told her she could just say she had a  
sexual affair with Clinton because prosecutors have ``sex charges'' 
on the president that they could use to hurt him before the 1996 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Riley also testified Wednesday that she participated in a  
telephone conference call with Mrs. McDougal before her sentencing 
on the 1996 convictions and heard part of a conversation between 
McDougal attorney Bobby McDaniel and Starr prosecutor Ray Jahn. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Jahn said he would recommend probation for Mrs.  
McDougal. ``I remember the words `We could get you out of 
California and get out you of the income tax (problem),''' Mrs. 
Riley testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal testified last week that prosecutors offered to  
suggest probation instead of a jail term. She said they also 
offered to take care of embezzlement charges against her in 
California and an investigation into her federal income taxes if 
she would give them something on the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Riley testified that McDaniel asked Jahn what prosecutors  
wanted from Mrs. McDougal. ``The response was, `We know what this 
trial's about. We know who it's about and we want something from 
her,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But on questioning from Myers, Mrs. Riley said she did not hear  
Jahn say he only wanted truthful testimony from Mrs. McDougal. She 
also said she did not take notes during the call and acknowledged 
having a hearing loss in one ear. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial resumes Friday with defense testimony from Julie Hiatt  
Steele of Richmond, Va., who has accused Starr of mistreating her 
in his investigation of Clinton's relationship with former White 
House intern Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
