<HEADLINE> Prison Abortion Case Thrown Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A civil rights claim accusing a judge of  
sending a pregnant woman to prison to keep her from getting an 
abortion has been dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Yuriko Kawaguchi, 21, had sued Common Pleas Judge Patricia  
Cleary over the six-month prison term. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kawaguchi eventually decided to have the baby, explaining  
she was too far along in her pregnancy. She gave birth to a girl in 
February, and was seeking about $700,000 to pay for the child's 
upbringing. 
</P>
<P>
	Common Pleas Judge Mark Wiest threw out Ms. Kawaguchi's claim  
last week, ruling that Ms. Cleary may have exceeded her authority 
but was immune from such lawsuits as a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kawaguchi, a Japanese citizen living in Burlingame, Calif.,  
was arrested last year in a scheme to buy computer equipment with 
fake credit cards and then sell the goods. She pleaded guilty to 
forgery. 
</P>
<P>
	During Ms. Kawaguchi's sentencing in October, the judge  
questioned her at length about the pregnancy and at one point said, 
``I'm saying she is not having a second-term abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Cleary, who opposes abortion, said after the sentencing that  
it ``worked out swell'' if Ms. Kawaguchi couldn't get an abortion 
as a result of her prison term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
