<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame Will Cancel Hawaii Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Notre Dame apparently will be the next school to  
opt out of a game with the University of Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fighting Irish are scheduled to play at Aloha Stadium on  
Nov. 24, 2001, but a school spokesman said it's not worth the risk 
of playing the game given the new Bowl Championship Series rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Those rules factor strength of schedule into whether a school  
qualifies for the BCS. A team that earns a BCS bid sees a payday of 
a minimum $12.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The implications of playing that game are different than they  
used to be,'' Notre Dame spokesman John Heisler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawaii athletic director Hugh Yoshida said the Rainbows -- whose  
1991 and 1997 losses to Notre Dame were by a touchdown or less -- 
won't fight the Irish's request. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision will cost Hawaii money -- it earned an extra  
$225,000 in revenues for the last Notre Dame game. 
</P>
<P>
	But new Hawaii coach June Jones said Notre Dame is afraid to  
play the Rainbows, who he vows will be improved by the 2001 season. 
Hawaii has lost 18 straight games, dating back two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I personally think, as we get to winning, we're going to have  
a harder time scheduling,'' Jones said. ``What we're going to do 
offensively, some teams are going to look at it and say, `We don't 
want to play those guys.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia also backed out of a game against Hawaii this coming  
season and was replaced by Washington St. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
