<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 127.10  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices retreated on Wall Street today, dousing  
an early rally in technology stocks, as interest rates rose in 
response to several reports of the economy's continuing strength. 
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 127.10 to 9,786.16. The Dow 
opened higher, climbing 88.80 to 10,002.06 in the first hour of 
trading, but quickly fell back. Broader stock indicators faded in 
the final hour as technology shares trimmed early gains. The Nasdaq 
composite index fell 18.57 to 2,461.72. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Stocks Hold Up Well  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dow component IBM closed down 1 5/16 at 177 1/4  
today. In Nasdaq trading, Dell ended up 1 at 40 7/8, after trading as 
high as 42 1/4. Other Internet stocks held up well, with Amazon.com 
adding 8 15/16 to 173 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:         9786.16 - 127.10
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1396  Declines 1643  Unchgd  512
NYSE Volume:         864,872,110
Most Active NYSE issue:         Pepsi Bottling21 3/4   UNCH
S&AMP;P 500:         1286.37 - 14.38
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          710.30  -  1.33
Nasdaq Composite Index        2461.72  - 18.57
Gold(final) -    $279.80    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	GDP Grows at 6 Percent Annual Rate  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's economy grew at a  
seasonally-adjusted rate of 6 percent in the last quarter of 1998, 
the Commerce Department said today. That gave the yearly showing of 
total production of goods and services within U.S. borders a growth 
rate of 3.9 percent for the year. A price index tied to the GDP 
rose just 1 percent for the year -- the lowest since 1959, when the 
figure also was 1 percent. Despite the healthy growth and low 
inflation, however, corporate profits dropped at a 1 percent rate 
in the fourth quarter, and were down 2.2 percent for the year their 
first drop in about a decade. In another bit of economic news, the 
Commerce Department said orders for factory goods fell 2.5 percent 
in February, the steepest decline in nearly four years. Declines 
for aircraft and military goods led the way. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Verdict Put Off for While  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The judge in the Microsoft antitrust case  
outlined a new courtroom schedule today, promising to resume the 
marathon trial in mid-May. That will delay any verdict until late 
summer or early fall. The extended recess provides Microsoft and 
the government more time to try to negotiate a settlement, although 
one round of talks ended unsuccessfully late yesterday after only 
two hours. In those negotiations at the Justice Department -- 
described as cordial -- Microsoft's top legal negotiators couldn't 
reach common ground with government lawyers, a person close to the 
discussions said. 

</P>
<P>
	New Database for Futures Info  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Investors thinking of sinking their money into  
oil futures or pork bellies now have an online option to check out 
the background and disciplinary information on companies and 
salespeople in the commodity futures industry. The new Internet 
database was unveiled today. Named BASIC, it is available on the 
Web site of the National Futures Association at 
www.nfa.futures.org. The information comes from the self-regulatory 
association, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and the 
nation's 14 futures exchanges. 

</P>
<P>
	Dorfman To Work on Web Site  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Controversial financial journalist Dan Dorfman,  
whose commentary on cable network CNBC could move markets, is 
making a return -- this time on the Internet. Dorfman will be part 
of a team at stock research company JagNotes.com Inc. that will 
produce daily Wall Street coverage. Details about the column are 
still being worked out, though it is expected to begin in mid-May. 
Dorfman, who has covered business news for more than 30 years, held 
legendary sway on CNBC with his market commentary that could send 
stocks plunging or soaring. He stopped appearing on the network 
after suffering a mild stroke in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	WTO Delays Decision on Leader  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization missed its latest  
deadline today in the search for a new chief. In a meeting that 
lasted less than half an hour, the chairman of the general council 
of the world free trade body told the members there was no chance 
of reaching a consensus about either of the two candidates. Ali 
Mchumo, the Tanzanian trade ambassador, advised the countries to 
carry out some ``soul-searching'' over the Easter break and said 
they would meet again next week. Thai deputy prime minister 
Supachai Panitchpakdi and former New Zealand premier Mike Moore are 
``very, very close,'' said WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell. 

</P>
<P>
	Emergency Trunk Releases for Fords  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said it will be the first major  
car maker to install an emergency trunk release as a standard 
feature on a wide range of cars. All Ford, Lincoln and Mercury cars 
sold in the United States and Canada will include this feature, Ken 
Kohrs, a Ford vice president, said at the New York Auto Show. The 
system features a cable-operated release inside the trunk. A 
T-shaped handle will be made of phosphorescent material so it glows 
in the dark, Ford said in disclosing details of a feature already 
announced. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Upbeat for 1999  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG sought to play down  
transatlantic culture clashes in the newly merged auto giant while 
giving an upbeat outlook for 1999 at its first annual earnings news 
conference today. Sales were up 6 percent for the first two months 
of this year, with increases in all divisions. Revenues were 
expected to rise at least 4 percent over 1998's record level, the 
company said. Using Europe's new single euro currency, the company 
said revenues for 1999 were expected to climb at least 4 percent to 
$161 billion $155 billion in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Southern Co. Leases Electric Cars  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Southern Co. plans to lease at least 400  
electric cars and trucks to its employees over the next four years, 
giving the utility holding company one of the nation's largest 
fleets of electric-powered vehicles. Southern Co. Chairman A.W. 
``Bill'' Dahlberg kicked off the lease program today by loaning two 
Ford Ranger electric vehicles to the National Zoo in Washington, 
D.C. He was joined by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who said 
electric vehicles generate 35 percent less greenhouse gas emissions 
than conventional vehicles. 

</P>
<P>
	French Jobless Rate Up to 11.5 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- France's unemployment rate edged up to 11.5 percent  
in February from 11.4 percent a month earlier, the Labor Ministry 
said today. The surprise increase saw job losses rising 6 percent 
after two years of near-continuous declines. Economists said it 
underscored the fragility of growth in France. ``It's a 
psychological shock,'' said Olivier Eluere, economist at Credit 
Lyonnais. 

</P>
<P>
	Canada Cuts Key Interest Rate  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Canada's central bank lowered its key interest  
rate by a quarter percentage point today, to 5 percent, citing low 
inflation in Canada and calmer financial markets. The Bank of 
Canada's rate cut had been widely anticipated since the country's 
main inflation rate dipped below the central bank's 1 percent to 3 
percent target band in February. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Gross domestic product: grows at 6 percent annual rate  
</P>
<P>
	Today: Factory orders: down 2.5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Personal income  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Construction spending  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Unemployment  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Good Friday: Stock and most U.S. commodity markets  
closed 

</P>
