<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Player Probe Includes Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Investigators looking into possible  
cheating by University of Minnesota basketball players will be able 
to examine hundreds of documents from a woman who says she wrote 
papers for players. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Jan Gangelhoff said his firm has printed the papers  
from copies of computer disks and plans to share them with 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangelhoff had shared 225 of the files with the Saint Paul  
Pioneer Press, which first reported the accusations, and will also 
print papers from additional disks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to sit down with the investigators, and Jan, and a  
stenographer and go through all the papers,'' lawyer James Lord 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lord said Gangelhoff will show investigators those papers she  
wrote alone and those she and the players wrote together. No date 
has been set for that meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangelhoff said she did course work for 20 players from 1993 to  
1998. Her sister, Jeanne Payer, also said she did course work for 
players during the 1997-98 school year. A third tutor, Alexandra 
Goulding, said she wrote one paper for a basketball player during 
her first tutoring session, then told officials she would not do 
such work any more. 
</P>
<P>
	Academic tutors at the university are required to sign an  
employment document that outlines their responsibilities, 
confidentiality laws and NCAA and university rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The document states: ``These (NCAA) rules, for example, prohibit  
giving any item of value to student-athletes, prohibit the 
researching of or typing of student reports/papers, and prohibit 
staff from providing students with access to copy machines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, Gangelhoff declined to share the papers with  
university officials, saying that would make her an ally of the 
university. 
</P>
<P>
	``The investigators have to have them,'' Lord said. ``The papers  
are what started the avalanche of revelations about wrongdoing at 
the university. The papers are certainly not the only place the 
investigators can be looking right now, but we want to be 
cooperative.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
