<HEADLINE> Dorfman To Work on Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Controversial financial journalist Dan Dorfman,  
whose commentary on cable network CNBC could move markets, is 
making a return -- this time on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfman will be part of a team at stock research company  
JagNotes.com Inc. that will produce daily Wall Street coverage. 
Details about the column are still being worked out, though it is 
expected to begin in mid-May. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got my mind, my mouth and my sources, and I'm hungry to  
get back,'' Dorfman said in a statement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfman, who has covered business news for more than 30 years,  
held legendary sway on CNBC with his market commentary that could 
send stocks plunging or soaring. He stopped appearing on the 
network after suffering a mild stroke in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfman was also involved in one of the most notable ethics  
controversies this decade. Dorfman was fired as a Money magazine 
columnist in 1996 for refusing to reveal confidential sources to 
his editor amid reports that authorities were investigating his 
relationship with stock promoter Donald Kessler. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorfman was never charged in the matter, while Kessler  
ultimately pleaded guilty to two counts of securities fraud and one 
count of tax evasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
