<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Release Cecil Fielder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- Cecil Fielder's comeback with the Toronto  
Blue Jays didn't even make it to opening day. 
</P>
<P>
	Fielder, who agreed last month to a minor league contract with  
the Blue Jays, was released today, a day after Toronto acquired 
Dave Hollins from Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess it had to do with the Hollins trade,'' Fielder said as  
he packed his gear in the Blue Jays' clubhouse, ``I just don't 
understand the change of heart by the team. I'm a little 
disappointed, I thought everything was set, but I will be OK. Life 
goes on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fielder, 35, split last season between the Anaheim Angels and  
Cleveland Indians, hitting a combined .233 with 17 home runs and 68 
RBIs in 117 games. He batted .264 in 17 spring training games, 
going 14-for-53 with two doubles, a team-high three homers and 11 
RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto also made former Chicago White Sox manager Terry  
Bevington its third-base coach, replacing Sal Butera. Bevington had 
been manager at the Blue Jays' Triple-A team at Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Butera will decide in several days whether to take another  
position in organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
