<DOCNO> APW19990331.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 07:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stocks were mixed Wednesday, with the top  
three markets -- Tokyo, Hong Kong and Singapore -- closing with 
little change. 
</P>
<P>
	The day's biggest movement was in Bangkok, where share prices  
plunged after the Thai government announced a U.S. $3.5 billion 
economic package that met expectations but didn't have any 
surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	The SET index lost 7.75 points, or 2.2 percent, to 352.01.  
</P>
<P>
	The new stimulus measures include various tax cuts, but analysts  
said most of them, such as the reductions in corporate income tax 
and personal income tax, were too small to significantly boost 
consumer spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the blue chips fell after a volatile session on the  
last day of the country's fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 22.53 points, or 0.14  
percent, to close at 15,836.59. On Tuesday, the index lost 149.72 
points, or 0.94 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei average lost as much as 207 points early in the  
session but bounced back later as U.S. pension funds bought shares 
to dress up their performance at the end of the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, share prices ended largely unchanged, as investors  
found no news to motivate them in a bumpy session. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index edged up just 1.99 points, or 0.02  
percent, to close at 10,942.20. The Hang Seng had rallied 2.4 
percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Wong, research manager at OSK Asia Securities Ltd., said  
most investors remain hopeful that some positive news will boost 
the market soon, such as an April government land auction, a 
possible interest rate cut and China's possible entry into the 
World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets were closed in Indonesia for year-end  
clearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed nearly unchanged in sluggish trading in  
a holiday-shortened week. The Straits Times Index rose just 0.23 
point, or 0.02 percent, to 1,518.31. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares rose on anticipation that the  
central bank would unveil plans to cut interest rates when it 
released its annual economic report after the market's close. The 
investors were left disappointed. The Composite Index rose 0.9 
percent, or 4.25 points, to end at 502.82. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Some last-minute bargain-hunting in key blue-chip issues  
lifted Philippine stocks in late trading. The PSE index rose 16.19 
points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,028.21. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares rose on expectations of an inflow of  
funds into the stock market amid low local interest rates. The 
Kospi index edged up 0.93 points, or 0.15 percent, to 618.98. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares fell on the back of Wall Street's  
overnight drop. The All Ordinaries Index fell closed down 28.1 
points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,967.2. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed lower, led by losses in the  
technology sector. The Weighted Price Index lost 16.94 points, or 
0.24 percent, closing at 6,881.72. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares rose for a second day, led by  
market heavyweight Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. The benchmark 
NZSE-40 capital index rose 17.12 points, or 0.8 percent, to 
2,143.18. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Entrepreneurs Go to Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- At his first day of business boot  
camp, graduate student George Shillenger broke a light sweat, took 
a deep breath and described his plans for launching a high-tech 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're building a community of science on the Internet,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	What about making money?  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh yes,'' he said, relaxing a bit. ``We're planning to make a  
lot of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpening up business plans is what this training ground for  
entrepeneurs is all about. Shillenger, who hopes to fire up his Web 
site TheScience.com this summer, was among more than 600 aspiring 
entrepreneurs this week learning some tough business lessons about 
making it in the light-speed world of high technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The attendees hope to receive some of the more than $16 billion  
in venture capital expected to be invested in startup companies 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of Silicon Valley pros is staging the two-day boot camp,  
dispensing their wisdom about how to snag investment capital, 
protect inventions from bootleggers and ``create a buzz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't worry, be crappy,'' advised Guy Kawasaki, a former Apple  
Computer evangelist who now helps startups. ``Revolutionaries ship 
their product first and then they test it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Costello, who has successfully launched several major  
Silicon Valley companies including Cadence, said his most important 
advice is to focus on the positive goal, and avoid fixating on the 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm flying along and there's the power pole, and I'm  
thinking, 'Don't hit that power pole. Don't hit that power pole,' 
then the next thing you know, Whap! I'm going to hit it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other advice: ``Twenty-page business plans are obsolete. Don't  
bother. Give the investor a two-page summary and a ten slide 
PowerPoint presentation,'' said Steven Bengston, who sorts through 
hundreds of proposals each year at PricewaterhouseCoopers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Eric Witte of Harrisburg, Penn., said he came to ``make the  
transition from pipe-dreaming to pioneering. ... I have a fire in 
my belly and I'm getting old. I have a sense of urgency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of his ideas is to provide Internet users an incentive --  
frequent flyer miles, bonus shopping points, even cash -- to pay 
their bills online. ``At this point the online bill providers have 
the audacity to charge the customers. That's the wrong way to do 
it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While he spoke, the owner of a small online bill provider  
company approached, gave him his card and suggested they consider 
working together. 
</P>
<P>
	Shillenger, who met his three partners at a Yale class called  
``How To Start A High Tech Company,'' said they have already 
received close to $500,000 in investments. They hope to bring in 
much more this summer when they seek a round of venture capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're willing to forgo the big corporate salaries because  
there's something really exciting about entrepreneurship,'' said 
Shillinger. ``We just want to jump right on to that Internet 
wave.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
