<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cell Phone Use Up Dramatically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of mobile telephone users in the  
United States rose 25 percent last year to 69.2 million people, 
according to the industry's most recent figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase -- the industry's largest one-year gain -- was driven  
by fierce competition that continues to drive down monthly charges, 
said Thomas Wheeler, president of the Cellular Telecommunications 
Industry Association, which compiled the figures. 
</P>
<P>
	In many markets, people have a choice of six different mobile  
phone providers, Wheeler said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 69.2 million customers, nearly 28 percent subscribed to  
the newer digital mobile phone service, which offers improved sound 
quality and more features. The rest of the customers subscribed to 
regular analog service. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of mobile phone customers surpassed the number of  
cable TV customers in the United States -- now at 67 million -- 
Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not your father's car phone anymore,'' Wheeler said.  
``The wireless phone has changed in the way in which people use it. 
It is now a take-me-anywhere, use me to call anywhere, treat me as 
a local call kind of service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, 55.3 million people used mobile phones in the United  
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting the increased competition, customers' average monthly  
bill decreased by 7.8 percent last year to $39.43 compared to 
$42.78 in 1997, according to the industry figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry revenues, meanwhile, rose 20 percent last year to $36.6  
billion, compared with $30.5 billion in 1997. That reflects 
customer growth and an increase in the amount of time people talk 
on their mobile phones, Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	The revenues include ``roaming'' fees that customers pay when  
using their phones outside core service areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Pushes Web Privacy Disclosures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With $60 million earmarked for Internet ads, IBM  
will be twisting some arms to make Web sites more forthright about 
how they take notes on their visitors and what they do with that 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, $60 million amounts to a tiny fraction of the $2  
billion spent on Internet ads in 1998 and the $4 billion that some 
see being spent on Internet ads in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	And even as the second-biggest advertiser on the Internet, IBM's  
reach is limited, with its ads appearing on just 780 sites in a 
World Wide Web of millions. 
</P>
<P>
	As a first step, most consumer advocates were encouraged by  
Wednesday's news that IBM plans to pull its ads from any Web site 
that doesn't state its policy on collecting and using information 
on Web users' interests, finances and spending habits. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the fierce debate over Internet privacy protection -- and  
whether the industry or the government should regulate it -- there 
was plenty of doubt about the impact and scope of IBM's new policy. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, IBM won't be evaluating the substance of those  
policy statements, and that may not provide much more protection 
for consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too easy to write a really bad privacy policy that  
contains a lot of apple-pie public relations statements,'' said 
Jason Catlett, the head of Junkbusters, a privacy group based in 
Green Brook, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	And unless Microsoft, the most prolific Web advertiser, follows  
suit, the initiative may not go very far. The software maker was 
silent on the topic Wednesday, declining to comment on IBM's move 
or its plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a constructive thing for IBM to have done, but it will  
only make a difference if IBM is the first of many who do same 
thing,'' said Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he expects a recent FTC survey to show that the number  
of sites with privacy statements has risen from 14 percent a year 
ago, Pitofsky added that ``It's not just a matter of percentages. 
You want to know the quality of the notice'' and whether people are 
given a clear opportunity to give permission for their information 
to be used. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's move was designed ``to help build consumer confidence in  
the use of the Internet as a medium for conducting business,'' said 
spokesman John Bukovinsky, noting that only 30 percent of the sites 
where the company now advertises post their privacy policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The action by IBM comes two weeks after the Better Business  
Bureau announced a program to bestow a seal of approval on Web 
sites with full disclosure. Trust-E, an industry-funded privacy 
organization, already offers a similar seal of approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem, say some observers, is that cryptic privacy  
statements and seals of approval may quickly become as commonplace 
-- and ignored -- as the fine print on contracts or those rambling 
notices from credit card companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real boiler plate stuff really. You wonder how many  
people, once these policy disclosures are posted everywhere, will 
read them,'' said Cathy Taylor, editor Adweek's IQ publication 
covering online media. 
</P>
<P>
	The government, however, isn't looking to baby-sit consumers or  
make them pay better attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't replace action and the judgment of consumers,'' said  
the FTC's Pitofsky. ``It's generally accepted by a wide range of 
people concerned about these issues that if you give consumers 
notice and the opportunity to consent or not consent, that's 
adequate. Whether they exercise their right and withdraw consent, 
that's up to consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many consumer advocates are looking for the government to  
step in, insisting the industry will never offer the level of 
protection provided in other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``European nations are more sensitive to this than we are,''  
said Roland Rust, a professor of marketing at Vanderbilt University 
in Nashville, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	In some countries, ``companies can't send customer information  
across national boundaries. The United Sates is lagging in that 
area,'' he said. ``The average consumer on the street is just 
beginning to understand the degree to which companies accumulate 
information about them.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 10:40:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Begins Settlement Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp.'s top legal negotiators met  
with government lawyers for two hours behind closed doors but 
couldn't reach common ground in the first settlement talks since 
the Justice Department filed its landmark antitrust case last 
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no plans to meet again today, although neither side  
ruled out future talks, said a source close to the discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	The negotiations, described as cordial, were held Tuesday  
evening at the Justice Department, according to the person, who 
spoke only on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	During a status hearing on the trial today, U.S. District Judge  
Thomas Penfield Jackson said he wants to resume the trial May 10 
for both sides' rebuttal cases. The trial was originally scheduled 
to resume in April after a six-week recess, but Jackson is occupied 
with a criminal case taking longer than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	If he's not done with the other case by May 10, Jackson said, he  
wants to resume Microsoft the first Monday after the criminal case 
goes to the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	On the courthouse steps after the hearing, the government's lead  
attorney, David Boies, said both sides had agreed not to discuss 
any settlement talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there are going to be productive settlement discussions,  
they must not take place publicly,'' Boies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts agree an out-of-court settlement in the interim is  
unlikely because the sides remain far apart on central issues after 
nearly five months of a bitter courtroom fight. Wisconsin's 
attorney general, James Doyle, said before the talks that he didn't 
expect them to be successful. 
</P>
<P>
	But the seriousness assigned to Tuesday's negotiations was  
evident in the roster of lawyers who participated. 
</P>
<P>
	The government was represented by Boies, its top litigator in  
the case; Assistant Attorney General Joel I. Klein, head of the 
Justice Department's antitrust division; attorneys general from 
Iowa and Connecticut; and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft dispatched William Neukom, its top in-house lawyer and  
former senior partner in the law firm of Bill Gates' father; 
Richard Urowsky, the architect of a controversial 1995 Microsoft 
settlement with the government; and legal consultant Charles Rule, 
who headed the Justice Department's antitrust division during the 
Reagan administration. 
</P>
<P>
	For Microsoft, a courtroom loss years ago in another important  
legal fight remains a clear reminder of the perils of taking an 
unyielding position at the bargaining table. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, Microsoft chose to stand defiant and risk a  
verdict in a lawsuit that bears striking parallels to its current 
courtroom troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	Accused of illegally bundling a competitor's technology into its  
dominant computer operating system, Microsoft lost that case in 
1994 and was ordered by jurors to pay $120 million in damages to a 
small industry rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're very tough and aggressive in everything they do,''  
said Morgan Chu, the lawyer who represented Stac Electronics Corp. 
in failed settlement talks with Microsoft in 1993 but beat the 
software maker in court a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's true in the way they market products, the way they  
conduct business negotiations -- and it's true in the way they 
conduct litigation,'' Chu remembered. 
</P>
<P>
	In its lawsuit, Stac had accused Microsoft of patent  
infringement for including its ``Stacker'' data-compression 
technology in its MS-DOS operating system, the precursor to 
Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The government in the current antitrust trial alleges that  
Microsoft bundled Internet software with Windows to try to crush 
rival Netscape Communications Corp. It also holds that Microsoft 
introduced a ``polluted'' version of a new technology by Sun 
Microsystems Inc. to stem its widespread use. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike in Microsoft's current case, Gates testified personally  
in 1993. But Stac lawyers used Gates' own e-mail to try to 
discredit him, much as the government has done over past weeks in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lost the Stac case for $120 million and was ordered to  
recall versions of its software with the technology. It later 
settled with Stac for $83 million by promising not to appeal. The 
same jury also awarded Microsoft $13.6 million in a counterclaim. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 10:35:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Delays Decision on Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The World Trade Organization missed its latest  
deadline today in the search for a new chief. 
</P>
<P>
	In a meeting that lasted less than half an hour, the chairman of  
the general council of the world free trade body told the members 
there was no chance of reaching a consensus about either of the two 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali Mchumo, the Tanzanian trade ambassador, advised the  
countries to carry out some ``soul-searching'' over the Easter 
break and said they would meet again next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai deputy prime minister Supachai Panitchpakdi and former New  
Zealand premier Mike Moore are ``very, very close,'' said WTO 
spokesman Keith Rockwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Mchumo told the delegates certain countries have said they will  
not throw their support behind one candidate or the other, making 
it impossible to build a consensus. The WTO always works by 
consensus and has never held a vote in its four-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization has been deadlocked on a replacement for Renato  
Ruggiero since late last year when it first missed a December to 
make the appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	The position is seen as a key one as the WTO faces the  
challenges of global economic turmoil and also tries to mediate in 
the damaging banana trade war between the United States and the 
European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though one candidate, Moroccan trade ambassador Hassan  
Abouyoub, has dropped out of the race, the organization has been 
unable to decide on a single choice. A third candidate, former 
Canadian trade minister Roy Maclaren, has insisted he will not drop 
out even though he enjoys little support. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruggiero has said he intends to leave at the end of April, and  
that he will not stay on under any circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	The members now hope to make an official appointment at the  
WTO's scheduled general council meeting on April 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
