<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Loses Tax Status for Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal court decision stripping a church of  
its tax-exempt status for running anti-Clinton ads may diminish 
political activity from the pulpit, activists on both sides of the 
issue said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman's decision backed the Internal  
Revenue Service, which had revoked the tax-exempt status of the 
Church at Pierce Creek near Binghamton, N.Y., for running newspaper 
advertisements against Bill Clinton in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time a church had lost its tax exemption for  
partisan political actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads, which ran in USA Today and The Washington Times, warned  
``Christian Beware'' and stated: ``Bill Clinton is promoting 
policies that are in rebellion to God's laws.'' The ad sought 
donations to help pay for the ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of political activism by churches seized on the decision  
as providing more ammunition to challenge the tax-exempt status of 
religious institutions engaged in partisanship. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pastor who ran the ad warned of a chilling effect on the  
church's role to speak out on moral issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``If every time the church decides to say something about morals  
in the public arena, they have to stop and look over their shoulder 
to see what the IRS is going to say, they're no longer in control 
of their own words,'' said the Rev. Daniel Little, now pastor of 
Landmark Church in Binghamton. 
</P>
<P>
	Added Mark Troobnick, a lawyer with the American Center for Law  
and Justice, a conservative legal organization that represented the 
church in court: ``There will be a hesitancy for churches to speak 
out concerning the moral stance of politicians in particular and 
campaigns generally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Tate, executive director of the Christian Coalition, said  
he did not expect any resistance to distribute the group's voter 
guides in the next election. 
</P>
<P>
	Tate noted that none of the churches that have given out the  
guides in the past had lost tax-exempt status. He also said the 
coalition planned to distribute a record 70 million guides next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall outcome of this case is an exception to the rule.  
It will not be a deterrent to active churches,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive director of Americans United for Separation of  
Church and State, which has challenged the Christian Coalition's 
voter guides, disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This decision is so clear that it is the death knell for  
church politicking in election campaigns,'' Barry Lynn said. ``Now 
people on the Religious Right and elsewhere no longer can claim 
that they're in court and about to win a case. They were in court 
and they have lost big time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The church, which had sued to overturn the IRS decision, plans  
to appeal Tuesday's ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0075 </DOCNO>
