<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Widow Remote Control Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CERRITOS, Calif. (AP) -- The manufacturer and distributor of a  
remote-control car starter recalled the product after reports it 
caused doors to randomly lock and engines to run after the driver 
has left the vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerritos-based distributor David Levy Co. said the problems were  
relegated to less than 1 percent of the thousands of units sold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the problems we've discovered are due to battery  
voltage in cold weather,'' said company president David Levy. ``The 
weather causes a voltage drain and the main processor on the 
circuit board reacts to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Levy said customers have several options.  
</P>
<P>
	``They can return it to the place where they bought it for a  
refund or a new main processor that we've supplied,'' he said. 
``Most consumers who have had problems already have returned the 
units, but a majority haven't had problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to manufacturer Precision Engineering Industries Inc., in  
North Hollywood was answered by a recording that said the offices 
were closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Best Buy, the nation's largest consumer electronics and  
appliance store, announced Wednesday it would stop selling and 
installing the Black Widow RAS-200 remote control car starter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
