<HEADLINE> Driver in Van Crash Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- The driver accused of vehicular homicide  
in a van crash that killed seven young magazine sales people cried 
as the charges were read in court Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeremy Holmes, 20, stood mute when asked for a plea. The court  
entered innocent pleas on his behalf before holding him on $47,500 
bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Holmes, of Clinton, Iowa, was driving a van with 13  
other young people selling magazine subscriptions door-to-door when 
it overturned on Interstate 90, spilling bodies onto the highway. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven people died and five were seriously injured. Two remained  
in critical condition Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened as Holmes tried to switch seats with a  
passenger when he saw a police officer preparing to pull him over 
for speeding, authorities said. His driving license was not valid 
in Wisconsin because of a string of traffic tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The occupants of the van, who ranged in age from 15 to 25, had  
been selling magazines for YES, an affiliate of Subscriptions Plus 
of Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin labor officials have cited Subscriptions Plus for a  
child labor violation involving a 15-year-old Madison girl injured 
in the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma Labor officials have also cited the company for  
allegedly not having workers' compensation coverage for 123 
administrative employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Subscriptions Plus has denied wrongdoing in both cases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
