<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:42:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cell Phone Use Up Dramatically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of mobile telephone users in the  
United States rose 25 percent last year to 69.2 million people, 
according to the industry's most recent figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase -- the industry's largest one-year gain -- was driven  
by fierce competition that continues to drive down monthly charges, 
said Thomas Wheeler, president of the Cellular Telecommunications 
Industry Association, which compiled the figures. 
</P>
<P>
	In many markets, people have a choice of six different mobile  
phone providers, Wheeler said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 69.2 million customers, nearly 28 percent subscribed to  
the newer digital mobile phone service, which offers improved sound 
quality and more features. The rest of the customers subscribed to 
regular analog service. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of mobile phone customers surpassed the number of  
cable TV customers in the United States -- now at 67 million -- 
Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not your father's car phone anymore,'' Wheeler said.  
``The wireless phone has changed in the way in which people use it. 
It is now a take-me-anywhere, use me to call anywhere, treat me as 
a local call kind of service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, 55.3 million people used mobile phones in the United  
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting the increased competition, customers' average monthly  
bill decreased by 7.8 percent last year to $39.43 compared to 
$42.78 in 1997, according to the industry figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry revenues, meanwhile, rose 20 percent last year to $36.6  
billion, compared with $30.5 billion in 1997. That reflects 
customer growth and an increase in the amount of time people talk 
on their mobile phones, Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	The revenues include ``roaming'' fees that customers pay when  
using their phones outside core service areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:43:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Thursday morning on  
selling by overseas funds as Japanese stocks rebounded on continued 
buying from foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.84 yen at midday, down 1.14 yen from late  
Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its level of 118.97 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average gained 265.48 points, or 1.68 percent,  
to close the morning session at 16,102.07. On Wednesday, the 
average lost 22.53 points, or 0.14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved lower against the yen in  
thin trading on selling by overseas funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the euro was traded at 128.00 yen, down from 128.59  
yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices advanced amid expectations for  
active buying by both foreign and domestic institutional investors 
in the new Japanese fiscal year, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Continued buying from foreign investors is supporting the  
market,'' said Harushige Kobayashi of Meiko National Securities Co. 
``But the market may remain range-bound around current levels 
before testing the further upside in the middle of April.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said investors also welcome recent news of drastic  
corporate restructuring by major manufactures. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Mitsubishi Electric soared after the company announced  
plans Wednesday to cut 10 percent of its global work force in an 
effort to erase growing losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 24.12 points, or 1.90 percent, to 1,291.34. 
The TOPIX had fallen 2.02 points, or 0.16 percent, the previous 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,786.16  
points Wednesday, down 127.10 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.730  
percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.760 percent, driving its price 
up to 100.60 yen from 100.34 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
