<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss WWII Task Force Disbanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- The Swiss government announced  
Wednesday it was disbanding a special crisis task force looking 
into the country's role in World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``The controversy has been settled,'' a government statement  
said, adding the task force would be broken up immediately. The 
group was set up in October 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	It was designed to give the official government response and  
coordinate action over claims that neutral Switzerland acted as the 
banker for the Nazis and that millions of dollars deposited in 
Swiss bank accounts by Jewish holocaust victims were never 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Switzerland's two largest banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, agreed  
to pay out $1.25 billion in settlement of the claims from Jewish 
groups for money left in accounts at the end of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``The settlement between the Swiss banks and the World Jewish  
Congress together with the class-action plaintiffs has finalized 
all financial claims on Switzerland,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's Foreign Affairs Department said any work left  
over from the task force would be handled within the department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
