<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WORK LIKE YOUR DOG: Man's best friend has a better time than the  
typical American worker, according to author Matt Weinstein. His 
book about having more fun at work is called ``Work Like Your 
Dog.'' Weinstein says dogs approach their work -- being our pets -- 
with dedication, loyalty and sensitivity, as well as joy, 
enthusiasm and a willingness to see work as play. So, he says, take 
a cue from the family pooch and bring a playful attitude to the 
job; it will go a long way toward making work more interesting and 
rewarding. Weinstein has some advice for managers: Do not repress 
the natural urge to play. Encourage your staff to take breaks 
during the day to have a little fun. Order in pizza once a week. 

</P>
<P>
	DON'T GET YOUR BOSS TEED OFF: If your boss invites you to play a  
round of golf, it's possible to have a good time and help your 
career, according to Men's Health magazine. Some suggestions: Don't 
worry about beating the boss -- he or she will respect you for 
giving your best effort. Don't talk about work unless the topic is 
brought up. Don't hand out advice on how the boss can improve a 
swing. And be sure to dress right -- assume that the golf club 
expects players to wear slacks, and bring a sport jacket in case 
one is required to enter the club lounge. 

</P>
<P>
	WARNING SIGNS: Are your days at your current job numbered? Are  
you about to become a downsizing casualty? Andrew DuBrin, a 
management professor at Rochester Institute of Technology, says 
employers often give off signals that can tell a staffer that he or 
she is losing favor at work or is on the way out -- for example, if 
employees suddenly find themselves out of the loop when it comes to 
meetings and important memos or e-mail. Another sign is when plum 
assignments are suddenly being given to other people. If your memos 
and phone calls to important managers are not being returned, 
that's also an indication. And a noncommittal or icy response when 
you do get through on the phone is a tip-off, too. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
