<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hal's Pal Wins Berkeley Handicap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, Calif. (AP) -- Hal's Pal returned with a flourish from a  
six-month layoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-year-old, showing no signs of the foot problems that  
sidelined him, outdueled Wild Wonder in the stretch for a 
half-length victory in Wednesday's 48th running of the Berkeley 
Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first race since last October for Hal's Pal, who  
earned a $75,000 first prize to boost career earnings to $526,428. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always had problems with his feet so we took him out of  
training for a while,'' trainer Ben Cecil said. ``It gave him a 
chance to put his feet down and put on some weight. And he seems to 
have thrived since then. I knew this horse was a lot better than 
people have given him credit for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cecil said Hal's Pal, racking up his seventh win in 27 career  
starts, actually cracked a front hoof again two days before he was 
scheduled to be shipped to northern California from Hollywood Park 
near Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran today in a three-quarters shoe. It was a little bit of  
a worry but my blacksmith got it straightened out and he was 
fine,'' Cecil said. 
</P>
<P>
	The race set up nicely for Hal's Pal's closing style with Wild  
Wonder and odds-on favorite Mud Route fighting for the lead for 
much of the race. Hal's Pal charged up to challenge turning for 
home and wore down Wild Wonder, who lost for the first time in five 
starts at Golden Gate. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner, with jockey Brice Blanc, covered the mile in 1:34.96  
and returned $14.20, $5.20 and $3.60. Wild Wonder paid $4.20 and 
$3.20 and Worldly Ways returned 5.60 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavily favored Mud Route faded to last in the seven-horse field  
after forcing the pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
