<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Kasich Hunts for Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The name of John Kasich, the powerful member  
of Congress who wants to be president, doesn't ring many bells in a 
town where cinematographers and movie producers have broader 
recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is that?'' wondered Mike Garner as Kasich and an entourage  
left a restaurant during the Republican's swing through California 
this week in search of money and votes. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll released last week showed just 4 percent of California  
Republicans favored Kasich over his GOP rivals. But the Ohioan 
believes he can connect with California, which is holding its 
primary earlier than ever next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Californians like the underdog, they like `against the grain.'  
I'm clearly both,'' he said in an interview Tuesday over a 
breakfast of eggs and bacon. He left the fresh fruit untouched. 
</P>
<P>
	There is plenty about the telegenic congressman that could  
appeal to Californians. He is young, 46, self-confident and 
straightforward. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, chairman of the House Budget Committee, preaches the  
need to reinforce families, religion and volunteerism. Most of all, 
he rails against the ``the elites'' and says the government should 
``keep its mitts off'' citizens and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich has spent most of his adult life in government work, but  
insists he's no Beltway insider, reminding listeners that he is the 
son of a mail carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am of the people,'' he says. ``My dad couldn't get me on the  
Little League team, let alone in the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a visit to telecommunications giant Nortel Networks in  
the Silicon Valley, Kasich derided Vice President Al Gore for 
claiming to have helped create the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kasich, who compares his work in Congress to ``bending  
steel,'' is himself given to speaking in superlatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the biggest supporter of tax cuts in the Republican Party  
-- I mean, of anybody who's ever served in public office,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also claimed he was the first to use the Web to announce his  
bid for the GOP nomination. Lamar Alexander made such a declaration 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Like other candidates who have crossed the country seeking  
support and dollars this year, Kasich soon must file fund-raising 
reports with federal officials for the first quarter, which ends 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He likens his campaign to climbing Mount Everest, and he knows  
that reaching the White House won't be possible without the 
financial oxygen -- ``the Os,'' in his own parlance -- supplied by 
Los Angeles, Silicon Valley and San Francisco entrepreneurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people don't give me the Os, I'll die on the mountain,'' he  
said, adding that he's not above begging for the help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
