<DOCNO> APW19990331.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 12:15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Aid Approved for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Agency for International Development  
sent a disaster relief team to Albania today to assess the growing 
humanitarian crisis stemming from the Serb crackdown in Kosovo and 
the NATO airstrikes against the Serbs. President Clinton also 
authorized $50 million ``to address the urgent humanitarian needs 
of refugees who fled Kosovo,'' Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said. 
He said the money would be drawn from an emergency contingency fund 
and the Department of Defense. Half will be sent to the U.N. High 
Commission on Refugees and half will pay for food and shelter. 

</P>
<P>
	Refugees Complain About Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Refugees arriving today in northern  
Albania complained that NATO airstrikes in southern Kosovo have 
been ineffective as Western officials expressed new resolve to try 
to cripple the Yugoslav military. Refugees said bombs were hitting 
military buildings abandoned by the Yugoslav army and soldiers now 
were staying in homes left behind by fleeing ethnic Albanians. U.S. 
Gen. Wesley Clark has called for more firepower to accelerate the 
mission, but he has warned airstrikes would not be enough to stop 
attacks against civilians reportedly spearheaded by Serb militia 
units. 

</P>
<P>
	Jurors To Sentence Marine Navigator  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- An Air Force psychologist testified  
today that Marine Capt. Joseph Schweitzer was ``immediately 
tearful'' when he learned 20 people had died as a result of a 
flight on which he served as navigator. The psychologist said 
Schweitzer was the ``most distressed'' of the four crew members on 
the EA-6B Prowler that hit a ski lift cable in the Italian Alps on 
Feb. 3, 1998, and sent a gondola plunging to the ground. Schweitzer 
pleaded guilty to two charges in connection with the destruction of 
a videotape of the flight. A jury is considering his sentence. He 
could face up to five years in prison for each charge. 

</P>
<P>
	Audit: Federal Bookkeeping Woeful  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government still does a woeful job  
of keeping its financial books, but they are better than they were 
in fiscal 1997, according to an audit released today. Comptroller 
General David Walker, who heads the General Accounting Office, told 
the panel that 24 federal agencies don't properly account for ``a 
majority'' of their $466 billion in assets. The audit revealed 
numerous other problems, including inadequate data on loans and 
liabilities such as veterans' benefits, poor computer security, and 
even lack of documentation to support the costs of many day-to-day 
government operations. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: DNA Conducts Electricity  
</P>
<P>
	BASEL, Switzerland (AP) -- Strands of DNA might someday be used  
as wires in computer chips and transistors, a study suggests. 
Hans-Werner Fink and Christian Schoenenberger of the University of 
Basel in Switzerland found that DNA conducts electricity as well as 
a good semiconductor. A semiconductor carries electricity better 
than an insulator but not as well as a conductor like copper. If 
DNA strands could be made with a switch to turn the current flowing 
through them on and off, they could be used to build extremely tiny 
electrical devices, the researchers said. 

</P>
<P>
	Activists Score Some Vs. McDonald's  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A pair of vegetarian activists won a partial  
victory today in their struggle to overturn a ruling that they 
libeled McDonald's Corp. by accusing it of selling food that can 
cause heart disease. Three Court of Appeal judges ruled that Dave 
Morris and Helen Steel were justified in claiming that regular 
customers face a heightened risk of heart trouble. The judges also 
said it was fair to say McDonald's subjected its employees to poor 
conditions and paid them badly. The judges reduced the amount of 
damages the two must pay to $61,300 from $92,700. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 33.30  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as reports about the  
economy's continuing strength revived interest rate concerns. Just 
before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 33.30 
at 9,879.96. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led 
decliners 1,485-1,408. The Nasdaq was down 1.35 to 2,478.94. 

</P>
<P>
	Agent Says Jordan Will Not Play  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Michael Jordan's agent said today there  
is ``absolutely no truth'' to a report he is considering coming out 
of retirement to play for the Charlotte Hornets. Jordan has had 
preliminary discussions with NBA commissioner David Stern and 
Hornets owner George Shinn about buying 50 percent of the team. Fox 
Sports reported last night that Jordan was considering playing a 
full season for the Hornets while his ownership shares were held in 
a trust or deferred. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  

</P>
