<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coles Removed As Torch Relay Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian IOC member Phil Coles was  
removed from his role as the Sydney 2000 Olympics torch relay chief 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles did not attend the SOCOG board meeting in which Anna Booth  
was selected to replace him as chair of the torch relay committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to be moving forward and we need a chairperson that's  
available,'' said SOCOG president Michael Knight. ``It's pretty 
clear that Phil's circumstances have not been the best of late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles is under investigation by the IOC for accepting excessive  
hospitality from the Salt Lake bidders that won the 2002 Winter 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	He is also being investigated following his ex-wife's claims  
that he took jewelry from a Greek businessman associated with 
Athens' failed bid for the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has denied the jewelry allegations and has not made any  
public statements since returning to Australia last week following 
the IOC's extraordinary session in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG board members and the president of John Hancock insurance  
company, a major Olympic sponsor, have urged Coles to resign but 
the 67-year-old said he won't quit his post. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight led the decision to remove Coles as the torch relay chief  
and said he was concerned about poor publicity concerning Coles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made it clear to Phil that I thought it was in his best  
interests not to continue on the board and he made it clear to me 
that he intended to continue,'' Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Olympic Committee president John Coates said he and  
Coles' fellow IOC member Kevan Gosper abstained from Thursday's 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm unhappy for Phil, I just didn't involve myself today''  
Coates said. ``It involved someone I've worked with for a long time 
and in Kevan's case, as he said, it involved an Olympic 
colleague.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight also said Coles informed him Sunday that he wanted to  
return to SOCOG if cleared by the IOC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
