<HEADLINE> Klan Not Allowed To Adopt Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Anne Arundel County has scrapped its  
adopt-a-road program rather than let the Ku Klux Klan participate 
and have its signs posted along a mile of roadway. 
</P>
<P>
	County Executive Janet Owens said she did not want highways to  
become forums for political statements, especially by organizations 
``that have a history of racism and violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Klan was more interested in attention than picking up trash  
in the county east of Washington, D.C., she said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Klan approached the county last summer about joining 26  
community and civic groups that periodically clean litter from 
roads. The county posts two signs identifying the organization that 
keeps the stretch of road clean. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Owens said she had only two choices -- kill the program or  
refuse to let the Klan participate and undertake an expensive court 
battle to defend the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Kelly, head of a Klan organization that he said has  
members in 11 states, called the decision ``childish and 
immature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly denied that his group advocates hatred and violence and  
said Ms. Owens ``doesn't know my group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we agreed to dropping the KKK on the signs and just  
put the Knights of the Invisible Empire,'' Kelly said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
