<HEADLINE> Fireworks Firm Closes After Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSSEO, Mich. (AP) -- The founder of the fireworks company where  
five people were killed in an explosion this week says he is 
closing the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Although government officials said Tuesday they had no reason to  
shut down Independence Professional Fireworks Co., William 
Richardson told investigators that fireworks manufacturing would 
cease at the plant, the Detroit Free Press reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's explosion followed a December blast in which seven  
people died at the site about 80 miles southwest of Detroit. Among 
the victims of the latest blast was Robert Slayton, the company's 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told us he'd lost his best friend,'' Detective Sgt. Ken  
Hersha of the state police told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	A charred wall was all that remained of a small building that  
exploded Monday just 100 yards from the rubble of the Dec. 11 
blast. Several cars near the site also were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not know what the cause was,'' said Sonny Wilson of the  
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. ``There are a lot 
of questions. What we're trying to do is make the scene safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation into the December blast is also continuing.  
</P>
<P>
	Independence is among the country's largest makers of display  
fireworks shells. 
</P>
