<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Upbeat for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG today reported its  
sales rose 6 percent in the first two months of this year and 
predicted revenue and operating profit for all of 1999 would rise 
at least 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In releasing the projections, executives also sought to play  
down trans-Atlantic culture clashes in the company formed by last 
year's takeover of Chrysler Corp. by Germany's Daimler-Benz AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Technical aspects of last year's merger, such as coordinating  
global sales and purchasing, were on track, they said, and savings 
were already being realized. DaimlerChrysler said its previously 
announced target of $1.4 billion of merger-related savings would be 
achieved this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were up 6 percent for the first two months of this year,  
with increases in all divisions, the company said at a news 
conference at Stuttgart, where it is based. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue is expected to rise at least 4 percent over 1998's  
record level, and co-chairman Juergen Schrempp said growth in 
operating profit ``will definitely match sales growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Due to economic stability on both sides of the Atlantic ... we  
are confident of continued success in 1999, despite some tough 
challenges around the rest of the world,'' said co-chairman Robert 
J. Eaton, who headed Chrysler before the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Using Europe's new single currency, the company said revenue for  
1999 is expected to climb to 137 billion euros, or about $147 
billion at current exchange rates, from 131.8 billion euros in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It also said almost half of 1998's record $10.2 billion  
operating profit came from the Chrysler passenger car and truck 
division, which includes Plymouth, Jeep and Dodge. Chrysler's 
contribution was $4.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But while business operations are merging at a ``great pace,''  
Schrempp said, ``the human integration, that's a process that's 
going to take longer ... because we have to take into consideration 
human feelings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those difficulties were partly responsible for DaimlerChrysler's  
decision this month not to buy into ailing Nissan Motor Co. of 
Japan, said both Schrempp and Eaton. Last weekend, France's Renault 
bought a 37 percent stake in Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to focus on making sure our merger is successful,''  
Eaton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Joint projects already are under way in areas like sales and  
marketing and combined financial service. The U.S.-built Mercedes 
M-Class off-road vehicle begins European production in May at 
Chrysler's Jeep plant in Graz, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	But there also have been defections of Chrysler executives to  
General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co., with some reports 
suggesting the Americans felt Germans were being favored for top 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a later teleconfernce with U.S. reporters, Schrempp bristled  
at repeated questions about the American defections. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we would need somebody from Ford or General Motors we would  
buy it as well, but we don't need that,'' Schrempp said. ``We also 
don't need their know-how. You can quote me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The co-chairmen described the departures as normal.  
</P>
<P>
	``What is the big deal of seven people ... having left? ... No  
deal whatsoever, happens all the time and will continue to happen. 
And by the way, it will happen very soon at the other two companies 
in Detroit as well,'' Schrempp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton said he, too, was unconcerned.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you have a management team as attractive as we have, you  
always have people trying to lure them away,'' Eaton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton has said since the deal was announced last May that he  
would leave DaimlerChrysler within three years and leave Schrempp 
as sole chairman. He declined today to say if he might leave sooner 
than that, as some analysts expect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always said that I would be here until I felt the  
integration is going well,'' Eaton said. ``But Juergen Schrempp and 
I agree that a company can have only one CEO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler headquarters is divided between Stuttgart,  
former home of Daimler-Benz, and Auburn Hills, Mich., former home 
of Chrysler. The company has started its own jet shuttle between 
the two. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 reporters from around the world packed a Stuttgart  
concert hall for the news conference, which was translated into six 
languages and transmitted live on the Internet. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
