<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Dying in Mexico City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A glowing red sun set in a cloudless sky, a  
light breeze blowing through the stadium. And, on this perfect 
night for baseball, the home team had a 4-1 record. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet all but a few hundred of the 25,000 seats were empty when  
the Mexico City Tigers rallied in the eighth inning to beat the 
Cancun Lobstermen. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad to see how few people come,'' said Carlos Hernandez,  
a 41-year-old trauma surgeon who had a section all to himself just 
to the first-base side of home plate. ``It's really such a pretty 
stadium, and it's so nice to sit out here in the evening. All 
that's missing is a little human warmth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's a common complaint among baseball fans in the Mexico City  
area, the country's political, financial and cultural capital and 
home to one out of five Mexicans. 
</P>
<P>
	What once was baseball fever has been tamed by bitter memories  
of a players' strike and news media that largely ignore the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico's national television channels, which crowd the airwaves  
with soccer, NFL football and professional wrestling, haven't 
broadcast a Mexican baseball game in years. The only way to see 
Mexican league play is on ESPN2, alongside strongman contests and 
beach volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	The major national newspapers banish baseball to the inside  
pages of their sports sections, behind soccer, boxing, NBA 
basketball and tennis. 
</P>
<P>
	So it should be little surprise that interest has dropped off.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're used to playing without fans,'' said Matias Carrillo,  
the Tigers' star right fielder who drove in the winning run this 
spring evening. ``We play with enthusiasm, but if there were fans 
we'd play with more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And yet in much of the country, ``beisbol'' is the sport of  
kings. Just ask Carrillo, who is from Sinaloa state on the Pacific 
coast, or Hernandez, who's from the Gulf of Mexico state of 
Veracruz. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside Mexico City, local television stations transmit games  
and people listen on radio for the latest score. Baseball players 
are celebrities and children play in leagues, hoping to make it big 
someday. 
</P>
<P>
	When the San Diego Padres and the Colorado Rockies open the  
major league season in Mexico on Sunday, they will do so in 
Monterrey, a northern city where baseball still dominates. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball is still immensely popular across the entire north of  
the country, where more contact with the United States helps the 
sport. But even in many places with no U.S. link, baseball still 
reigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Only an hour north of Mexico City, a mountain town called  
Omitlan de Juarez has no soccer fields. Its baseball stadium is the 
town's pride and is home to weekly games by three local teams -- 
children, teen-agers and adults, all amateurs. 
</P>
<P>
	On a recent Sunday, the Omitlan Parrots were down 19-2 to the  
state champions, the Zimapan Miners. 
</P>
<P>
	But it didn't matter. About 300 fans packed the bleachers,  
whooping and ringing cowbells with every hit. Those who didn't fit 
in the stands gathered on nearby roofs to watch the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Soccer's a tough thing to go up against with games on TV all  
the time,'' said Omitlan manager Daniel Garcia, a 38-year-old 
industrial engineer. ``But boys see their fathers playing, and we 
try to pass on our values. If not, baseball would be finished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Omitlan, at least, it seems to be working.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've been playing since I was 3, and I don't play anything  
else,'' said Mario Ruben Rodriguez, 12, a center fielder on his 
Little League team. ``I'll play until I die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most fans point to television for baseball's drop in popularity  
the last decade or two. They accuse the two television networks, 
both of which own soccer teams, of favoring soccer for financial 
reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican TV networks once broadcast games, then went to the  
championships only, and now have dropped baseball altogether. 
Antonio de Valdez, sports coordinator for Televisa, Mexico's 
biggest television network, conceded that baseball isn't a 
profitable broadcast because of its slow pace and the uncertainty 
of a game's length. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has become a regional broadcast rather than a national  
one,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he also blamed the drop-off on a strike in the early 1980s  
in which the players walked out on full stadiums to demand higher 
salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a very sad memory,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Alejandro Merlos is 23 years old and doesn't remember the  
strike. But he sure knows about the empty stands. A beer vendor at 
the Mexico City ballpark, he struggles to make $4 a night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I work on commission, and it's hard to make anything  
nowadays,'' he said. ``And every year it gets worse.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
