<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Ads Spurs Tax Status Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- A federal judge has ruled that a church  
should lose its tax-exempt status because it ran ads saying that 
voting for Bill Clinton would be a sin. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman on Tuesday upheld a 1995  
decision by the Internal Revenue Service to strip the Church at 
Pierce Creek of its tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling means that followers may no longer deduct church  
donations from their taxable income and the church will have to 
file corporate tax returns. 
</P>
<P>
	The 500-member congregation, an unaffiliated Protestant group,  
now worships as the Landmark Church. Among its members is Randall 
Terry, founder of the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	The church's pastor said the decision threatens freedom of  
speech as well as freedom of religion. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have to start as church to consider what the  
government might do to you if you speak on moral issues, that's the 
exact problem,'' the Rev. Dan Little said Wednesday. ``This is 
scary stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four days before Clinton defeated President Bush in 1992, Pierce  
Creek bought full-page ads in The Washington Times and USA Today 
attacking Clinton's morals. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans United for Separation of Church and State, a watchdog  
group, complained to the IRS that the ads were political and 
violated the church's tax-exempt status as a nonpartisan group. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said he found no prior instance ``in which a church so  
brazenly claimed responsibility for a political advertisement in a 
national newspaper and solicited tax-deductible donations for that 
political advertisement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friedman's decision will be appealed, said Colby May, a  
spokesman for the American Center for Law and Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
