<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jenny Jones' Civil Trial Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- ``The Jenny Jones Show'' and its  
distributor ``lit the fuse'' that led to a guest's shooting death, 
an attorney for the victim's family said today during opening 
statements in a lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	A waitress, a machinist, a retiree and a decorator are among  
jurors chosen Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Amedure was killed in 1995, three days after revealing a  
crush on a heterosexual acquaintance, Jonathan Schmitz, during a 
taping of the show. Schmitz was convicted of second-degree murder 
in 1996, but the conviction was overturned last fall because of an 
error in jury selection. Schmitz's retrial is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure's family contends in the $50 million lawsuit that the  
show's producers lied to Schmitz about the gender of his admirer, 
disregarded warnings about the dangers of surprising guests and had 
no concern about Schmitz's mental state. The suit names the show, 
distributor Warner Bros. and producer Telepictures Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	In his opening statement for the family, attorney Geoffrey  
Fieger said he will show ``that they lit the fuse that resulted in 
Jonathan Schmitz committing this god-awful and unspeakable act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fieger said talk shows are driven to capture audience share,  
which influences how much advertisers pay for time. ``And so people 
like Jonathan Schmitz and Scott Amedure are like profits. They're 
not people to be concerned about,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his opening statement, Telepictures attorney James Feeney  
said that after the shooting, Schmitz never told police that he 
felt he was tricked, deceived, or lied to about the show's topic. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not what Jonathan Schmitz said. That's not how he saw  
it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Feeney also said that before the taping, Schmitz suspected the  
secret crush might be Amedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside court, Feeney said earlier today that he has witnesses  
who will testify that Amedure and Schmitz had a sexual encounter 
after the show's taping. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question they had a relationship and it was sexual  
and that Scott Amedure told his mother of that,'' Feeney told 
reporters. He didn't immediately bring up the allegation as he 
began his opening statement this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz made no such claim when he was on trial.  
</P>
<P>
	The judge ruled in a pretrial motion this morning that Feeney  
must give Feiger the names of the witnesses alleging the two men 
had an affair. If Fieger finds those witness' stories questionable, 
he can request an evidentiary hearing on whether they can testify. 
</P>
<P>
	Fieger today called such testimony prejudicial and irrelevant  
and questioned whether such witnesses or testimony even exists. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is listed as a witness in the case. Feeney said it was  
likely she would testify early next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
