<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks' Johnson Feeling Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Arizona Diamondbacks fans can breathe a  
sigh of relief. Randy Johnson pitched six no-hit innings in a minor 
league game Wednesday and said he felt no hint of the strained 
right groin that had caused him to miss his previous start. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt good,'' he said. ``I'm ready to go.''  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-10 left-hander had his fastball clocked at 97 mph and  
his slider at 83 to 86 mph, an indication that despite the minor 
injury that altered his spring training timetable, he's in shape 
for Monday's opening day showdown against Kevin Brown at Dodger 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's enough to beat the Dodgers, I won't know until I  
get over there,'' Johnson said, ``but I feel confident enough that 
I'm leaving spring training with the arm strength that I wanted and 
the mentality that I wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson threw 89 pitches -- 39 balls and 50 strikes -- in game for  
Arizona's Triple-A club against the Chicago White Sox Triple-A 
team. A strong, gusty wind blew at Johnson's back throughout the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Keeping his balance must have been tough with the wind blowing  
the way it was, but I think he handled it very well,'' manager Buck 
Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson walked four, hit a batter and struck out five. Only  
three balls were hit out of the infield. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to get the most out of today's game,'' Johnson said.  
``Health-wise, I felt good. I threw the amount of pitched Buck 
wanted and I threw the amount of innings I set out to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was able to work on all his pitches, both from the windup and  
the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's encouraging,'' Showalter said. ``You couldn't ask for  
anything better in terms of pitch count.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the spring, Johnson's well-documented moodiness has  
been nowhere to be seen. He's been cooperative with reporters, 
patiently signed autographs and made all the public appearances 
that were asked of him. During Wednesday's game, he was at the 
entrance to the dugout to high-five a Triple-A player who homered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my first spring training down here and people have been  
very nice and cordial,'' Johnson said. ``At the restaurants I went 
out to, they'd say how excited they were about the season. They've 
welcomed me here, so it's going to be a lot of fun this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's pleasant spring was interrupted when he strained his  
right groin during pitcher's fielding practice March 23. He missed 
his scheduled start last Friday and Showalter decided to have him 
pitch in a minor league game Wednesday rather than in the 
Diamondbacks game against Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have any symptoms that it's still there, but I'll ice  
it and continue to strengthen it between now and my next start,'' 
Johnson said. ``It was definitely a plus being able to pitch today 
and not having any problems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
