<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heyns Nears Breaststroke Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- South Africa's Penny Heyns missed a world  
record by just three-hundredths of a second Thursday as she led 
qualifying in the women's 50-meter breaststroke at the world 
short-course swimming championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Heyns, the Olympic champion and long-course world record holder  
at 100 meters, won her heat in 30.80 seconds, just behind the world 
mark of 30.77 held by China's Han Xue. For the first time, FINA, 
swimming's world governing body, is offering awards of $15,000 for 
any world record broken at this meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Han was fourth fastest among the 16 qualifiers for Thursday  
night's semifinals. Her 31.70 was behind the 31.19 of Japan's 
Masami Tanaka and the 31.63 of Britain's Zoe Baker. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Klim and Ian Thorpe led the pace in heats for the  
200-meter freestyle, where the Australians hope to break the oldest 
men's short-course record still on the books -- Italian Giorgio 
Lamberti's 1990 time of 1 minute, 43.64 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Klim, the long-course world champion in the 200 freestyle and  
100 butterfly, won his heat in 1:45.20. Thorpe, the long-course 
world champion at 400 meters, won in 1:45.56. Dutch swimmer Pieter 
van den Hoogenband was third in his heat behind Italy's 
Massimiliano Rosolino and Johan Kenkhuis, but his 1:47.16 put him 
sixth fastest among the eight qualifiers for Thursday night's 
final. 
</P>
<P>
	Klim was second fastest in qualifying for the 100 butterfly.  
Britain's James Hickman, who holds the world record of 51.02, led 
qualifiers in 51.78. Klim, in the same heat, was second fastest in 
51.89. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian world record holder Matthew Dunn was fifth fastest in  
qualifying for the men's 400-meter individual medley. He won his 
heat in 4:13.47, while Israel's Mickey Halka was the fastest 
qualifier in 4:12.74. 
</P>
<P>
	American Jenny Thompson, who holds the world records in three  
other events, was the fastest qualifier in the women's 100 
freestyle in 53.34, with Dutch swimmer Inge de Briujn and 
Slovakia's Martina Moraacova tying for fastest in another heat in 
54.07. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba's Rodolfo Falcon was fastest in the 50 backstroke in 24.71.  
</P>
<P>
	Other fastest qualifiers were Denmark's Sophia Skou in the  
women's 200 butterfly, Ukraine's Dmytro Kraevskyy in the men's 50 
breaststroke, Japan's Mai Nakamura in the women's 100 backstroke, 
and Canada's Joanne Malar in the women's 400 individual medley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
