<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Health Outfit Settles for $61M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Olsten Corp., one of the nation's largest home  
health companies, said its Kimberly Home Health Care subsidiary 
will plead guilty to federal criminal charges and pay $61 million 
to settle a government fraud investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal charges against Kimberly Home Health Care stemmed  
from a whistleblower lawsuit filed against hospital giant 
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. charging Medicare fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Justice Department, Columbia bought several  
Florida home-health agencies at artificially low prices from 
Kimberly, and then paid Olsten inflated fees to manage the 
agencies, apparently as a way to obtain more Medicare 
reimbursements from the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia has been the target of a federal billing fraud  
investigation for more than 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Olsten said Tuesday that $10 million of the $61 million  
settlement would be paid in fines and penalties. Olsten did not 
disclose the specific criminal charges to which Kimberly Home 
Health Care will plead guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	Olsten said it has been assisting the government in its Medicare  
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Melville, N.Y.-based Olsten said it will take a special  
after-tax charge of $70 million for the first quarter in connection 
with the settlement and a cost-cutting restructuring plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Olsten said it will eliminate 8 percent of its 400 health  
staffing branch offices in the United States and Canada as part of 
the realignment. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said it will leave the hospice business and a  
number of home medical equipment markets; close or consolidate 15 
nursing branch offices across the United States, and continue a 
streamlining of billing and collection services. 
</P>
<P>
	In morning trading, shares of Olsten fell 37 1/2 cents to $6, on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
