<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Two slow-moving storm systems were menacing much of the West and  
the Southeast today, while March was going out like a lamb from the 
Southwest across the central Plains to the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure moving off the coast was expected to keep skies  
clear across the Northeast and mid-Atlantic regions, allowing 
temperatures to climb well above normal. 
</P>
<P>
	But a sluggish low pressure system over the Gulf Coast was  
bringing showers to Alabama, Georgia and western Florida, with 
significant rainfall totals expected. The bad weather should spread 
into the western Ohio Valley and Carolinas by evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Winds gusting over 35 mph were expected in the Great Lakes and  
across the Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Plains should remain dry through the day, but afternoon and  
evening thunderstorms -- featuring large hail and damaging winds -- 
were possible in Nebraska and South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong winds were also forecast in the southern and central  
Rockies and into the desert Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the rest of the West was expecting precipitation due to  
a low pressure area moving across northern Nevada and into Utah. 
Significant snowfall was forecast across the Intermountain West and 
the higher elevations of the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal Oregon and California expected rain showers, while dry  
weather was forecast for Washington and Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast in the 30s in Montana, Idaho and parts  
of the surrounding states; the 40s and 50s in the rest of the 
Northwest, the northern Plains and in New England; the 80s in the 
desert Southwest and southern Florida; and the 60s and 70s 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures Tuesday ranged from 90 in Blythe, Calif., to 17 in  
Yellowstone, Wyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
