<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Waddell Overcomes Injury To Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It was the biggest win of Oza James Waddell Jr.'s life -- a  
second-place finish as the driver of Hutt Girl, an 8-year-old 
pacing mare, in a race for $2,500 claimers. 
</P>
<P>
	The race last week at Los Alamitos in Cypress, Calif., was a  
psychological victory as far as the 37-year-old Waddell was 
concerned. It was his first drive in a betting race. 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell is paralyzed from the waist down, a result of being shot  
during a dispute at a party in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Waddell, who has had a trainer's license for many  
years, has driven in several qualifying races, but due to 
opposition by people in the sport, he was unable to get a 
provisional license to drive in a betting race until he went to 
court and won. He got the provisional license two weeks ago and 
hopes to get a regular license.. 
</P>
<P>
	``I proved I was no more of a danger, no more of threat of  
getting hurt than anybody else,'' Waddell said of his second-place 
finish behind 10-1 shot Hutt Girl, 3 3/4 lengths behind Canterbury 
Tower. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the Waddell's satisfaction was the reaction  
immediately after the race of driver Jim Lackey, who had opposed 
Waddell being permitted to drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me, `O.J., it was a great drive out there,''' Waddell  
said. `You were very cool out there, very safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only difference in Waddell's sulky and others is that the  
seat is two inches higher. He wears orthopedic braces to keep his 
legs straight in the stirrups, and the braces have latches that can 
be easily released in case of a spill. 
</P>
<P>
	Making the night even more special for Waddell, who grew up on a  
horse farm at Fontana, Calif., and now lives at Rialto, Calif., 
were the numerous family members and friends on hand, including his 
father, who had a stroke 3 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4 Waddell, who prefers to be called Oza -- ``I'm  
trying to get away from O.J., especially here in California.'' -- 
was a good enough wide receiver to be offered a football 
scholarship at New Mexico State. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came that fateful party.  
</P>
<P>
	Waddell said there was some pushing and shoving and that one of  
those involved left and returned with a gun and shot him. The 
assailant was convicted, but Waddell's world was in tatters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked my father to take me to the top of the hospital and  
throw me off,'' he recalled. ``He said, `Hey man, you're name is 
Waddell and Waddells are no quitters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The father also told him, ``You sit in a wheel chair the same  
way to sit in the sulky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has just taken a long time for Waddell to prove to doubters  
that once he's sitting in sulky, he's not just along for the ride, 
but that he is a competitive harness-racing driver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to win, but second place is all right with me,'' he  
said after his initial drive. ``I think I proved that I belong in 
this sport and that I'm serious about competing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before ending a recent interview, Waddell said, ``If you can,  
put a word in for Christopher Reeve (the actor, who was paralyzed 
from the neck down when he fell off a horse). He's been a real 
inspiration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So has Waddell -- to a lot of people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
