<DOCNO> APW19990331.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 09:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McClelland, Crawford Named Top Umps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Umpires don't like baseball players rating them.  
</P>
<P>
	``I give no credence whatsoever to those ratings,'' umpires  
union head Richie Phillips said Tuesday. ``I think they're patently 
absurd. I've even been told that some players had their kids fill 
them out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tim McClelland and Jerry Crawford are the top umpires, according  
to a survey by the players association, and Ken Kaiser and Charlie 
Williams are the worst. 
</P>
<P>
	Players rated umpires on physical condition, physical and mental  
toughness, accuracy of calls on the bases, accuracy of calls at the 
plate, consistency, temperament, respect for players and overall 
capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	McClelland topped the AL ratings, followed by Jim Joyce, Rich  
Garcia, John Hirschbeck, Mike Reilly and Drew Coble. Kaiser was 
32nd and last, with Durwood Merrill 31st, Ted Hendry 30th, Joe 
Brinkman 29th and Dale Ford 28th. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawford, president of the umpires union, was tops in the NL,  
followed by Ed Rapuano, Ed Montague, Randy March, Frank Pulli and 
Jeff Kellogg. Williams was 36th and last, with Eric Gregg 35th, Joe 
West 34th, Bruce Froemming 33rd and Harry Wendelstedt 32nd. 
</P>
<P>
	West and Froemming are among the most confrontational umpires.  
West was last in the NL in both the respect for players and 
temperament categories and Froemming was next to last in both. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials said they thought players penalized  
confrontational umpires in their ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	``The survey was a players association initiative, and the  
players are certainly entitled to their opinion,'' NL president Len 
Coleman said. ``I will point out that umpire popularity was a 
factor, and the skills and qualities of many fine umpires were 
distorted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Alderson, who is taking increased responsibility for  
umpires in his role as executive vice president of baseball 
operations in the commissioner's office, thought players ``were 
serious in their effort and tried to be as systematic and objective 
as possible.'' He said he didn't look at the survey until it became 
public this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the outset of my involvement with the umpires, I didn't  
necessarily want to be to be swayed by prior opinion,'' Alderson 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bud Selig and AL president Gene Budig declined  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look at a guy like Bruce Froemming and how many times he's  
assigned by the league president to work big, important games, and 
then you see him rated next to last, what does that mean?'' 
Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crew that worked last year's AL championship series, which  
was heavily criticized, had four members with poor ratings: Tim 
Welke (10th), Jim McKean (12th), Jim Evans (20th), John Schulock 
(21st), Larry Young (22nd) and Hendry (30th). 
</P>
<P>
	The World Series crew fared much better. It included Garcia  
(third), Tim Tschida (eighth) and Dale Scott (ninth) from the AL, 
and Crawford (first), Mark Hirschbeck (10th) and Dana DeMuth (11th) 
from the NL. 
</P>
<P>
	The ratings, which were distributed to players, were first  
reported earlier this week by the New York Post, USA Today and the 
Philadelphia Daily News. A copy was obtained by The Associated 
Press on Tuesday from a baseball source on the condition he not be 
identified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
