<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan Z-Car Will Return in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ailing Nissan Motor Co. plans a needed image  
transfusion: The Japanese automaker confirmed Wednesday it will 
resurrect the Z sports car that helped make it an automotive force 
in the United States back in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The original Z-car was known as the Datsun 240-Z and was largely  
a U.S. phenomenon. It was inexpensive, fast, sporty and stylish. 
</P>
<P>
	The new version, which will debut no later than the 2002 model  
year, will simply be called the ``Z.'' It will be sold worldwide; 
officials said that in some markets, it may be branded as a 
Renault. 
</P>
<P>
	France's Renault SA announced last week that it was buying a 37  
percent stake in debt-ridden Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's announcement at the New York International Auto Show  
was made by Minoru Nakamura, president and CEO of Nissan North 
America Inc., who borrowed a theme from the baseball movie ``Field 
of Dreams'': ``If you build it, they will come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nakamura stood on a stage amid a fake cornfield and shouted,  
``We will build it!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan said the strong positive reaction to the Z concept car  
since it was unveiled in January at the Detroit auto show convinced 
executives in Japan to approve the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been overwhelmed with letters from all over the world to  
go forth,'' said Jerry Hirshberg, president of Nissan Design 
International in La Jolla, Calif. ``This a company that needs to 
get back in the business of doing passionate products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan wants the Z to be more than a niche vehicle and hopes its  
price in the mid-$20,000 range will make it more affordable than 
most of the two-seaters that have crowded the sports car market in 
the last few years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the reincarnation represents a big gamble for Nissan.  
</P>
<P>
	If the car succeeds, it will help erase Nissan's reputation for  
bland styling and lure more customers into Nissan showrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Should it flop, it will exacerbate Nissan's woes. The company is  
mired in nearly $20 billion in debt and is about to embark on the 
$5.4 billion deal with Renault, in which the French automaker plans 
to subject Nissan to a heavy dose of cost-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just the motivation the corporation needed during what  
has been, after all, rather difficult times for us with our minds 
on a few other things, such as learning French and staying in 
business,'' Hirshberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the Z, while risky, seemed like just the right thing to do  
at exactly this kind of time,'' he said. ``It says to the world, 
`We're playing hardball.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Hirshberg said the concept car, which was created in just four  
weeks, will be further refined and that the finished production 
model will be ``bolder.'' It likely will be rear-drive and powered 
by either a four- or six-cylinder. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan plans to follow up the coupe with a convertible.  
</P>
<P>
	``While it will retain some reference to its heritage, it will  
not be a `retromobile.' It will be a forward-looking car because we 
think the car has to resonate with people for whom `Z' is just a 
letter in the alphabet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan picked New York for the announcement because the original  
240Z was unveiled here in October 1969. The show opens to the 
public Saturday and runs through April 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:35:09 </DATE_TIME>
