<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Teams Combine for 16 HRs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- New Mexico and New Mexico State  
combined for 16 homers at Lobo Field on Tuesday, one shy of the 
NCAA record. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lobos, who won 28-18, hit 10 homers, eclipsing the school  
record of six. New Mexico State (12-21) tied its school record with 
six homers. Louisville and Western Illinois combined for an 
NCAA-record 17 home runs in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Scott Candelaria hit two home runs with five RBIs to  
lead the way for New Mexico (15-19-1) as eight starters homered. 
Ironically, second baseman Lon Yamaguchi, the school's career 
leader with 36 home runs, was the only Lobos starter not to homer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lobos' 28 runs also set a school single-game record, while  
their 28 hits were two shy of the school mark set against Hawaii in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	New Mexico, leading 8-7 in the third inning, blew the game open  
with 10 runs on nine hits, including a solo homer by Candelaria, 
and two-run homers by outfielders Mike Campbell and Miguel Montiel. 
</P>
<P>
	Catcher Steve Elzy went 5-for-6 with five RBIs for the Lobos.  
Third baseman Aaron Sisk was 3-for-6, and has homered in six 
straight for New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Chris Weekly hit two homers and drove in six runs for  
New Mexico State, which had 21 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Vance Bonner (4-2) picked up the win despite allowing 10 runs on  
11 hits in four innings. Aggies starter Pat Leach (2-7) allowed 18 
runs, 10 earned, on 18 hits in three innings. 
</P>
<P>
	All nine Lobos starters had at least two hits and two runs  
scored, while every Aggies starter had at least one hit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 07:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Not Compelled To Buy Saab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The president of General Motors Corp. appeared  
to be a cautious shopper Tuesday when asked about the prospects for 
buying the 50 percent of Sweden's Saab Automobile AB that GM does 
not yet own. 
</P>
<P>
	GM President G. Richard Wagoner Jr., said his company was in the  
process of analyzing whether it makes sense to expand its Saab 
investment, but that so far he saw ``no compelling reason'' to 
exercise the option. 
</P>
<P>
	``This co-ownership has worked out pretty well,'' he told  
reporters during the media preview of the New York International 
Auto Show. ``I can't think of a single incident where having two 50 
percent owners resulted in not doing what was right for the 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM acquired half of Saab from the Swedish holding company  
Investor AB for $600 million in 1989 and has an option to buy the 
remaining half for the six months starting on July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Saab's chief executive suggested that an  
acquisition might be costly, given the automaker's recent sales 
gains and improving financial balance sheet. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 12:35:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 38 After Being Up 88 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were moderately lower today as  
interest rates rose in response to several reports of the economy's 
continuing strength. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 38.02 at 9,875.24. The Dow rose as high as 10,002.06, up 
88.80, in the first hour of trading but quickly retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris, a Dow component, was down 3 3/16 at 34 5/8,  
translating to a 13-point loss in the blue-chip index. Philip 
Morris and other tobacco stocks fell after an Oregon jury ordered 
the cigarette maker to pay $81 million to the family of a man who 
died of lung cancer after smoking Marlboros for four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were narrowly mixed. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 3.82 at 1,296.93, and the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was up 0.74 at 2,496.93. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues edged past advancers with 1,435 up, 1,538 down  
and 563 unchanged on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came 
to 693.45 million shares, up from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks came under pressure after prices fell and yields rose in  
the bond market in response to a report from the Purchasing 
Management Association of Chicago. The report, which showed that 
the manufacturing sector in that region strengthened during March, 
is considered a precursor of the national purchasing managers' 
report due out Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the 30-year Treasury traded at 5.62 percent, up  
from 5.58 late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that the nation's gross  
domestic product surged at a 6 percent annual rate during the 
fourth quarter, close to the department's earlier estimate of up 
6.1 percent. GDP increased by a robust 3.9 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A price index tied to the GDP rose just 1 percent in 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	But the government's corporate profit report, which is the  
bottom line for stock investors, was less upbeat. Its first 
estimate of after-tax corporate profits showed a drop at an annual 
rate of 1 percent in the fourth quarter, the third quarterly 
decline of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	And for all of 1998, profits slipped 2.2 percent, the first drop  
since 1989, when earnings fell 4.8 percent in a precursor to the 
1990-91 recession. 
</P>
<P>
	``You had a bit of a reaction in the bond market to the Chicago  
report,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward 
Jones of St. Louis, although I think the silver lining is that the 
economy is still strong. What the stock market should recognize is 
that ultimately, the strength of the economy will lead to stronger 
corporate profts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer stocks in general were lower. Dow component Procter &AMP;  
Gamble was down 1 5/16 at 98 13/16. Coca-Cola, still reeling from a 
report of lower sales on Tuesday, was down 2 1/4 at 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow member IBM was up 3/16 at 178 3/4 Dell was up 1 31/32 at 41  
27/32 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain, Ireland Pledge Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The prime ministers of Britain  
and Ireland resumed negotiations with Northern Ireland's 
politicians today in hopes of keeping the nearly year-old peace 
accord from unraveling over the IRA's refusal to disarm. 
</P>
<P>
	But the marathon efforts of Britain's Tony Blair and Ireland's  
Bertie Ahern suffered a setback when the Irish Republican Army 
issued a much-anticipated policy statement that failed to mention 
disarmament. 
</P>
<P>
	Blair and Ahern have been trying since Monday to get local  
politicians to agree on terms for forming a new Protestant-Catholic 
government, the centerpiece of last year's Good Friday agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the landmark accord depends on forming the 12-member  
government, which is supposed to receive powers gradually from the 
British and pursue joint policy-making with Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Catholics bill the latter step as likely to promote the eventual  
abolition of Northern Ireland, a Protestant-majority state founded 
in 1920. 
</P>
<P>
	But the largest Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, is  
insisting the IRA -- now 20 months into a truce after violently 
destabilizing Northern Ireland for 27 years -- must start to disarm 
before the outlawed group's Sinn Fein party can receive two posts 
in the government. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous IRA statements, the group has insisted it will never  
surrender its weapons, even though the peace accord requires the 
group to completely disarm by May 2000 in cooperation with an 
international commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's statement emphasized that the IRA's cease-fire would be  
all it had to offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past five years, we have called and maintained two  
prolonged cessations of military operations to enhance the 
democratic process and underline our definitive commitment to its 
success,'' the statement said. ``We have contributed in a real and 
meaningful way to the creation of a climate which would facilitate 
the search for a durable peace settlement. IRA guns are silent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he arrived for today's talks, Sinn Fein chairman Mitchel  
McLaughlin reiterated his party's position that any IRA arms 
gesture was ``absolutely unachievable in the context of this 
week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After talking with Blair and Ahern late Tuesday, Ulster Unionist  
negotiators emphasized peaceful words would not be enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are still waiting for Sinn Fein and the IRA to honor their  
side of the agreement,'' said Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, 
who would lead the government. He said his supporters required 
``deeds, not more words. We have had more than enough words from 
Sinn Fein.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Wilson Has Elbow Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- New York Mets pitcher Paul Wilson  
had reconstructive surgery on his right elbow Wednesday, an 
operation that is expected to sideline him for 9-12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, 25, the top pick in the 1994 draft, found out earlier  
this month that he had torn a ligament. Dr. James Andrews performed 
the surgery in Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson has not pitched in the major leagues since 1996.  
Following surgery on his right shoulder, he wasn't able to play in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	An elbow injury last year limited him to only 57 innings in the  
minors last year. He was supposed to start this season at Triple-A 
Norfolk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:25:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
