<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  New Mexico Hoops Eyes NCAA Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- On his first day in town, newly hired  
New Mexico coach Fran Fraschilla promised to turn the Lobos' 
schedule from fast food to filet mignon. 
</P>
<P>
	``How about New Mexico-UConn?'' Fraschilla said. ``The only way  
to get to the top is to go after the guy at the top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla, 40, was hired Saturday to take over a program that  
under Dave Bliss gained moderate national prominence. The Lobos 
have been to the NCAA tournament seven of the last nine years -- 
losing in the second round the past four seasons -- and have been 
ranked in the Top 25 for 54 consecutive weeks over three years. 
</P>
<P>
	But in recent seasons the Lobos also have gained notoriety for  
playing too many home games against some of the weakest teams in 
Division I. That trend hit an all-time low this season when the 
home schedule included teams like Sacramento State, Arkansas-Pine 
Bluff and Texas-Pan American. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, the constant refrain emanating from New Mexico's  
athletic department has been that the Connecticuts, Dukes and 
Michigan States aren't willing to come play New Mexico in The Pit. 
</P>
<P>
	They will, said Fraschilla, if the Lobos are also willing to  
play them at their place. And he's also counting on getting a 
little help from television. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, the way those kind of games are made is through  
TV,'' he said. ``I know a lot of people that don't want to come 
play here. But sometime you can get TV to twist some arms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla is confident the Lobos can toughen their schedule,  
provided they're willing to sign home-and-home agreements with top 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you go on the road, you want to play the toughest  
competition that you can so that it will help you build a program 
like we want in regard to recruiting, with regard to getting ready 
for your conference and with regard to putting together a strong 
RPI (power rating) for postseason play,'' Fraschilla said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we build the program and build the schedule with it, one of  
the things I'm excited about is playing games that get us national 
attention,'' he said. ``The long term goal is to win a national 
championship. How long that will take, I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla met Tuesday with the New Mexico players. Among them,  
Lamont Long, a junior who would be the Lobos' leading returning 
scorer. But Long has said he is considering leaving early to enter 
the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to have the chance to coach him because he's  
obviously going to be one of the best guards in the country next 
year,'' Fraschilla said. ``And I think the way we'll play will fit 
his style. But if he has a chance to go high in the draft, that may 
be what he and his family choose to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla has six years of head coaching experience. He coached  
four years at Manhattan, taking the Jaspers to two NCAA tournaments 
and then two years at St. John's, where he led the Red Storm to the 
1998 NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	He was fired two months later and Fraschilla has said his  
interest in the then vacant job at Arizona State ``ruffled some 
feathers'' with St. John's officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Fraschilla said, he's where he belongs.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if there's a better match for me,'' he said.  
``I'm a very spiritual guy and I can tell you this has all happened 
for the best. Down the road, if you told me I'm going to stay here 
15 years and coach the Lobos and retire at 55, I'd be very happy 
with that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:24:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NIH To Unveil Vaccine List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new list of ``best buys'' in vaccine  
research highlights vaccines for some little-publicized but 
devastating diseases in newborns and better nationwide flu 
immunization. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Institutes of Health sought advice on priorities  
for funding vaccines against diseases that do not get as much 
attention as, for example, AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	So the Institute of Medicine, a branch of the prestigious  
National Academy of Sciences that advises the government, analyzed 
which potential vaccines would offer society the greatest benefits, 
both by preventing deaths and general suffering as well as by 
saving on health-care costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, which is due out soon but was previewed at a vaccine  
meeting this week, is not a list of vaccines that doctors most 
want. Instead, it advises NIH and private companies how to 
determine which potential vaccines would bring the most bang for 
the investment buck -- offering examples of ``best buys'' that could 
save both money and suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the ones we really want society to invest in ...  
sort of a no-brainer,'' said panel chairman Dr. Robert Lawrence of 
Johns Hopkins University. 
</P>
<P>
	They include:  
</P>
<P>
	--A cytomegalovirus vaccine. CMV is so common that almost  
everyone is exposed at some point. But about 5,000 infected 
newborns a year suffer serious complications, including death or 
retardation, Lawrence said. A vaccine could be developed within 
seven years with an investment of $360 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Group B streptococcus is a widespread bacterium that sometimes  
causes serious disease in adults, but the biggest risk is in 
pregnant women who pass it to their newborns. Childbirth infects 
one in 500 newborns each year. Ten percent die, and up to half 
suffers some neurologic damage. Antibiotics can help at-risk 
pregnant women, but a vaccine could be completed within seven years 
with a $400 million investment. 
</P>
<P>
	--Many elderly Americans now are vaccinated against strep  
pneumonia. But the vaccine does not protect against strains of the 
bacteria-caused pneumonia found in all regions, and expanding its 
use to newborns significantly could cut meningitis and even ear 
infections that the germ also can cause, Lawrence said. Better 
vaccines could be developed within three years with $240 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--Investing $450 million to expand flu vaccinations to more  
Americans significantly could cut the 30 million annual influenza 
cases each year. Flu kills about 20,000 Americans a year, 
hospitalizes 50,000 to 300,000 and costs billions in medical care 
and lost workdays. 
</P>
<P>
	Less cost-effective but still promising vaccines included ones  
to fight ulcer-causing H. pylori bacteria, liver-destroying 
hepatitis C, and cervical cancer-causing human papillomavirus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 09:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vizquel Pleased Contract Mess Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) -- All the worrying Cleveland fans did  
over the winter about Omar Vizquel and his contract seems pretty 
silly now as spring training winds down. 
</P>
<P>
	When Vizquel's request to have his deal renegotiated was denied  
by the Indians during the offseason, it touched off weeks of 
hand-wringing as to what might happen. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel, one of Cleveland's most popular players, hinted at  
delaying his arrival at training camp in protest. There were even 
rumors the Indians were thinking about trading Vizquel. 
</P>
<P>
	Just great, Indians fans thought. Figures. We finally get  
Roberto Alomar to play second base, and now our Gold Glove 
shortstop is leaving town. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, Vizquel isn't going anywhere. And he's not mad at the  
Indians, either. Or if he is, he's not showing it. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the field, Vizquel has been his fun-loving self, recently  
dancing around the Indians' clubhouse before an exhibition game to 
the Latin beat of a CD of Salsa music. 
</P>
<P>
	And on the field, Vizquel, who played with 16 different second  
baseman in the past two seasons, has had instant chemistry with 
Alomar. The Indians' double-play duo looks like it's been together 
for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's over with,'' Vizquel said of his headline-making contract  
situation. ``I'm not even thinking about it anymore. What was done 
was done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel's decision to ask the Indians to rip up his deal irked  
some teammates, especially Sandy Alomar, who was the most outspoken 
critic of the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel hasn't changed his stance, just softened it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think I deserved the right to go up to my general manager  
and the owner of the team and talk about my contract situation,'' 
he said. ``At this point, it's not on my mind anymore. I'm trying 
to focus on getting to the World Series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of Alomar to Cleveland's roster of All-Stars gives  
the Indians a good shot at finally ending a 51-year World Series 
title drought. Alomar's presence has already given the club one of 
the best double-play combos in baseball history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams are stopping to watch us take infield practice,''  
Indians coach Brian Graham said. ``They're something special, and 
the exciting thing is that there was no adjustment. They were on 
the same page on Day 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During batting practice, the two put on quite a show. Alomar  
lines up a grounder, and after scooping the ball, flips it in one 
motion right over the bag to Vizquel. 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel said he wasn't surprised he and Alomar clicked right  
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all we really have to work on is knowing where he  
likes the ball (on a double play turn) and where I want the ball,'' 
he said. ``We don't need to make a perfect throw every time. I 
think instincts will take over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vizquel played 151 games at short last year, and there were  
times, he said, when it felt like there was a different second 
baseman there each time. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998 alone, David Bell, Jeff Branson, Joey Cora, Shawon  
Dunston, Torey Lovullo, Jeff Manto and Enrique Wilson, stepped 
through the revolving door at second to play alongside Vizquel 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it bothered me that much,'' Vizquel said. ``I  
just wish I could have had an everyday player that I could 
communicate with all the time instead of having to change partners 
every two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a challenge for me to try and adjust to each one of  
them. But now having a guy like Robbie out there is going to make 
my job much easier. Obviously, it's going to bring my game level a 
little higher having a guy with that kind of talent beside me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 07:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Student Loans' Report Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Education Department maintains it saves  
money through providing direct college loans to students and 
parents rather than subsidizing loans made by mostly private 
lenders. The department's internal watchdog begs to differ. 
</P>
<P>
	In a recent report, the department's inspector general concludes  
that low interest rates mean low costs, but when interest rates are 
high, the government pays more to make the loans in its 
direct-lending program than it recovers from borrowers repaying 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The report says outdated computer equipment is at least one  
source of the extra costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Education Department officials disputed the findings. They said  
the report used outdated figures for 1996 and 1997, and that it 
made unfair comparisons between the government's actions and how 
the best private lenders would manage the loan program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't believe for a second that the numbers in the study are  
right,'' said Greg Woods, in charge of improving management of the 
department's student financial aid programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics dispute that the program costs less to run and passes  
the savings to students. Currently, rates for borrowers vary in 
both programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The recent report is ammunition against the program, they say.  
</P>
<P>
	``It paints a bleak picture of the Education Department as  
efficient managers,'' said Mark Cannon, the Coalition for Student 
Loan Reform, which lobbies for private lenders. ``It shows that 
there is $100 million annually that is going to bureaucrats and not 
to students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steven A. McNamara, acting Education Department inspector  
general, insists the report is not questioning the department's 
management of either program. He noted that the report also said it 
is difficult to compare the costs of the two loan programs fully 
because they vary each year, depending on interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance officials continue to fight over the two major types of  
loans offered to student borrowers. For many years, the government 
paid subsidies to private lenders so they would make the loans. In 
1994, the government said it could save borrowers money by taking 
out the middleman and started a lending program of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton angered Republican lawmakers and private  
lenders with his budget plan to give the program more funding and 
cut the private lenders' federal subsidy. Direct loans account for 
a third of the $32 billion student-loan market. 
</P>
<P>
	A department plan to offer rebates to student borrowers using  
electronic payments was announced Monday at a meeting of college 
financial aid officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  New Mexico Hoops Eyes NCAA Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- On his first day in town, newly hired  
New Mexico coach Fran Fraschilla promised to turn the Lobos' 
schedule from fast food to filet mignon. 
</P>
<P>
	``How about New Mexico-UConn?'' Fraschilla said. ``The only way  
to get to the top is to go after the guy at the top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla, 40, was hired Saturday to take over a program that  
under Dave Bliss gained moderate national prominence. The Lobos 
have been to the NCAA tournament seven of the last nine years -- 
losing in the second round the past four seasons -- and have been 
ranked in the Top 25 for 54 consecutive weeks over three years. 
</P>
<P>
	But in recent seasons the Lobos also have gained notoriety for  
playing too many home games against some of the weakest teams in 
Division I. That trend hit an all-time low this season when the 
home schedule included teams like Sacramento State, Arkansas-Pine 
Bluff and Texas-Pan American. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, the constant refrain emanating from New Mexico's  
athletic department has been that the Connecticuts, Dukes and 
Michigan States aren't willing to come play New Mexico in The Pit. 
</P>
<P>
	They will, said Fraschilla, if the Lobos are also willing to  
play them at their place. And he's also counting on getting a 
little help from television. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, the way those kind of games are made is through  
TV,'' he said. ``I know a lot of people that don't want to come 
play here. But sometime you can get TV to twist some arms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla is confident the Lobos can toughen their schedule,  
provided they're willing to sign home-and-home agreements with top 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you go on the road, you want to play the toughest  
competition that you can so that it will help you build a program 
like we want in regard to recruiting, with regard to getting ready 
for your conference and with regard to putting together a strong 
RPI (power rating) for postseason play,'' Fraschilla said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we build the program and build the schedule with it, one of  
the things I'm excited about is playing games that get us national 
attention,'' he said. ``The long term goal is to win a national 
championship. How long that will take, I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla met Tuesday with the New Mexico players. Among them,  
Lamont Long, a junior who would be the Lobos' leading returning 
scorer. But Long has said he is considering leaving early to enter 
the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to have the chance to coach him because he's  
obviously going to be one of the best guards in the country next 
year,'' Fraschilla said. ``And I think the way we'll play will fit 
his style. But if he has a chance to go high in the draft, that may 
be what he and his family choose to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fraschilla has six years of head coaching experience. He coached  
four years at Manhattan, taking the Jaspers to two NCAA tournaments 
and then two years at St. John's, where he led the Red Storm to the 
1998 NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	He was fired two months later and Fraschilla has said his  
interest in the then vacant job at Arizona State ``ruffled some 
feathers'' with St. John's officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Fraschilla said, he's where he belongs.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if there's a better match for me,'' he said.  
``I'm a very spiritual guy and I can tell you this has all happened 
for the best. Down the road, if you told me I'm going to stay here 
15 years and coach the Lobos and retire at 55, I'd be very happy 
with that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
