<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Survives Train Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANDERSON, Ind. (AP) -- Her car was rear-ended in dense fog,  
launched into a moving freight train and dragged for miles along 
the tracks -- and a bruised and sore Amber Scott remembered nearly 
every detail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just sitting there, waiting for the train,'' Ms. Scott  
recalled Tuesday, a day after her brush with death. ``I looked in 
my rearview mirror and I saw it (a truck) coming. I just gripped 
the steering wheel and closed my eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When she opened them, she saw the driver's side door of her 1989  
Pontiac Grand Am pinned to the train's side and the car's front 
stuck under it. The train pushed on, dragging the car and its 
frightened passenger with it. 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old Ball State University student grabbed her  
cellular phone and called for help. Her first instinct was to call 
her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mom! Mom! I need help,'' Patricia Scott heard her daughter  
scream. ``Mom, I've been hit!'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the roar of the train in her ear, Ms. Scott could hear only  
a voice on the phone -- maybe an answering machine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was scared,'' she said. ``But I just knew I couldn't sit  
there and be scared. I knew I had to help myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called 911 twice, believing that police would be able to  
trace her call and find her. Her cries for help were barely audible 
over the steady roar of the engines. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm being dragged ... by a train! Oh, please help!'' she  
cried. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott said she briefly thought about rolling out her  
passenger side door but decided against it. Authorities estimated 
the train's speed at 30 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Her car was attached to a middle car of the Conrail train -- and  
the conductor had no way of knowing what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``I scooted down in my seat some, and I just waited,'' said Ms.  
Scott, who was wearing her seat belt. ``I prayed the whole time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She doesn't remember much of what happened after her car hit a  
railroad signpost at another crossing and finally broke free. She 
was shaken up -- and the car was a wreck. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross Schroeder, 25, the driver of the pickup that slammed into  
Ms. Scott's car, has been cited for not having insurance. 
Authorities said the warning lights were working at the crossing, 
but there is no gate. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott's family is thankful to have her home and safe.  
</P>
<P>
	``Her presence of mind has just absolutely astounded me,'' her  
mother said. ``I'm so proud of her. You know there had to be arms 
around her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Ms. Scott: ``It hasn't really all sunk in that I've made it  
through a real life and death experience. I feel like it was a 
miracle.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LPGA's Andrews Prefers Cold Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Calif. (AP) -- Cool weather might be just the thing to  
heat up Donna Andrews' golf game. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the Northern California weather was less than  
perfect for the $600,000 Longs Drugs Challenge. But Andrews' game 
was on target at Twelve Bridges Golf Club. She shot a final-round 
69 to beat runnerup Carin Koch by a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews, third last year in earnings but only 49th so far this  
season, wouldn't mind seeing bad weather again as she defends her 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I actually like the cold weather,'' said Andrews, a nine-year  
LPGA veteran from Pinehurst, N.C. ``It's what I'm used to at home, 
it's what I practice in all winter. This town reminds me a lot of 
home, the weather, the trees, the climate. I love coming back 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fond memories are easily recalled. One of the biggest came when  
Andrews birdied the 16th, pulling ahead of Koch for good. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could tell Donna had been there before, she knew what to  
do,'' said Koch, whose second place was her best career finish. 
``You could tell she was fired up. This was not new to Donna, she's 
tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews will defend her title with many of the tour's top  
players on vacation following last week's Dinah Shore at Rancho 
Mirage. Only six of the top 20 on the money list are in the field. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them is Annika Sorenstam, who likes the tight layout at  
Twelve Bridges. She won the tournament in 1997 and finished third 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dinah Shore winner Dottie Pepper is also expected to play, even  
though she missed Wednesday's pro-am because of the flu. Pepper is 
second on the money list, trailing Karrie Webb, who skipped this 
event for the third straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	Other current top-20 players in the field are Juli Inkster, Kris  
Tschetter, Liselotte Neumann and Maria Hjorth. 
</P>
<P>
	Also scheduled to play are Hall of Famer Pat Bradley, Michelle  
McGann and Jan Stephenson. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Divots:* Koch had the best individual round a year ago,  
shooting a 6-under-par 66 the first day. ... The tournament will 
increase its purse to $700,000 next year and $800,000 in 2001. ... 
Nos. 1 and 18, which have been criticized in the past, have been 
renovated for the tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
