<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kansas City Gets First Female Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Kay Waldo Barnes was elected the city's  
first female mayor with help from a famous relative, cousin Walter 
Cronkite. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes defeated Mayor Pro Tem George Blackwood on Tuesday by 59  
percent to 41 percent, according to final returns. Barnes received 
45,146 votes to Blackwood's 31,319. 
</P>
<P>
	The city's first black mayor, Emanuel Cleaver, was barred by law  
from seeking a third term after eight years in office. 
</P>
<P>
	The race had been expected to be close. Both candidates had  
worked primarily behind the scenes of city government, offering 
little name recognition to voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel honored and humbled by the voters,'' Barnes said. The  
victory came on her 61st birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwood conceded, saying: ``We gave it our best shot.''  
</P>
<P>
	During the campaign Barnes focused on bringing a fresh  
perspective to running the city, which has been plagued by 
corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	Three City Council members have been convicted of felonies and  
several other public officials have been investigated in a federal 
corruption probe that began in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want us to be a city where neighborhoods flourish,  
businesses grow and we're proud of this place we call home,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barnes is president of Kay Waldo, Inc., a human resource  
development consulting firm. She was a member of the City Council 
from 1979-1983. She will be inaugurated April 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Cronkite, who lived in Kansas City for a time as a boy, visited  
earlier this month to attend fund-raisers for his first cousin. The 
82-year-old former CBS anchorman said it was the first time in 60 
years he had endorsed a candidate, adding, ``Bloodlines made that 
necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwood, 59, has been a City Council member for eight years  
and mayor pro tem for four. He had served on the board of directors 
of the National League of Cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwood's campaign was dogged by questions about drinking. He  
was arrested on a charge of driving under the influence of alcohol 
in 1995 and went through a diversion program to have the arrest 
wiped from his record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
