<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Corp. Leases Electric Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Southern Co. plans to to lease at least  
400 electric cars and trucks to its employees over the next four 
years, giving the utility holding company one of the nation's 
largest fleets of electric-powered vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Co. Chairman A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg kicked off the  
lease program Wednesday by loaning two Ford Ranger electric 
vehicles to the National Zoo in Washington, D.C. He was joined by 
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who said electric vehicles 
generate 35 percent less greenhouse gas emissions than conventional 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have two goals for this program,'' Dahlberg said. ``We want  
to help create the mass market for automakers to produce electric 
vehicles nationally and help clean the air by removing the tail 
pipe emissions of hundreds of cars from roadways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dahlberg said Southern employees will have the chance to lease a  
Ford Ranger truck for $150 a month or a General Motors EVI sports 
car for $200 a month. The payments will be automatically deducted 
from employees' paychecks. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 100 electric vehicles will be leased each year over the  
next four years, officials said. That number may be increased based 
on employee demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Co., based in Atlanta, is the parent of Georgia Power,  
Alabama Power, Gulf Power, Mississippi Power and Savannah Electric. 
It already has about 190 electric vehicles, including 147 operated 
by Georgia Power and 35 used by Alabama Power. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
