<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airport Replaces White Supervisor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A white customs supervisor at the Atlanta airport  
was replaced with a black one after the agency was accused of 
unfairly singling out black travelers for searches, an inspector 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale O'Connor, the white supervisor of the 16-member passenger  
inspection team, was transferred to the cargo inspection division, 
said Cathy Harris, a customs inspector who is suing the agency for 
alleged discrimination against blacks. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Robert White, a black supervisor, is being shifted from  
another division to head the passenger inspection team. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Murphy, a spokesman for the Customs Service in Washington,  
declined to confirm the personnel moves. But he did say the agency 
has reassigned some staff members at Hartsfield Atlanta 
International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's issues that have been raised in Atlanta and we want to  
take a serious look here,'' he said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor said he could not comment. White did not immediately  
return calls for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., asked the Treasury Department  
for an investigation into allegations, including Ms. Harris', of 
racial discrimination by Hartsfield customs inspectors. The Customs 
Service is part of the Treasury Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' letter cited a report by WAGA-TV alleging that Hartsfield  
customs inspectors are more likely to detain blacks than whites. 
The report said 90 percent of passengers X-rayed for drugs were 
black, but only 20 percent of blacks detained by customs agents 
were carrying drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my hope that these personnel changes will bring about  
some greater degree of fairness in the way people are treated as 
they pass through the Atlanta airport,'' Lewis said Wednesday. But 
he added that Congress still needs to look into the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Harris, a customs inspector in Atlanta and Miami for 13  
years, has filed several complaints over the last four years, 
alleging discrimination in inspections and saying she has been 
subjected to discrimination and sexual harassment. Customs 
officials have declined to discuss her case. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegations of racial discrimination during the customs process  
have surfaced nationwide. In Chicago, more than 80 black females 
have filed a class-action lawsuit claiming they were singled out 
for strip searches at O'Hare Airport because of race and gender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
