<DOCNO> APW19990331.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Allows Suit vs. Merrill Lynch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The state Supreme Court on Wednesday  
allowed 14 public agencies in an Orange County investment pool to 
sue Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the brokerage they accuse of helping to 
bankrupt the county in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The court unanimously denied review of a lower-court ruling  
reinstating the suit by government agencies from around the state 
who turned down the county's offer to share in its settlement. The 
suit seeks nearly $80 million in damages, interest and legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit accuses Merrill Lynch, the nation's largest brokerage,  
of taking part in former Orange County Treasurer Robert Citron's 
violations of his duties to taxpayers and investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Citron's failed bets on interest rates led to $1.64 billion in  
losses for the county's investment pool, a savings bank for 
schools, cities and water and sewer districts. The losses forced 
the county to seek federal bankruptcy protection in December 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Citron pleaded guilty to falsifying records and violating state  
securities laws and served eight months in a prison work-release 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch agreed last year to pay the county $437.1 million  
to settle a suit accusing the firm of giving bad advice that 
contributed to the financial collapse. The company later agreed to 
pay $2 million to settle Securities and Exchange Commission 
accusations that it was negligent in warning investors about the 
risk of buying the county bonds it underwrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The county and nearly 200 members of the investment pool who  
agreed to take part in its suit have shared $781 million in 
settlements so far, including the money from Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	The agencies that declined were paid $24.5 million for dropping  
their suit against the county. Their suit against Merrill Lynch was 
dismissed in 1997 by Contra Costa County Superior Court Judge 
Walter Rogers, who ruled that only the county could sue on behalf 
of pool members. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1st District Court of Appeal disagreed last December, ruling  
that pool members could try to prove the broker violated an 
independent legal duty to them. The agencies say Merrill Lynch 
fraudulently induced them to invest about $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In seeking state Supreme Court review, Ronald L. Olson, a lawyer  
for Merrill Lynch, said the appellate ruling allowing a separate 
suit by members of a trust fund would open the door to multiple 
suits in the same case, with potentially conflicting results. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 23:53:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Hires Harrick As Hoop Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Jim Harrick figures he can win another  
national championship at Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	After spending the past two years at Rhode Island, where he  
rehabilitated his reputation, Harrick was hired Wednesday as coach 
of the Bulldogs, who haven't made the NCAA tournament since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lack of success under former coach Ron Jirsa,  
Georgia is the kind of school that can be force on the national 
scene, Harrick said. He cited the strength of the Southeastern 
Conference and the state's strong recruiting base, evidenced by 
Monday's national title game when Duke and Connecticut each had a 
player from the same Augusta high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a terrific basketball area,'' he said. ``I'd like  
to control the state. I think we would be very, very good if we do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick came to the news conference with a stuffed dog that  
belted out the Georgia fight song, and he wasted little time 
issuing his first edict to a group of players standing in the back 
of the room 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to see you guys later,'' he said. ``I want you to get  
excited about Georgia basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After suffering through two disappointing seasons under Jirsa,  
the Georgia players were ecstatic to get a coach who has won a 
national title. Harrick guided UCLA to the 1995 championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unbelievable,'' center Robb Dryden said. ``When I heard  
the news, I was like, `He's coming here?' That should do volumes 
for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five returning players attended the news conference, but  
sophomore Jumaine Jones was a no-show. The All-SEC forward, who led 
the Bulldogs in scoring and rebounding, has said he plans to enter 
the NBA draft. He did not answer phone calls to his campus 
apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he should change his decision'' because of Harrick's  
hiring, guard D.A. Layne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Vince Dooley checked with the NCAA before  
hiring Harrick, who was fired by UCLA in 1996 for his involvement 
with an illegal recruiting dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick paid the tab and allegedly lied to cover up that more  
players were at the dinner than allowed by NCAA rules. After 
sitting out the 1996-97 season, he spent two years at Rhode Island, 
leading the Rams to the NCAA tournament both seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick, who has long maintained that he didn't deserve to be  
fired by the Bruins, admitted Wednesday that mistakes were made and 
said he learned from the experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've grown from that,'' he said. ``I'm a better coach and a  
better human being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia president Michael Adams was vice president of  
development at Pepperdine when Harrick coached at the California 
school. The two are close friends, but Adams said he would not 
tolerate the kind of infractions that occurred at UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take compliance very seriously,'' Adams said. ``If a coach  
ever misled me, I wouldn't have that coach working for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick, 60, has a record of 403-182 in 19 years as coach at  
Pepperdine, UCLA and Rhode Island. His teams qualified for the NCAA 
tournament 14 times, including a current streak of 10 in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	At UCLA, he won at least 21 games during each of his eight  
seasons, highlighted by the 31-2 team that won the national title. 
</P>
<P>
	Jirsa, who had never been a head coach before he was picked to  
succeed Tubby Smith, went 35-30 in two seasons. Jirsa was fired 
March 11 after the Bulldogs were routed by Clemson in the first 
round of the National Invitation Tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But Smith showed the school's potential during his two-year  
stint as coach, winning 45 games and reaching the NCAA round of 16 
in 1996 before moving on to Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick was chosen over Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson. The  
other finalist, Delaware's Mike Brey, removed himself from 
consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the beginning, we said our commitment would be to hire a  
proven head coach,'' Dooley said. ``Obviously, we've far surpassed 
that expectation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick received about $350,000 a year at Rhode Island, while  
his four-year contract with Georgia is worth an estimated $550,000 
annually in salary and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The school also will set up a yearly $100,000 annuity, similar  
to the deal for football coach Jim Donnan, that would be paid in 
full if Harrick fulfills his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are sorry to see him leave,'' Rhode Island athletic  
director Ron Petro said. ``His expertise as a coach was appreciated 
by the university, our fans, supporters and players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harrick hoped to bring his son, Jim Jr., to Georgia as an  
assistant coach, but the school nixed that idea because of the 
state's anti-nepotism law. 
</P>
<P>
	``That hurt me more than anything,'' Harrick said. ``That was  
really the only thing that delayed it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
