<HEADLINE> Czechs Stay Perfect in Euro Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Czech Republic, intent on improving its runner-up finish in  
Euro '96, won its fifth straight qualifying game Wednesday night 
with a 2-1 victory over Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day featuring 16 games leading to the 2000 European  
Championships, Germany, Latvia and Spain -- with a hat trick by Raul 
Gonzalez to give him seven goals in the last two games -- took the 
lead in their groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukraine stayed on top despite a 1-1 tie with Iceland, and World  
Cup champion France struggled to a 2-0 win over Armenia. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy, leaders in Group 1, was held to a 1-1 tie by lowly  
Belarus, the Italians' first draw after three victories. 
</P>
<P>
	Three games were postponed because of NATO air strikes against  
Yugoslavia: Slovenia vs. Albania in Group 2, Croatia vs. Malta and 
Yugoslavia vs. Malta, both in Group 8. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 1    	
</P>
<P>
	At Ancona, Italy, the Italians have 10 points after four games.  
Italy evened the score in the 30th minute on a penalty kick by 
Filippo Inzaghi. 
</P>
<P>
	At Zurich, Switzerland, two goals from Stephane Chapuisat  
propelled the Swiss to a 2-0 win over Wales to boost their hopes of 
reaching the finals. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Riga, Latvia, Greece and Latvia's scoreless tie was enough to  
give Latvia the group lead over Norway on goal difference. Greece 
remained No. 3 with six points in five games. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Nuremberg, Germany, the defending European champions scored  
twice in five minutes in the first half -- by Jens Jeremies and 
Oliver Neuville -- to beat Finland 2-0 and take the group lead from 
Turkey on goal difference. 
</P>
<P>
	At Chisinau, Moldova, Northern Ireland tied Moldova 0-0. Moldova  
has two points in five games and Northern Ireland has five in as 
many games. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 4    	
</P>
<P>
	At Kiev, Ukraine, despite a 1-1 tie, Ukraine held its group lead  
on goal difference over France. Iceland has nine points in five 
games and Ukraine and France have 11 in five. 
</P>
<P>
	At Saint-Denis, France, the World Cup champions lacked firepower  
in struggling past Armenia 2-0 on first-half goals by Sylvain 
Wiltord and Christophe Dugarry. France has 11 points but trails 
Ukraine on goal difference. 
</P>
<P>
	At Moscow, Russia routed Andorra 6-1, with Vladimir Beschastnykh  
scoring twice. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 5    	
</P>
<P>
	At Chorzow, Poland, Sweden beat Poland 1-0 on Fredrik  
Ljungberg's goal in the 36th minute. Sweden has won all four of its 
qualifiers. Poland has only six points in four games. 
</P>
<P>
	At Luxembourg, Bulgaria defeated Luxembourg 2-0 behind two goals  
from Hristo Stoichkov to keep its slim hopes alive. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 6    	
</P>
<P>
	At Serravalle, San Marino, Spain bashed San Marino 6-0 with  
three goals from Raul Gonzalez. He had four goals in a weekend rout 
of Austria. Spain leads the group on goal difference. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 7    	
</P>
<P>
	At Baku, Azerbaijan, Romania defeated Azerbaijan 1-0 and has 11  
points in five games. 
</P>
<P>
	At Vaduz, Liechtenstein, Portugal kept the group lead with a 5-0  
victory over winless Liechtenstein. 
</P>
<P>
	At Bratislava, Slovakia, Slovakia and Hungary played to a 0-0  
tie, giving each team eight points in five games. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Group 9    	
</P>
<P>
	At Vilnius, Lithuania, Estonia has seven points in five games  
after a 2-1 decision over Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	At Glasgow, Scotland, the Czechs, who finished second to Germany  
in the last championships, beat Scotland 2-1 and have 15 points in 
five games. 
</P>
