<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virtual Life: `Civilization' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The future of ``Civilization'' was never in  
doubt, with a sequel, a spin-off and add-on packs following its 
immensely successful debut in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	With the millennium fast approaching, the problem now for  
diehard fans of the epic world-building strategy game is having too 
much of a good thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Closely following the release of ``Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri,''  
a global conquest challenge set on a distant planet, comes 
``Civilization: Call to Power,'' a follow-up that extends the 
familiar earthly battle for dominance by nearly 1,000 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meier wasn't involved in developing the latest ``Civ'' sequel,  
devoting his time to ``Alpha Centauri,'' which picks up where 
``Civilization II'' left off, thrusting players onto an off-world 
environment in the 22nd century, where they must build a new 
society from the ground up. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a brilliant continuation of what Meier started, without  
covering any old ground. Players choose one of seven rival factions 
to lead, each based on an overriding philosophy: commerce, military 
might, information freedom, ecology, humanitarianism, spirituality 
or totalitarianism. 
</P>
<P>
	Subtitled ``The Future of Mankind,'' players represent parts of  
a large group of explorers sent to a planet orbiting Alpha Centauri 
who split along ideological lines when their ship was hit by a 
meteor and crash landed on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	The site is significant because players of ``Civilization II''  
could win the game by successfully launching a spacecraft to Alpha 
Centauri, Earth's nearest neighboring star. 
</P>
<P>
	A world of futuristic technology awaits to be discovered in  
Meier's newest creation, leading to dozens of possible military 
applications straight out of science fiction classics, including 
invisibility and antigravity devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Players can also learn how to function in their new environment,  
like building land bridges across bodies of water to access new 
frontiers or raising mountains around inhabited areas to impose 
natural strategic defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The controls are updated, allowing players to delegate many  
mundane tasks to computer operated subordinates. There are five 
different ways to win the game, which comes with a fully equipped 
map editor so players can remodel their new world and play the game 
out again and again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri'' (EA Sports and FIRAXIS Games,  
CD-ROM for Windows95-98, $42.95) is a wild jaunt into the distant 
future that examines the psyche of mankind in the context of an 
action-packed, society-constructing race for survival, where 
embracing the unknown is the only means for success. 
</P>
<P>
	``Call to Power'' is an extension of previous ``Civilization''  
games with a slew of major enhancements and an intriguing look at 
the dark side of humanity, bringing previously unused aspects of 
history into play. 
</P>
<P>
	The game covers 7,000 years, from primitive, nomadic man to 3000  
A.D. It features a streamlined interface designed to minimize the 
micromanagement required in earlier versions, making the game 
easier to play and allowing players to focus on the big picture. 
</P>
<P>
	The most exciting innovations come in the form of so-called  
unconventional warfare, adding subtle dimensions far beyond the 
simplistic states of peace or war players could pursue in previous 
``Civ'' incarnations. 
</P>
<P>
	None are very pretty, as fascism, slavery, terrorism, propaganda  
and hostile corporate takeovers are introduced into the mix. New 
minions one can employ include televangelists, eco-terrorists, 
lawyers, futuristic cyber ninjas, slavers and abolitionists. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the ``Civ'' experience into new arenas, players can  
construct colonies beneath the sea or in orbiting space colonies. 
The goal of the game is to defeat all rival nations, or use 
wormholes in space to make first contact with a superior alien 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Civilization: Call to Power'' (Activision, CD-ROM for  
Windows95-98, $49.95) will also be the first new game released both 
for Windows and Linux, the open-source operating system trying to 
chip away at Microsoft's monopoly of the market. Loki Entertainment 
Software will distribute the Linux version. 
</P>
<P>
	Both games support multiplayer Internet and modem play. Each is  
a credit to the strategy game software excellence brought to home 
computers by ``Civilization,'' which has sold more than 2,500,000 
copies in its first two versions. 
</P>
<P>
	The only difficulty for ``Civ'' junkies devoted to Meier and his  
legacy is deciding whether to buy one, or the other, or both. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
