<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Order Sues Nun's Estate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Sister Sean Condon honored her vow of  
poverty, living for decades in a modest, shared apartment and 
dedicating her life to teaching kindergarten in a working-class 
town. 
</P>
<P>
	She honored her vow even after her parents died and left her a  
small fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not my money. It's not my money,'' her brother-in-law,  
Charles Goetz, said she told him when discussing the $400,000 
inheritance. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sister Condon's order, the Sisters of Mercy of Providence,  
has no intention of rejecting the money. As nuns across the nation 
deal with dwindling ranks and treasuries, the Roman Catholic order 
in Rhode Island has sued Condon's estate to pay her medical and 
burial expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Condon died of leukemia in 1996 at age 53. Until her  
death, she never touched her share of the fortune, which is now 
worth about $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the 400-member Sisters of Mercy of Providence  
insist their finances are strong and that the lawsuit is not aimed 
at shoring up their accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not an effort to find a new way to bolster finances,''  
said their lawyer, James Sloan III. ``All the order wants is 
Sister's will to be carried out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Sisters of Mercy, whose average age is 69, rely like  
most other orders on contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless there is some kind of spiritual rebirth in this  
country, eventually it is going to be dire'' for religious orders, 
said Arlene Violet, a former nun who trained with Sister Condon and 
left the order to become Rhode Island's attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, the number of nuns has dropped 25 percent in the  
past decade -- from 106,912 in 1988 to 85,412 last year, according 
to the National Conference of Catholic Bishops. 
</P>
<P>
	The median age in Catholic religious orders has risen during the  
same time, to 68 for women and 61 for men. With too few working 
members, the conference says, orders face a pension shortfall of 
$7.9 billion, or about 60 percent of their need. 
</P>
<P>
	The strife over the Rhode Island will is rooted in the decline  
of religious orders since the early 1960s, when plump-faced Marilyn 
L. Condon became a nun. 
</P>
<P>
	Although her family was well-off, she chose the Sisters of  
Mercy, which attracted mainly poor girls from the factory towns 
dominating Rhode Island. It began in Dublin in 1831 as one of the 
first non-cloistered groups of nuns. 
</P>
<P>
	She seemed suited to kindergarten, standing just 5 feet tall, so  
short that her young students at the Pawtucket school rose to her 
chest. 
</P>
<P>
	When her father, the owner of a textile mill, drew up his will  
in 1965, he left Sister Condon nothing. Her future, however, seemed 
secure: She would give the order faith and a teacher's wages; in 
return, it guaranteed her health care, a pension and a modest 
living. 
</P>
<P>
	But by 1983, the prospects of a nun's life had dimmed, with many  
abandoning their vows. Sister Condon's mother, Miriam O. Condon, 
amended the will, giving the nun an equal share of the fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Condon, who died in 1990, included a proviso that Sister  
Condon would not get the principal as long as she was a nun in an 
order ``where members take a vow not to own and retain property.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That phrase is at the center of the legal dispute.  
</P>
<P>
	The order allows members to keep their inheritances, so long as  
the money is held by a trustee and used only with the approval of 
the order. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers, the estate claims that Mrs. Condon never  
intended her daughter to get the principal so long as she was in 
Sisters of Mercy. The Sisters of Mercy insist on a literal 
interpretation of the will and believe Sister Condon deserved 
$500,000, rather than only the $100,000 in interest. 
</P>
<P>
	In her own will, Sister Condon gave 25 percent of her estate to  
the order. If her estate were worth $500,000, the order would 
inherit $125,000 -- $100,000 more than Goetz, the executor, was 
prepared to turn over. 
</P>
<P>
	The order, based in Cumberland, is trying to recover the costs  
of Sister Condon's medical and burial expenses, and the taxes it 
paid on the interest income -- about $95,000 in all. 
</P>
<P>
	The case has strained a long relationship between the sisters  
and the devoutly Catholic Condon family. 
</P>
<P>
	A Web site set up by Goetz, a law professor at the University of  
Virginia who stands to get more money if the order loses its suit, 
appeals to nuns to disavow the lawsuit, calling it an example of 
``greed and belligerent litigiousness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Order president Sister Barbara Riley wrote a letter to members  
saying the Web site is inaccurate and part of ``a very difficult 
time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 12:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young People Are Buying Less Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- True or false: Young people love to buy music,  
they crave rock 'n' roll and record stores are their favorite 
places to shop for sounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Answers: False, false and false, at least for increasing numbers  
of people. 
</P>
<P>
	A consumer profile of music buyers issued by the Recording  
Industry Association of America offers insights into a business 
buffeted by change from several directions. 
</P>
<P>
	People ages 15 to 29 -- the bedrock of a youth-obsessed industry  
-- are buying less music, the survey found. This age group accounted 
for 39 percent of music purchases in 1998, down from 42 percent the 
year before. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many ways, music is much more ubiquitous for young  
people,'' said Hilary Rosen, RIAA president and chief executive. 
``You can get it on the radio, get it on MTV, get it on the 
Internet. There are many more choices out there to get music for 
free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through the MP3 technology, computer users are able to sell or  
trade copies of songs through the Internet, an activity that's 
causing major headaches now for the music industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen said Internet distribution is a small factor in the trend.  
But Siddiq Bello, publisher of industry newsletter The MP3 Impact, 
suggested Wednesday that the availability of music in cyberspace is 
responsible for a real dent in sales, particularly among people 
ages 15 to 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers 30 and older bought half the music sold last year,  
compared with 34 percent a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The size of the young age group is shrinking, Rosen said. The  
industry has also heard from many young people who didn't like much 
of the new music put out last year, RIAA spokeswoman Alexandra 
Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rock 'n' roll is still the most popular category of music, but  
its slip is showing. Rock accounted for just under 26 percent of 
the music sold last year, down from 33 percent in 1997 and 42 
percent in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the biggest rock stars of the past decade, such as  
R.E.M., Pearl Jam and U2, have found their influence on music 
buyers has dipped dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
	Rock sales are highly dependent on radio airplay, and more  
stations are playing oldies instead of new music, Rosen said. It's 
also a genre dominated by white males, and women bought more music 
than men in 1998 for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rock is also losing its dominant status to rap and rhythm 'n'  
blues. Rap's stake of the marketplace has doubled over the last 
decade. Rap and rhythm 'n' blues together accounted for 23 percent 
of sales last year, up from 16 percent in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Latin music is also booming, its sales up 25 percent last year,  
in large part because record companies have begun courting this 
demographic, Rosen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dominance of record stores as the most popular shopping  
destination is also fading, although more slowly in the past few 
years. Fifty-one percent of consumers bought music in record stores 
last year, down from 72 percent in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Cost-cutting retailers like Wal Mart and Best Buy are taking up  
a larger share of the marketplace. Just over 1 percent of consumers 
bought music through the Internet last year, a category the 
industry only started counting in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer profile is based on 3,051 telephone and Internet  
interviews conducted by Chilton Research Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Jump Nearly 12 Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The price of gasoline jumped by nearly 12  
cents per gallon in the past two weeks, the steepest increase since 
1990, the American Automobile Association said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The national average price of self-serve regular unleaded  
gasoline increased 11.8 cents since March 16 to reach $1.088 per 
gallon, according to the AAA. This marks the largest increase since 
August 1990, after Iraq invaded Kuwait, when gas prices increased 
23.2 cents, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for other types of gasoline had smaller increases:  
self-serve mid-grade unleaded gas is up 11.4 cents to $1.178, and 
self-serve premium is up 11.1 cents to $1.235. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the country, prices at the pump have soared, in part  
because world oil producers agreed to take an additional 2.1 
million barrels daily off the market, and because of anticipated 
increases in demand for spring and summer driving. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have also pointed to refinery production troubles in  
California, one of the largest U.S. driving markets. Gas is most 
expensive in the West, increasing nearly 14 cents in the past two 
weeks to bring self-serve regular unleaded gas to $1.243 a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas is least expensive in the Southeast at $1.003, an increase  
of 10.6 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate survey found that gasoline prices had increased about  
8.5 cents a gallon in the two weeks leading up to March 19. The 
Lundberg Survey of 10,000 gas stations nationwide found the 
weighted average, including all grades and taxes, had increased to 
$1.0869 cents per gallon in that time period. 
</P>
<P>
	Other regional prices for self-serve unleaded:  
</P>
<P>
	--New England: up 7.2 cents to $1.054.  
</P>
<P>
	--Mid-Atlantic: up 8.8 cents to $1.032.  
</P>
<P>
	--Great Lakes: up 17 cents to $1.123.  
</P>
<P>
	--Midwest: up 11.9 cents to $1.042.  
</P>
<P>
	--Southwest: up 14.5 cents to $1.087.  
</P>
<P>
	The association's Fuel Gauge report is based on data from more  
than 37,000 transaction on March 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 12:15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Hears States' Rights Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A clearly divided Supreme Court tackled an  
overtime-pay dispute Wednesday that could yield a key ruling on 
state governments' vulnerability to being sued when they violate 
someone's federally protected rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the Clinton administration and dozens of probation  
officers seeking overtime pay from Maine urged the court to rule 
that states can be sued in state courts by employees seeking to 
enforce a federal labor law. But an attorney for Maine said doing 
so would violate the state's sovereignty. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits against states generally are barred from federal court,  
Solicitor General Seth Waxman noted for the administration. If 
state courts also cannot be used, he said, people's federal rights 
``were written in disappearing ink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``State courts may not deny a federal right absent a valid  
excuse,'' Waxman said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Maine Solicitor Peter Brann said, ``There's no compelling  
evidence that the states surrendered ... their sovereignty.'' That 
means Congress is powerless to ``give a private individual the 
right to bring a damages action'' against any state, he contended. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maine case is one of several related controversies to be  
decided by a court increasingly sympathetic to state authority when 
it is pitted against the federal government's power. 
</P>
<P>
	The court consistently has split 5-4 in recent rulings on state  
sovereignty. In each, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and 
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy 
and Clarence Thomas prevailed over more liberal colleagues, 
Justices John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg 
and Stephen G. Breyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing in the 60-minute argument session suggested that  
alignment would change when the Maine case is decided, sometime by 
late June. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you prevail, we're going to get some kind of hodgepodge ...  
of enforcement,'' Breyer told Brann. And Souter accused the state 
of lacking ``a coherent theory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kennedy said it was ``hard to conceive the founding fathers  
believed states could be sued in their own courts.'' And Scalia 
suggested the federal government could ``achieve its ends in 
various other ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The probation officers sued Maine in federal court in 1992,  
saying they were unfairly being denied the time-and-one-half pay 
guaranteed by the federal Fair Labor Standards Act for work over 40 
hours per week. 
</P>
<P>
	While their lawsuit was pending, the Supreme Court ruled in 1996  
that the Constitution's 11th Amendment shields states from such 
lawsuits in federal court. So the probation officers refiled their 
lawsuit in state court, still depending on the federal labor law. 
</P>
<P>
	Maine's courts, however, ruled that the 11th Amendment makes  
states immune from state court lawsuits that would be barred in 
federal courts. That would make the state totally immune from being 
sued by employees who allege labor-law violations, although federal 
labor officials still could sue the state to enforce the law. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also has agreed to decide three other states-rights  
issues within the next year: 
</P>
<P>
	--Can states be sued for patent infringement?  
</P>
<P>
	--Can they be sued for violating a federal false-advertising law?  
</P>
<P>
	--Can state employees sue over alleged violations of the federal  
law banning on-the-job age bias? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
