<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silicon Graphics To Post Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) -- Silicon Graphics Inc. said  
Wednesday that its third-quarter losses will be steeper than 
expected, mostly because of production delays in its workstation 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Silicon Graphics said it expects to report a loss of up to 32  
cents a share in the quarter that ended Wednesday. Analysts 
surveyed by First Call Corp. had predicted the company would lose 7 
cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In last year's third quarter, the company lost 36 cents a share  
excluding one-time charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Silicon Graphics said it expects revenue in the low- to mid-$600  
million range. In last year's third quarter, the company had 
revenue of $708.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, the maker of powerful desktop computers said it  
hoped two new competitively priced workstations would end the 
company's financial struggles. Silicon Graphics has lost money in 
nine of the past 10 quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	But production delays have slowed the launch of the new SGI 320,  
a $3,995 model with two Intel Pentium chips and one gigabyte of 
memory. It was to be shipped last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've only been able to ship them in volume over the last few  
weeks,'' said Bill Kelly, vice president of corporate operations. 
``It's not uncommon with this kind of big production transition, 
but it is unfortunate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SGI 540, which has twice the power and memory of the SGI 320  
and is priced at $5,995, will ship in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly said shipping of an updated model of SGI's Origin servers  
also had been delayed by a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to officially report its results for the  
quarter on April 22. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
