<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 02:24:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Lucien Aigner    	
</P>
<P>
	GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. (AP) -- Lucien Aigner, a photojournalist  
known for his images of Albert Einstein and Benito Mussolini, died 
Monday. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hungarian-born Aigner, brother of the noted designer Etienne  
Aigner, was among the first photojournalists to exploit the ability 
of a 35 mm camera to capture candid images of prewar Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	His image of Italian dictator Mussolini tweaking his nose was  
taken at a 1935 conference where Allies tried to dissuade Mussolini 
from an alliance with Hitler. He was able to take it only because 
his camera was inconspicuous. The shot eventually ran on the cover 
of Newsweek in 1941. 
</P>
<P>
	Aigner had fled Paris in 1938, when the war was looming. His  
photo of a rumpled Einstein in droopy trousers standing before a 
blackboard was taken in a Princeton classroom in 1941. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his other notable photo topics were a French sailor and  
his girl dancing in the street on Bastille Day, a smirking Hitler 
and New York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a writer, radio announcer, script writer and  
producer for the Voice of America before coming to this small 
village in the Berkshires in 1954 to open a portrait studio. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his brother, survivors include two sons, two  
daughters and a sister. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Larry Cole    	
</P>
<P>
	WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- Larry Cole, a reporter for the Watertown  
Daily Times for nearly 30 years, died Sunday of a heart attack. He 
was 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole covered several different beats. He was covering Jefferson  
County government at the time of his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole was a member of the news team covering the 1980 Winter  
Olympics at Lake Placid that won an award from the New York State 
Publishers Association for distinguished local reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his father, a son, two daughters, a brother  
and three sisters. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Michel Crepeau    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Michel Crepeau, a longtime lawmaker known for his  
incisive questions and lyrical orations before the French 
Parliament, died Tuesday, a week after collapsing in his National 
Assembly seat from a heart attack. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Crepeau, a longtime leftist, was rushed to Cochin Hospital after  
collapsing before television cameras on March 23, minutes after 
asking a question about savings accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Crepeau, mayor of the Atlantic coastal town of La Rochelle since  
1971, was a member of the Radical Party of the Left. 
</P>
<P>
	He headed various ministries, including Environment from  
1981-83, Commerce from 1984-86 and Justice in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Crepeau, who was elected deputy in 1973, 1986 and 1997, was  
introduced to politics in 1948, when he joined the Radical Party. 
From 1978-81, he served as president of the Movement of Radicals of 
the Left, a small party allied with the Socialists. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his death, Crepeau served as president of the  
Radical, Citizen and Green group in the National Assembly, which 
brought together several small parties. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a presidential candidate in the 1981 election won by  
President Francois Mitterrand. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Bernhardt L. Dorman    	
</P>
<P>
	NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Bernhardt L. Dorman, a longtime  
aerospace executive and former assistant administrator for NASA, 
died Saturday. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorman worked as an executive of Aerojet General Corp., which he  
joined in 1943. He helped establish the firm's rocket production 
and testing facilities in Azusa, Calif., and was among the early 
leaders in the rocket propulsion industry. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1958, when Aerojet was playing a major role in the U.S. space  
and missile development effort, Dorman was named a corporate vice 
president in charge of Test Operations. He later served as 
president of Aerojet Investments Limited, a subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorman took a yearlong absence from Aerojet in June 1967 to  
serve as an assistant administrator for industry affairs at NASA. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Darlene Geis    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darlene Geis, an award-winning author who wrote  
the children's book ``The Little Train That Won a Medal,'' died 
Thursday in a house fire. She was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	She wrote a series of children's books, including ``Dinosaurs  
and Other Prehistoric Animals,'' which earned a Boys Club of 
America Award, ``Design for Ann,'' and ``The Mystery of the 
Thirteenth Floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Geis also worked for book publisher Harry N. Abrams. She  
wrote and edited books for Disney Enterprises, including ``The 
Fantasia Book,'' and ``Treasury of Children's Classics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She retired in 1992.  

</P>
<P>
                          *Edward F. Lapos    	
</P>
<P>
	GLOVERSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- Edward F. Lapos, retired managing  
editor of The Leader-Herald of Groversville, died Monday. He was 
76. 
</P>
<P>
	Lapos began his journalism career at the Leader-Herald as a  
reporter in the 1950s. He was managing editor at the time of his 
retirement in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	He was an Army Air Corps veteran of World War II, where he was a  
B-17 bombardier in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife of 45 years, Grace.  

</P>
<P>
                       *Leonard Mountain Chief    	
</P>
<P>
	HEART BUTTE, Mont. (AP) -- Leonard Mountain Chief, a tribal elder  
of the Blackfeet Indian tribe, movie actor and champion fiddler, 
died Monday of a heart attack. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Mountain Chief appeared in the 1989 film ``War Party.'' He also  
played actor Steven Seagal's father-in-law in the recent film ``The 
Patriot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mountain Chief had roles in 17 films and documentaries since  
1948, including ``All the Young Men'' with Sidney Poitier in 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	He ranched in the Heart Butte area and was active in the  
political community, serving three terms in the Blackfeet Tribal 
Council, and as chairman of the Land Board and gambling committee. 
</P>
<P>
	An avid fiddler, Mountain Chief had played in Nashville and  
Hollywood, and in 1987 headlined a country jamboree at the 
then-College of Great Falls. Later that year he performed in a show 
with Willie Nelson and Waylon Jennings and toured Russia. 

</P>
<P>
                            *J. Sid Webb    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- J. Sid Webb, a veteran high-technology  
executive who became chairman of Titan Corp. after many years with 
TRW Inc., died March 24 of cancer. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb was also longtime chairman of the Doheny Eye Institute at  
the University of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb was with TRW, which provides technology products and  
services for automotive, space and defense and information 
technology markets, from 1954 until his retirement in 1981, and had 
been chairman of Titan, a San Diego-based satellite communications 
company, since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb served as chairman of the Doheny Eye Institute, a center  
for patient care, vision research and physician education, for two 
decades. In 1987, he co-wrote its history in a book titled ``The 
Estelle Doheny Legacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was general manager of its electronics operation and then  
executive vice president. In 1978, he became vice chairman of the 
board of directors and a member of the chief executive office. 

</P>
</TEXT>
