<DOCNO> APW19990331.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:53:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Aftershocks Hamper Rescues in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOPESHWAR, India (AP) -- Villages inaccessible by road awaited  
food, medicine and help to dig out from their shattered homes 
today, two days after a powerful earthquake killed at least 110 
people in a remote mountain region of northern India. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong aftershock measuring magnitude 5 during the night  
toppled more houses, injuring at least 50 people in the town of 
Nandprayag, the Press Trust of India reported. A series of 
subsequent tremors, about one every hour until dawn, kept residents 
on the edge of panic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the wrath of the gods. This is very unusual. We have  
never had so many shocks,'' said Vijay Prasad, the priest in charge 
of the 2,800-year-old temple of Gopinath. 
</P>
<P>
	Medical teams drove as far as they could to treat the injured.  
Villagers from deep in the mountains walked to the road for 
treatment, while others were carried across narrow mountain tracks 
on stretchers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Gopeshwar, a town of several hundred families, most people  
slept in the streets, in playgrounds and even on an army helipad, 
listening in fear as tremors dislodged more boulders from the 
hilltops and sent them crashing down scarred slopes. 
</P>
<P>
	Frightened leopards and other animals strayed into villages from  
nearby forests. One girl was killed by a leopard Monday, Press 
Trust of India reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 350 people were injured in Monday's quake and 2,500 houses  
destroyed. Helicopters evacuated the most seriously injured. Tents 
and makeshift shelters sprang up for the survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	Men walked from distant villages to plead for help from relief  
and rescue workers who have focused on the worst hit town, Chamoli, 
and on towns along the few paved roads in the Garhwal hills, 185 
miles north of New Delhi. 
</P>
<P>
	Kanak Singh Dasauli said he had asked civil authorities to speed  
up deliveries of food and medicine to his village of Kiruli, well 
off the main road. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our houses are destroyed and we have to sit in the open, but  
nobody seems to care,'' Dasauli said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Gwai, a difficult 1,500-foot climb above the nearest road, a  
60-year-old farmer named Sartulal complained: ``All of them come to 
ask for votes when there is an election, but when the earthquake 
took place no one cared if we were dead or alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian Red Cross Society sent a first relief shipment of  
tarpaulins, blankets, clothing, rice and food for 500 people and 
said it asked the International Federation of Red Cross and Red 
Crescent Societies for $95,000 to finance further efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial quake measured 6.8 magnitude, one of the strongest  
recently in India and the most powerful this century in this 
quake-prone district in the lower Himalayas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0209 </DOCNO>
