<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 14:25:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Harnisch Won't Start Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- A stiff back and three disheartening  
innings cost Pete Harnisch his opening day start. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Reds switched to Brett Tomko for the opener after  
Harnisch had more stiffness in his back and trouble getting anyone 
out Wednesday during a 10-4 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko, who is entering this third season with Cincinnati, will  
start Monday against the San Francisco Giants at Cinergy Field. 
Harnisch was pushed back to the fourth game of the season to give 
his back time to get better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an honor,'' Tomko said of his first opening start.  
``That's what everyone strives to do. I'll do my best job. I just 
wish Pete would have been healthy. That would have been the best 
thing for the team because we can't afford to have someone else 
hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds' top two starters have had setbacks this spring.  
Left-hander Denny Neagle is on the disabled list with weakness in 
his left shoulder and isn't expected to rejoin the rotation until 
mid-April at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch was the Reds' top winner last season at 14-7 and the  
clear-cut choice to become the No. 1 starter when Neagle was 
sidelined. Things were going fine until March 16, when he was 
pounded for eight hits and 12 runs in 2 2-3 innings against 
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterwards, he felt tightness on the left side of his back. He  
developed back spasms in a start on March 21, forcing him to the 
sidelines for 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	When he started again on Wednesday, the right-hander couldn't  
get the ball by anyone. Nine of the 18 Phillies that he faced 
reached base on a hit or a walk, and his back never loosened up. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch showed little emotion during the three-inning stint,  
not even when Bobby Abreu hit a three-run homer in the first 
inning. In all, Harnisch threw 64 pitches and gave up seven hits, 
two walks and eight runs. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't know exactly what went wrong.  
</P>
<P>
	``The ball doesn't have the life in the hitting area that it  
normally has and I don't know why that is,'' he said. ``I'm not 
sure if it's mechanical or if my arm's not where I think it should 
be. I really can't answer that. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's quite obvious the ball has nothing on it. They're not  
missing anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only encouraging part of the day was that Harnisch felt no  
pain in his back, an indication that it's getting better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not 100 percent, but I can pitch with it the way it is,''  
he said. ``It's gotten a lot better. I'm not having any pain. It's 
a little stiff, but it's nothing I can't live with until it's gone. 
Hopefully it will be gone soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is for Harnisch to stay behind in Florida when the team  
heads north and pitch in a minor league game on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll push him to the back (of the rotation) and then he'll  
have plenty of time to get some treatment,'' manager Jack McKeon 
said. ``There's no sense in rushing him. You've got to go with four 
starters, so what's the difference if you're one or four -- if it's 
going to mean the extra rest and the treatment's going to help.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 21:12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Three Soldiers Missing in Macedonia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three U.S. Army soldiers were missing in  
Macedonia near the Yugoslav border Wednesday night after possibly 
being captured by members of the Serb military or police while on a 
reconnaissance mission, the Pentagon and NATO officials said. An 
immediate search and rescue mission was launched, involving teams 
from several NATO countries. The team had been on a daytime 
reconnaissance mission when they reported receiving ``small arms 
fire and said they were surrounded,'' according to NATO. The 
missing team was one of several Army units guarding the 
Yugoslav-Macedonia border during the ongoing NATO airstrikes 
against the Serb military in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Expands Yugoslavia Bombardment  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO widened its air assault on  
Yugoslavia Wednesday, vowing there would be ``no sanctuary'' for 
Yugoslav forces trying to rid Kosovo of ethnic Albanians. With the 
air campaign against President Slobodan Milosevic's forces entering 
its second week, Western officials acknowledged that NATO's 
missiles and bombs had so far failed to stop Belgrade's offensive 
in the province. Thousands more refugees from the province poured 
across the frontier into neighboring countries. At least 118,000 
ethnic Albanians have fled to Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, 
the U.N. said today. 

</P>
<P>
	More Taxpayers Using E-Filing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Drawn by the promise of swifter refunds and  
reduced chances of error, Americans are warming up to electronic 
tax filing. The number of people doing their taxes on computers and 
filing electronically has shot up 156 percent compared to last 
year. But the 1.7 million returns prepared at home on computers 
through March 26 represent a tiny fraction of the total of 63.1 
million returns filed so far. Counting returns prepared by 
professionals and simple returns filed over the telephone, total 
electronic returns have reached 24 million, up more than 16 percent 
from last year, according to IRS figures released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! To Acquire Broadcast.com  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. has agreed to acquire Broadcast.com  
Inc. for $5.6 billion in stock, according to a source. 
Broadcast.com is the Internet's leading supplier of radio and video 
programs. The transaction will be announced Thursday. Yahoo! is one 
of the premier destinations on the Internet. The company's stock 
has risen 264 percent in the past 12 months. This is Yahoo!'s 
second major deal this year. The company announced the $4.58 
billion acquisition of GeoCities in January. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Pushes Web Privacy Disclosures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM announced Wednesday it plans to pull its ads  
from any Web site that doesn't state its policy on collecting and 
using information on Web users' interests, finances and spending 
habits. Most consumer advocates were encouraged by the news. IBM is 
the second-biggest advertiser in cyberspace, earmarking $60 million 
earmarked for Internet ads. But IBM's ads appear on just 780 sites 
in a World Wide Web of millions. 

</P>
<P>
	Inuits Celebrate Nunavut Territory  
</P>
<P>
	IQALUIT, Nunavut (AP) -- Inuit chefs prepared a huge feast  
Wednesday to celebrate the creation of Nunavut, Canada's newest 
territory. Stretching deep into the Arctic, with only 25,000 
residents in an area as large as Western Europe, Nunavut is the 
product of the largest land-claims settlement in Canada's history 
and gives its Inuit majority their long-sought chance at 
self-government. Nunavut is being created out of the eastern 60 
percent of the Northwest Territories, culminating more than 20 
years of lobbying by Inuit leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	David Kelley Shows Win Peabodys  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two prime-time series produced by David E.  
Kelley, Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' and ABC's ``The Practice,'' on 
Wednesday won Peabody Awards for broadcast and cable excellence. 
One-third of the 33 awards went to programs that aired on PBS 
stations or to a PBS executive. The awards, chosen from among 
nearly 1,300 entries, are administered by the University of 
Georgia's Henry W. Grady College of Journalism and Mass 
Communications. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Share Prices Advance  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rebounded Thursday morning on  
continued buying from foreign investors. The Nikkei Stock Average 
gained 265.48 points to close the morning session at 16,102.07. In 
New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,786.16 
points Wednesday, down 127.10 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Hot-Shooting Bucks Down Hornets  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Ray Allen had 20 points and Milwaukee  
shot a season-high 61 percent for a 102-94 victory over the 
Charlotte Hornets on Wednesday night. Milwaukee, which came in 
shooting an NBA-best 40 percent from 3-point range, made seven of 
14 attempts from long range. Former Charlotte guard Dell Curry, who 
had 18 points, was one of three Milwaukee players to hit two 
3-pointers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
