<DOCNO> APW19990331.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Soccer Rocker Hits Kansas City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- At the top of a hill overlooking  
Interstate 35, the goateed face of Alexi Lalas looms from a 
billboard two stories high. Next to his face, two words: ``Soccer. 
Rocker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And on the other half of the billboard, one-quarter the size of  
Lalas' face, appears the logo of Lalas' latest team, Major League 
Soccer's Kansas City Wizards. 
</P>
<P>
	If Lalas isn't bigger than the team, the red-haired defender,  
once a fixture on the U.S. national team, is clearly one of the 
biggest things to hit Kansas City in a while. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides being the nation's most recognizable soccer player,  
Lalas is a bona fide off-field celebrity -- a veteran of late-night 
television, a TV pitchman (remember the ESPN spot with Keith 
Olbermann smashing Lalas' guitar right in the middle of ``Michael, 
Row Your Boat Ashore''?) and a rock musician with his own CD. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, that's my shtick,'' he says.  
</P>
<P>
	It's an act that's playing well in Kansas City.  
</P>
<P>
	Lalas already is in line for his own radio show. The 28-year-old  
player can't go out for an evening without being approached by 
streams of fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it's gratifying when people just come up and say,  
`Welcome to town,''' said Lalas, who came to the Wizards with 
national team goalkeeper Tony Meola in an offseason trade with the 
New York-New Jersey MetroStars. ``It's never been a drag, never 
been a hassle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That kind of attention is just what the Wizards need. They  
ranked last in attendance in the 12-team MLS last year, averaging 
8,072 fans -- the only team below 10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	MLS commissioner Doug Logan has said attendance in Kansas City  
remains a concern. And critics of the trade say the Wizards really 
need someone to jump-start an offense that scored just 45 goals 
last season, second-lowest in the league. The team hasn't scored 
yet in two losses this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Which raises a question: Were Lalas and Meola -- especially Lalas  
-- brought in to draw fans or produce winning soccer? 
</P>
<P>
	``We made the trade based on their playing abilities,'' general  
manager Doug Newman said. ``The fact that they are also marquee 
names and very marketable is certainly a bonus, but we don't make 
any trades based on marquee issues. We have to put the team 
first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Meola, who could miss half the season with a knee injury,  
bristles at being cast in the role of box-office draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been saying since I got here that my major purpose is to  
win games,'' he said. ``All the other things are so secondary to 
me. If they happen, they're great. But if they don't happen, that's 
what it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Lalas, the first American to play in Italy's top league,  
says he's heard the word ``savior'' used more than once since he 
arrived -- and not because of his soccer skills. 
</P>
<P>
	He shies at characterizing himself as the solution to the  
Wizards' attendance woes, but he embraces the role of soccer 
ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's part of my responsibility,'' he said. ``I have my  
soccer goals, which are first and foremost -- but I also have goals 
off the field, and to increase attendance and awareness is one of 
my goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``As proud as I am when we win and when I do well on the field,  
I'm just as proud as when people recognize players, and come up to 
me on the street and say they're coming to the game -- because 
that's important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The chance to introduce Americans to pro soccer was the main  
reason Lalas left the Italian club Padova for MLS when the league 
formed in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing against the guys who stayed over there, but I made a  
personal choice,'' he said. ``I could have stayed over there and 
made money -- not that I'm not making money here. But this was 
something important to me, that when I was done I wouldn't just 
left something on the field but off the field, to have done 
something for the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Ron Newman likes the idea of having high-profile U.S.  
players on his roster. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me, and I screamed quite loudly three years ago,  
that it's here that the American icons should be,'' the coach said. 
``There's not enough Mexicans in this area, enough Colombians, 
enough Irish, enough Brits -- so there's not that ethnic base for 
foreign players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a good move by the league, and now Kansas City  
has to take the opportunity to make it work.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:18:29 </DATE_TIME>
