<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Look but No Deal in Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) -- Cellular phones, pagers and fax  
machines were all invented for guys like John Hart. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland general manager is a mover and shaker, and it's  
been about this time the last two years that he has decided to mix 
things up with his Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Hart pulled the string on a blockbuster deal just a  
week before the season opener, sending Kenny Lofton to the Atlanta 
Braves for Marquis Grissom and David Justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Indians were less than 48 hours away from opening  
in Seattle when Hart acquired pitcher Dave Burba from Cincinnati 
for first baseman Sean Casey. 
</P>
<P>
	Can we expect a three-peat from Hart?  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have a gaping hole on this club,'' he said Wednesday.  
``Sure, we're always looking, and if the right thing ever presents 
itself, and we can help our club, then yeah, we'll go. 
</P>
<P>
	``But right now, we've got five starters, a solid bullpen, a  
quality everyday club, nobody's hurt and a young bench. There's not 
a priority like there has been in years past that we needed to do 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uh oh. Don't think for a second Hart would let priority get in  
the way of a good deal. He loves to tinker with his ballclub and 
admits not a day passes that he isn't working the phones to see 
what other teams are doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a part of me just doing my job,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Indians' search for a bonafide No. 1 starter has linked  
several big-name, big-salaried pitchers to the Indians in recent 
months, most notably Curt Schilling, Kenny Rogers and Kevin Appier. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart wouldn't confirm reports that he has had serious  
discussions in recent days with Oakland about Rogers. The 
34-year-old went 16-8 with a 3.17 ERA for the Athletics last 
season, and would give the Indians a lefty starter for the first 
time since Greg Swindell in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's probably not a pitcher that is out there that we  
haven't talked about,'' Hart said. ``But with any pitcher, and that 
includes Rogers, we've had no more than cursory talks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers, who has also drawn interest from other teams this  
spring, has been bothered by inflammation in his left elbow and 
hasn't pitched more than three innings in any start during the 
exhibition season. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Appier, the Indians have had scouts tailing the  
right-hander around Florida for a month. Appier is trying to come 
back from arthroscopic shoulder surgery and the Indians may be 
waiting to see how he pitches during the regular season before 
talking seriously with the Royals. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not someone we're looking at right now,'' Hart said. ``I  
don't know how he'd fit at this point, considering the money and 
the players he would cost us, and the way our rotation is already 
set up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And then there's Schilling. After saying his only remaining goal  
was to pitch again in the postseason, the Philadelphia ace recently 
called the Indians ``the surest lock in baseball to get to the 
postseason. Even more than the Yankees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, though, Hart isn't dialing Philadelphia GM Ed Wade's  
area code. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't even call him anymore,'' Hart said. ``He said he's  
(Schilling) not available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't mean he won't be later this summer, especially  
if the Phillies get off to a slow start and are out of the NL 
wild-card race by the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	The only area where Hart feels the Indians are shallow is in  
their pitching depth. He's been scanning the waiver wire to pick up 
some insurance in case one of Cleveland's starters gets hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have the luxury of a Bartolo Colon of Jaret Wright  
down in Triple-A anymore,'' said Hart. 
</P>
<P>
	One name that caught his eye was Hideo Nomo, released last week  
by the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our feeling is that right now it's going to be hard to put him  
on our club. We don't think from what we've seen he's ready to step 
in and take over a starting job from anybody.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
