<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Nixes Bell Atlantic-GTE Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- State regulators said Wednesday they will  
not approve a proposed merger between telecommunications giants 
Bell Atlantic and GTE, saying they lack enough information to 
conclude the deal won't hurt consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision Wednesday to ``disapprove'' the deal is short of a  
rejection, said State Corporation Commission spokesman Ken Schrad. 
Under a disapproval, the parties can file another petition with 
more information about the impact on customers, and the SCC will 
reconsider. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents have said the merger would stifle competition, meaning  
Virginians would not see the savings that utility deregulation is 
supposed to produce. Bell Atlantic has 3.4 million phone customers 
in Virginia and GTE has 557,000. They control a combined 92 percent 
of the state's access lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're obviously very disappointed,'' said Paul Miller, a Bell  
Atlantic spokesman. ``This is not what we expected. And we intend 
to refile the application for merger as soon as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to GTE was not immediately returned.  
</P>
<P>
	The SCC decision is, for now at least, a partial roadblock to  
the proposed merger of New York-based Bell Atlantic and Stamford, 
Conn.-based GTE, the nation's largest and third-largest local phone 
service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last July, the two announced plans to merge into one company.  
The combined company, worth about $53 billion, would control 63 
million local lines in 39 states plus Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the merger to go through, it has to win approval not  
only of the Federal Communication Commission and the Justice 
Department but also from states where the companies do business. 
</P>
<P>
	To date, 28 states have either approved the merger or said they  
don't have jurisdiction to consider it. The FCC and Justice 
Department haven't yet made a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia is the first state to oppose the merger.  
</P>
<P>
	If Bell Atlantic and GTE refile their merger petition, it could  
take six months for the SCC to make another ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	If the SCC says no again but the merger wins federal approval,  
the companies could still combine as long as they kept their 
Virginia operations separate. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
