<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loss of Aircraft Cost $30M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A prototype for an unmanned reconnaissance  
aircraft crashed during a test flight, and building a replacement 
would cost $30 million, an Air Force official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Global Hawk, built by Teledyne Ryan Aeronautical of San  
Diego, is the only high-altitude, long-endurance robot plane being 
considered for use by the military, which already has unmanned 
reconnaissance aircraft that operate at lower altitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	The aircraft that crashed Monday near China Lake was the second  
of two Global Hawks to fly in a program that already has cost $280 
million since 1994, said Col. Craig McPherson, director of 
high-altitude, long-endurance unmanned air vehicles at Wright 
Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty minutes after taking from Edwards Air Force Base, the  
craft rolled into a dive from 41,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause wasn't yet known, McPherson said Tuesday. There have  
been no other accidents with the Global Hawk, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Hawks are designed to fly at altitudes up to 65,000 feet  
with an endurance of up to 40 hours. The V-tailed aircraft has a 
116-foot wingspan and is more than 44 feet long. 
</P>
<P>
	The one that crashed had been outfitted with reconnaissance  
equipment and was being readied for flights over the Nellis Air 
Force Base range in Nevada to measure its usefulness to the 
military, McPherson said. 
</P>
<P>
	No commitment has been made for production but three additional  
prototypes are being assembled. McPherson said replacing the one 
that crashed would cost $30 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
