<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect Held in Mail Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A man who was arrested in the explosion of a pipe  
bomb at a U.S. Postal Service center told authorities he had mailed 
it to a Texas televangelist. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Darwin Alexander, 53, who was arrested in Las Vegas, faces  
charges of possessing components used to make bombs after police 
searched his hotel room there, authorities said. He was held on 
$24,000 bail on eight counts of possession of bomb components with 
intent to manufacture an explosive device, Officer Steven 
Meriwether said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured when the bomb exploded Sunday at a Postal  
Service bulk mail center in Dallas, but the blast touched off a 
small fire. The package was on a conveyor belt about 30 feet above 
the floor when it blew up. 
</P>
<P>
	``The danger in a mail bomb is the projectiles,'' said Linda  
Kirksey, a U.S. Postal Service inspector. ``This type of device had 
the potential to kill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kirksey said Alexander told authorities the package was  
addressed to the Rev. John Hagee, a conservative television 
evangelist and pastor of the 17,000-member Cornerstone Church in 
San Antonio. The address on the package itself was obliterated when 
the bomb went off, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why this gentleman has done this is not clear at this time,''  
Ms. Kirksey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagee said he was cooperating with agents and other than that  
had no comment. Political figures like Oliver North and Elizabeth 
Dole have spoken from his pulpit. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators also have linked Alexander to an explosive package  
found Monday at a Greyhound bus station in Las Vegas. It was 
addressed to an agent of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and 
Firearms, said ATF Special Agent Tracy Hite. 
</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas officers said they learned of Alexander on Sunday  
after he allegedly telephoned a mental health facility, saying he 
planned to use explosives. 
</P>
<P>
	Police found him near the pay phone where he made the call,  
Meriwether said, and he let police into his room at a nearby motel. 
Meriwether described the components that investigators found in the 
motel room as pieces that could be ``readily assembled into 
bombs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The motel is across the street from the bus station. Some 200  
people in small motels and businesses in the area were evacuated 
Sunday when the materials were found in the motel room, then again 
Monday when police learned about the device at the bus station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
