<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:35:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Third Party Proposed in Phone Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Long-distance customers whose telephone  
service was illegally switched would be able to take their 
complaints to a third-party group, under an industry proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom, Sprint and associations representing smaller  
long-distance companies on Tuesday offered the proposal, which must 
be approved by the Federal Communications Commission before it 
could be implemented. 
</P>
<P>
	An industry-funded panel, including representatives of large and  
small long-distance companies and consumer groups, would be created 
to field complaints, determine liability and handle refunds. The 
FCC would approve all panel members, an AT&AMP;T official said. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel would have 30 days to determine whether an illegal  
service change occurred. If so, and a customer paid the charges, 
the offending company would have to return the total amount of 
money to the customer's original carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	That carrier would then send half of that amount to the affected  
customer in the form of a credit, the proposal states. That way, 
customers would not have to be rebilled at their normal rate and 
refund the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	If a customer was illegally switched and did not pay anything,  
they would receive the first 30 days of service free. 
</P>
<P>
	In return for supporting a third-party administrator,  
long-distance companies want to be exempted from a provision in the 
FCC's anti-slamming rules that would require companies to resolve 
disputes among themselves and pay victims the difference between 
the illegal and legal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal follows through on a suggestion by the FCC last  
year that the industry set up such a group to handle disputes over 
``slamming,'' which occurs when a person's long-distance service is 
switched without permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposal, ``consumers will almost always get a larger  
refund and in a much shorter time than under the carrier-to-carrier 
dispute resolution system outlined by the FCC,'' contends AT&AMP;T 
General Counsel Jim Cicconi. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
