<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MTV Names Chief of Online Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Longtime TV producer Fred Seibert has been  
tapped to lead MTV's new online services division. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, MTV Networks Online, was created last month in  
a bid to beef up MTV's presence in cyberspace. It groups together 
the already successful Web sites of MTV, VH1 and Nickelodeon and 
plans to create more Web destinations in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the new projects in the works call for creating a Web  
site especially for kids, with moderated chat rooms, audiovisual 
content from Nickelodeon and an online toy store, and a music 
destination with a customizable online radio feature, concert 
information and music reviews. Both are to be released later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Seibert, who was MTV's original creative director before  
founding a TV production company and running Hanna-Barbera Cartoons 
Inc., said that following MTV's audience into cyberspace was a 
natural progression for the network. 
</P>
<P>
	``MTV networks has avoided stumbling by constantly being in  
touch with its customers,'' Seibert said in an interview Tuesday. 
``As MTV put their foot in the water and got more feedback from the 
audience, we decided it was time for a full immersion in this 
media, the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the venture, MTV's parent company Viacom Inc. is joining  
other media giants like Walt Disney Co., Time Warner Inc. and Sony 
Corp. in an effort to use their music, television and movie 
materials as ways to make money online. 
</P>
<P>
	Viacom's other holdings include the Paramount movie studio and  
Spelling Entertainment, which produces hit TV shows such as 
``Melrose Place.'' It also owns the Blockbuster Video rental chain, 
the Simon &AMP; Schuster consumer book publisher and half of the UPN 
television network. 


</P>
</TEXT>
