<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors To Sentence Marine Navigator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Nine Marine Corps officers will  
determine the sentence of a Marine aviator involved in last year's 
deadly Italian cable car accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury was selected Tuesday and opening arguments were to be  
held today in the sentencing phase of Capt. Joseph Schweitzer's 
court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty Monday to obstructing justice and  
conspiracy to obstruct justice. He admitted he destroyed a 
videotape he shot before the radar-jamming jet he was navigating 
struck a ski gondola cable near Cavalese, Italy, sending 20 people 
plunging to their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer could face up to five years in prison for each  
charge, dismissal from the service, loss of pay and allowances, a 
fine, a letter of reprimand and the loss of his place on the 
promotion list. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer will be given either the sentence reached in his plea  
agreement, which has not been disclosed, or that directed by the 
jury, whichever is more lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., was charged with involuntary  
manslaughter and negligent homicide after the Feb. 3, 1998, 
accident. The charges were dropped after Capt. Richard Ashby, the 
pilot, was acquitted of manslaughter on March 4. 
</P>
<P>
	A military judge ruled that Schweitzer and Ashby could be tried  
for obstruction of justice because of the missing videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer said he swapped a tape he shot during the flight for  
a blank one after the EA-6B Prowler jet landed at the NATO air base 
in Aviano, Italy. Schweitzer said he took the tape because he 
didn't want it to be an issue in what he thought would be a probe 
only by Italian authorities. At the time, there was no Marine Corps 
criminal probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif., will be tried on  
obstruction charges next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
