<HEADLINE> Missouri Coach Stewart Might Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Missouri basketball coach Norm Stewart will  
make an announcement Thursday regarding his future, amid 
speculation that he will retire. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference is scheduled for 10:30 a.m. Thursday at the  
Hearnes Center in Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who has coached the Tigers for 32 years, declined to  
comment when reached at his home Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, 64, has 731 career wins while at Northern Iowa and  
Missouri, seventh most in NCAA history. His record at Missouri is 
634-333, including 15 NCAA tournament appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Tigers have never made the Final Four, and Missouri  
hasn't won an NCAA tournament game since 1995, when it went 20-9. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri was also 20-9 this season, finishing in a three-way tie  
for second in the Big 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers lost to New Mexico in the first round of the NCAA  
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart was the conference coach of the year five times and was  
selected the AP's national coach of the year following the 1993-94 
season. The Tigers were 28-4 that season and made it to the Elite 
Eight, where they lost to Arizona. 
</P>
