<DOCNO> APW19990331.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 10:16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Filmmakers Hope for a Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's as close to glamour as the New  
Directors/New Films festival ever gets: Madeline Kahn, dressed in a 
chic black pants suit and carrying a red umbrella, smiling and 
speaking in run-on sentences as she talked about the script of the 
zombie-like comedy ``Judy Berlin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't necessarily tell from reading it, what you, in  
effect, meant, do you mean this or that, what your turn of mind was 
beneath the words,'' Kahn told writer-director Eric Mendelsohn 
after a press screening at the Museum of Modern Art. 
</P>
<P>
	``Judy Berlin,'' one of the opening night films at this year's  
festival, also stars Edie Falco, Julie Kavner and Anne Meara. Shot 
in black and white, the film is set in a suburban community on Long 
Island, on a day when a solar eclipse drives some already spacy 
people clear into the twilight zone. 
</P>
<P>
	But established actors at this festival seem as out of place as  
the moon at noon. Now in it's 28th year, New Directors/New Films 
remains an important, perhaps last chance for low-budget films and 
little-known directors to receive exposure in the country's biggest 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gets you a lot more attention than you might usually get,''  
said Bruce Pavlow, president of Leisure Time Features, which has 
two releases -- ``The Wounds'' and ``Sitcom'' -- in this year's 
festival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like the New York Film Festival, which is a little  
more imposing,'' said John Vanco, co-president of Cowboy Booking 
International, which is distributing ``West Beirut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This festival specifically seeks out films like `West Beirut'  
and `Trans' that aren't going to play to 2,000 screens. This 
festival is about the little films that need a little help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's hopefuls include Indonesia's ``Garin Nugroho''  
(``Leaf on a Pillow''), Norway's ``Unni Straume'' (``Thrane's 
Method'') and Lebanon's ``Ziad Doueiri'' (``West Beirut''). 
American directors looking for a breakthrough include Mendelsohn, 
Julian Goldberger (``Trans'') and Michael Polish (``Twin Falls 
Idaho''). 
</P>
<P>
	Presented jointly by the Film Society of Lincoln Center and the  
film department at the Museum of Modern Art, the festival includes 
27 movies from 19 countries. Its two-week run at MOMA ends April 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	New Directors/New Films has a fine history of recognizing new  
talent. Past directors featured here include Steven Spielberg, 
Spike Lee and Wim Wenders, and among the recent films presented are 
``Buffalo 66,'' ``Smoke Signals'' and ``Living in Oblivion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as offbeat as any of the movies is the festival's definition  
of ``new.'' Many of these films have been seen at other festivals 
and only a handful of directors are actually making their debuts. 
In fact, the works of four filmmakers have been released at 
previous New Directors festivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always joke that `new' means new to us,'' said Richard  
Pena, program director at the Lincoln Center society. ``When it 
comes to a second film here, basically, our motto is that if we 
like the film and it's going to help the film, we want to help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Here are festival highlights (x-denotes that the film has a U.S.  
distributor). 
</P>
<P>
	--''TRANS'': Ryan Kazinski is an escapee from a Florida juvenile  
detention center. He is free -- free to carry a gun, debate the 
meaning of corn and be chased in a Laundromat. He also dances with 
an old man, gets beat up in a parking lot and learns a truly 
disgusting method for catching wild hogs. Mostly, he runs and runs. 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't matter whether writer-director Julian Goldberger has  
actually lived through all this or just knows people who have. Like 
no U.S. director in years, he seems to know what it means to light 
out for the territory, even if the territory is Fort Myers. This is 
a major debut feature, a Great American Film in search of a Great 
American Distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	--''THRANE'S METHOD'': Thrane is a moody, middle-aged bachelor,  
searching for faith and in fear of temptation. His neighbor, Mol, 
is a short-haired beauty with a conveniently absent husband. The 
film starts out so dry it almost crumbles in your hands, but it 
turns into a tense, graceful dance, as the camera makes love to Mol 
in ways Thrane is too mixed up to try. For the viewer, Mol becomes 
a total object of desire. Expect, and hope, to hear more from 
Norwegian director-writer Unni Straume, and from the lead actress, 
Petronella Baker. 
</P>
<P>
	--x-''WEST BEIRUT'': A coming of age film set during a civil war.  
Or is it a civil war set during a coming of age film? Ziad 
Doueiri's wise debut takes place in Beirut, in 1975, where a 
smirking teen-ager is gradually worn down to tears. This 
Arabic-language film is the reverse of ``Saving Private Ryan.'' The 
latter showed you the war but not how it changes people. The former 
limits the gunfire, but reveals the real damage. Not only that, 
``West Beirut'' has the nerve to be funny. ``Blow my fuses,'' a 
woman of a certain size urges her husband. ``Trim my circuits. Show 
me the stars, you stallion!'' (Or at least that's what the 
subtitles said). 
</P>
<P>
	--''OF FREAKS AND MEN'': Alexei Balabanov's vintage-looking drama  
begins with a montage of tinted, turn of the century photographs. 
The subject matter: The various ways to spank a woman's bare 
bottom. The subjects: the wife and daughter of a Russian 
aristocrat, who innocently predicts that the moving image will 
change the world. It will certainly change his. 
</P>
<P>
	The pace needs to be quicker, but this is still a disturbing --  
and beautifully shot -- movie about the minds behind the camera, in 
the tradition of ``sex, lies and videotape'' and Michael Powell's 
``Peeping Tom.'' It's one of those pictures in which audience 
members get up at the end and smile nervously at each other. 
</P>
<P>
	--x-''FOLLOWING'': ``Of Freaks and Men'' imagines the artist as  
pornographer. This promising British film raises (or lowers?) the 
charge to breaking and entering. A young writer follows would-be 
subjects around London, only to have one confront him and bring him 
along for some real ``interruptions'' of people's lives. 
``Following'' is written, directed and photographed by Christopher 
Nolan, who seems to have read, watched and listened to every crime 
story ever told. 
</P>
<P>
	--''ORPHANS'': Anyone lucky enough to have seen Ken Loach's ``My  
Name Is Joe'' will remember the lead actor, Peter Mullan, who has 
the cool, sharp looks and sympathetic style of a young Paul Newman. 
Turns out, like Newman, that Mullan directs films, too. ``Orphans'' 
is his debut feature, the story of four Scottish siblings who 
nearly lose their minds (and their lives) after their mother dies. 
This is an actor's movie, with dollops of dialogue, arm-waving and 
four-letter words. But it's also a moviegoer's movie, with real 
graveyard humor. Questioned about his capacity to act as sole 
pallbearer, the eldest son responds: ``She ain't heavy, she's my 
mother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--''LEAF ON A PILLOW'': Directed by Garin Nugroho, an acclaimed  
young Indonesian film maker, ``Leaf on a Pillow'' gets to you 
because of the tale rather than the telling. It's based on real 
events in the slums of Jakarta, where kids sniff glue, pierce their 
bodies and sleep in the streets. There's nothing memorable about 
the camera work or the script, but you respond. You respond like a 
tourist, checking out the clothes, the food, the faces, and you 
respond as a witness, rooting and fearing for the kids, admiring 
the man who cared enough to make a movie about them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
