<DOCNO> APW19990331.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disinfectant Fabric Developed / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- Imagine a cotton T-shirt that breaks down  
pesticides into harmless particles immediately on contact or a pair 
of denim jeans that disinfects itself when it touches germs or 
viruses. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not far off, says a University of California, Davis  
researcher. 
</P>
<P>
	In what could be a breakthrough for people working everywhere  
from farms to hospitals, UC Davis scientist Gang Sun thinks his 
chemically-treated fabrics could change the way people wear their 
work clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun's work involves the use of one of the most common  
disinfectants people use in their homes: chlorine. 
</P>
<P>
	His research is based on a chemical called hydantoin, which  
grabs chlorine molecules and holds them. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun says the process would graft hydantoin onto cotton fabrics  
and immerse the fabric in chlorine bleach. When the fabric comes in 
contact with certain pesticides, virus or bacteria, the chlorine is 
released, disinfecting the cloth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were surprised how quickly and powerfully it killed the  
germs,'' said Sun, whose research gained attention at a recent 
chemical conference in Southern California. ``The main purpose 
would be for hospitals -- doctors' uniforms, bedding materials -- you 
can even use it in hotels for bed sheets and towels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The technology also can be used by farm workers who constantly  
come in contact with low levels of pesticides. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun's research showed his treated fabric can break down some  
agricultural pesticides known as carbamates into small, harmless 
fragments. 
</P>
<P>
	The breathable cotton clothes would be an improvement over  
impermeable clothing sometimes worn by farm workers who often work 
under the summer's intense sun. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not saying that it'll replace impermeable clothing  
during heavy spraying, but when the farm worker enters the field 
for harvesting, there's still pesticide residue in the field,'' Sun 
said. ``We can use our regular clothing like T-shirts and jeans and 
we can treat them. The worker will not notice any difference, but 
have additional protection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The research is still under investigation as Sun continues  
testing his cloth with more pesticides and germs. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-based Halosource Corp. purchased the licensing rights to  
Sun's chemical technology last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Williams, Halosource's chief scientific officer, said that  
although the treatment would make clothes more expensive, they 
would be competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're also looking at odor control, which comes from bacteria,  
fungus or mildew,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 10:25:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Takes Over Yugoslav Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State Department and Secret Service agents  
early Wednesday took over Yugoslavia's embassy buildings here, 
evicting the country's remaining diplomats. 
</P>
<P>
	An hour after the midnight deadline the United States had given  
Yugoslavia to vacate its embassy and chancery, officers arrived to 
clear and secure both buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Secret Service spokesman John Tomlinson said several people  
still in the buildings left when told to by officers, who met no 
resistance. A group of people were seen leaving the chancery in 
night clothes after the federal officers took over. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia announced Thursday it was breaking diplomatic  
relations with the United States because of the NATO attack on the 
country. Ties also were broken with Britain, France and Germany 
because of their participation in ``armed aggression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States closed its embassy in Belgrade last weekend  
and had evacuated remaining diplomats prior to NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	With neighboring streets blocked, officials first took  
possession of the Yugoslav chancery and then the ambassador's 
residence, both located just off Washington's main embassy row on 
Massachusetts Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States will respect and protect the properties  
without prejudice to the eventual settlement of property issues 
among all the successor states to the former Yugoslavia,'' said a 
statement by Lee McClenny, a State Department spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past seven years, the nations of the former Yugoslav  
union -- Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia, Macedonia and today's rump 
Yugoslavia, consisting of Serbia and Montenegro -- have been locked 
in a dispute over how to divide the assets left by the Yugoslav 
federation when it dissolved in 1991-92. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia has insisted that it is the sole successor state and has  
refused to turn over diplomatic missions, joint funds, or archives 
it controlled. With Wednesday's takeover, the government of 
Yugoslav will effectively lose control over the two properties in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department's Office of Foreign Missions coordinated  
the takeover, which officials said is routine when diplomatic ties 
are broken. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first days of the NATO attack, which began a week ago,  
Yugoslav diplomats tried to maintain a business-as-usual atmosphere 
in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Countries without diplomatic relations with the U.S. government  
frequently maintain offices in Washington under the jurisdiction of 
a third country's embassy. Cuba, for instance, operates under the 
umbrella of the Swiss embassy, while the Iraqi interest section is 
part of the Algerian embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	Milena Radovic, a spokeswoman for Yugoslavia's mission to the  
United Nations in New York, said Yugoslavia is looking for a 
similar arrangement but has yet to find a country that would host 
its interest section. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
