<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Passover Holiday Marked Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- With a last-minute flurry of cleaning and  
shopping, Israelis prepared today to usher in the holiday of 
Passover, when Jews the world over mark the exodus of the ancient 
Israelites from slavery in Egypt. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours before the holiday's start at sundown, outdoor Israeli  
markets were crowded with people buying key ingredients for the 
festive multi-course meal, or seder, during which the story of the 
Israelites' flight from Egypt is ritually recounted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this holiday,'' said Yedid Moshe, 61, buying celery,  
mint and tomatoes at Jerusalem's open-air Mahane Yehuda market, 
whose overflowing stalls of fruit, vegetables and flowers were 
watched by patrolling Israeli soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the strictly religious Jerusalem neighborhood of Mea Shearim,  
ultra-Orthodox Jews in black coats and hats used blowtorches and 
boiling water Tuesday to sterilize kitchen utensils. 
</P>
<P>
	Housewives hurried to complete exhaustive pre-Passover cleaning,  
which calls for ridding homes of each and every crumb of bread. 
That is in line with the traditional ban on leavened food items 
during the weeklong holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The biblical story of the Exodus says the Israelites had to move  
fast and did not have time to let bread dough rise, so they ate 
flat unleavened bread as they fled into the desert. During 
Passover, observant Jews steer clear of any product made with 
yeast, including items like beer and pasta. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the majority of Israeli Jews do not follow the strict  
Orthodox way of life, most dive into the Passover cleaning as if 
they did. By tradition, women clean floors, rugs, windows, curtains 
and furniture, while men check the entire house with a lit candle. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before this year's holiday, a government workers' strike  
left garbage piling up on the streets. The strike ended Monday, and 
garbage collectors worked overtime to try to rid the country of the 
piles of trash, lest people inadvertently track bread crumbs back 
into a Passover-ready house. 
</P>
<P>
	In Israel, sale of products deemed suitable for Passover use has  
expanded into an entire industry. Even specific brands of lipstick, 
toothpicks and soap are designated as Passover-appropriate, though 
rabbis say there is no religious reason for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Some, like Conservative Rabbi David Golinkin, wonder whether the  
real significance of the holiday may get lost amid rules and 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``People do tend to get carried away with the minutiae of  
preparing'' for Passover, Golinkin said. ``It's important to 
remember the meaning behind the ritual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of trying to clean up bread crumbs to a rabbi's  
specifications and change their menus to eliminate what would 
otherwise be ordinary ingredients, many Israeli restaurants simply 
close during Passover. 
</P>
<P>
	Some families take the same route, locking their doors behind  
them and spending Passover at a hotel. Tens of thousands of 
Israelis flock to holiday destinations. 
</P>
<P>
	Tradition has its perils. Each year, Israeli ambulance services  
are called on to treat hundreds of people who get matza -- the thin 
unleavened wafer eaten instead of bread -- or bones from gefilte 
fish, another Passover favorite, caught in their throats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
