<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital, HMO Resolve Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Humana Inc., Florida's largest HMO, and hospital  
chain Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. reached a deal late Wednesday 
to continue providing care to thousands of Floridians. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the two-year contract, which is effective April 1, were  
not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1.3 million Humana members in Florida were in danger  
of losing coverage for using the 56 Columbia/HCA hospitals in the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the nation, disputes between health care providers and  
HMOs have become more frequent in recent years as the companies 
battle over money and control of patient care, leaving patients 
caught in a high-stakes tug-of-war. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, hospitals have given managed care organizations large  
discounts for treating their patients, hoping to recoup the losses 
by treating more patients. 
</P>
<P>
	But with hospital profits falling due to big Medicare cuts this  
year and hospitals increasingly accusing health plans of failing to 
make prompt payments, hospitals are rethinking their HMO strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	Nashville, Tenn.-based Columbia, beleaguered by a federal  
billing fraud investigation and sagging profits, says it is taking 
another look at all its HMO contracts in an effort to boost its 
bottom line. For much of the past decade, Columbia would work with 
virtually all HMOs, hoping to build business, but officials say 
that may be changing. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia is not alone in the review.  
</P>
<P>
	``Each of our hospitals is now weighing every one of these  
contracts,'' said Bill Bell, a vice president with the Florida 
Hospital Association. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, Columbia dominates so many major markets that health  
insurers have little choice but to contract with them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Practically speaking, a contract with Columbia is almost a  
requirement,'' in most Florida markets,'' said Ryan Siemers, a 
consultant with William M. Mercer in Tampa. He said Humana risks 
alienating its members by losing the Columbia contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as HMOs have boosted premiums between 5 to 10 percent  
in the past year, hospitals feel they should benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	The old contract between Columbia and Humana expired Dec. 31.  
The two sides then agreed to a 90-day grace period, which was set 
to expire March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute wasn't the first time Columbia and Humana have  
battled. Last year, Humana filed for an injunction alleging that 
Columbia has refused hospital care to Humana members at least 27 
times. Columbia denied the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Columbia's own legal problems continue to mount. This  
week, Columbia said the Securities and Exchange Commission was 
investigating it for insider trading. Columbia officials said it is 
not unusual for the SEC to investigate a company whose stock has 
fallen sharply, as Columbia's did when the billing fraud 
allegations surfaced. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
