<DOCNO> APW19990331.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 10:16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Goldwyn Tries Out Directing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For Tony Goldwyn, falling in love with the  
screenplay for ``A Walk on the Moon'' was the easy part. Much 
harder was figuring out what to do next. 
</P>
<P>
	He's an actor, so was there a meaty part for him? ``I tried hard  
to fit myself in, but I just didn't feel like I could act in it,'' 
says Goldwyn, wistfully. 
</P>
<P>
	What about producing? After all, his pedigree is impressive:  
Tony's grandfather was the mighty Samuel Goldwyn, whose name still 
hangs above the roaring lion at the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer studios. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounded good, except he'd never produced before. And it was soon  
clear he wouldn't do it alone: Dustin Hoffman, also smitten by the 
script, had signaled interest in producing. And who refuses Dustin 
Hoffman? 
</P>
<P>
	That left only ... what? Directing? Trouble was, Goldwyn was a  
novice here, too. Plus, he would be making his feature-film debut 
with a tricky story about a rocky marriage set in the summer of 
1969. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to direct,'' says Goldwyn. ``I had no intention  
of directing a film. What I wanted to do was expand my horizons as 
an actor and start to produce material that I was involved with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, alas, he was in love.  
</P>
<P>
	``I found I couldn't give it away to somebody else because I had  
such strong feelings about what needed to happen with the 
material,'' he says. ``So then the natural next step was, I said, 
'Do it yourself.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But how exactly would he go about it? Goldwyn, ever the actor,  
soon hit upon an ingenious tactic: He devised a character in his 
mind of the kind of director for whom he had always wanted to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he simply played him.  
</P>
<P>
	``To approach the same process and environment from a completely  
different way was so much fun,'' he says. ``It's like wearing 
someone else's clothes. I felt like a total impostor. I would even 
forget to say, 'Action!' and 'Cut!''' 
</P>
<P>
	Impostor or not, the gamble seems to have paid off, at least  
judging from the warm response to ``A Walk on the Moon'' at the 
Sundance Film Festival in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldwyn was looking for his next acting project when he stumbled  
on Pamela Gray's script, which happened to have won the Samuel 
Goldwyn Screenwriting Award at the University of Southern 
California at Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie tells of a married woman who has a very public affair  
with a blouse salesman in the Catskills, the upstate New York 
countryside where large numbers of Jews from the city used to spend 
their summer holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray had spent all her summers in the late 1960s in the  
Catskills, and recalled passing the time with wives whose husbands 
were away at work during the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Goldwyn had grown up in Los Angeles, he would often  
visit his family in New York and was aware of the Catskills 
culture. He was 9 at the time of the rock concert in Woodstock, 
which is in the Catskills area and is the scene of much of the 
action in the movie, which also touches upon the U.S. space 
program, the war in Vietnam and early seeds of the women's 
movement. The title is drawn from Neil Armstrong's moon walk, an 
important event in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	What interested Goldwyn, he says, was the story of someone  
``waking up in the morning, and saying, 'Is my life what I dreamed 
it would be?' and, 'Do I have the right to have that expectation at 
all?''' 
</P>
<P>
	He says he identified with the idea as a man but wanted to  
explore it from a woman's point of view. 
</P>
<P>
	Now 39, Goldwyn's career suddenly has a crisp new focus after  
years of quiet success on stage and brief movie appearances in, 
among others, ``Ghost,'' ``The Pelican Brief'' and ``Kiss the 
Girls.'' he played Richard Nixon's brother in Oliver Stone's 
presidential biopic, and astronaut Neil Armstrong in HBO's ``From 
the Earth to the Moon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt that I wasn't achieving my potential in the film roles  
I was getting,'' he says. ``So I said, 'Hmmm, I've got to figure 
out a way to make this more fulfilling.' Directing became that 
role. Then it all made sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Being an actor himself paid off with his actors, he says. ``We  
had a shorthand. They knew that I'd been through what they were 
going through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Too much so, perhaps, jokes Diane Lane, who stars as a  
straight-laced housewife tempted by freedom in the Age of Aquarius. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes he would get so in my face, he would be experiencing  
the emotions himself. I would have to say, 'O.K., this is MY line 
and you stay over THERE!''' Lane says, laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would be trembling with tears in his eyes, he would get all  
caught up in it. I would say, 'Got it! Now put me in front of the 
camera already!''' 
</P>
<P>
	Born into the Goldwyn dynasty, Tony grew up in the posh suburbs  
of Los Angeles, the son of producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and actress 
Jennifer Howard. Grandpa Goldwyn, one of Hollywood's founding 
fathers, was the producer behind such classics as ``Guys and 
Dolls,'' ``The Secret Life of Walter Mitty'' and ``Wuthering 
Heights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tony recalls Saturday afternoons in his boyhood gabbing with his  
grandfather after he had his second stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a guy who had, at 16 years old, made his way from  
Poland to America. He landed on a boat in Canada and literally 
walked to New York City! This was one tough, determined dude,'' 
says Goldwyn. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was sitting in his wheelchair and we were talking. All of a  
sudden, he begins shaking. He's trying to lift himself up and tears 
are streaming out of his eyes. And I go, 'Grandpa, what are you 
doing?' And I start hugging him, to try and calm him down. He was 
so frustrated that he couldn't get out of the chair. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember, as a 10-year-old kid, trying to give this guy  
advice: 'Look at what you've done in your life!' I said to him. 
'It's time to relax! It's time to sit back and smell the 
flowers!''' 
</P>
<P>
	``It had a huge impact on him. He told everybody about it, that  
this little kid made him feel better!'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time he decided to be an actor, Tony discovered that  
extending the Goldwyn name into a third generation of Hollywood 
fame wasn't going to be easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Starting out as an actor, it was horrible -- having a famous  
last name and having a family in the business,'' he says. ``When I 
started applying for work in film and television, it was very, very 
tough, because people tend to write you off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he has kept detractors off-base with his eclectic mix of  
projects, including his latest -- voicing the title role of the 
upcoming animated feature ``Tarzan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with ``A Walk on the Moon,'' he's survived a different type  
of adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I loved it,'' he says. ``I felt like I was on a great water  
slide.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:35:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Reaches Efficiency Milestone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A Boeing Co. efficiency program with a name that  
could cure insomnia has reached another milestone toward proving 
its potency. 
</P>
<P>
	This month 8,000 employees -- chiefly engineers -- were brought  
into a new, streamlined system for designing and building 
airplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	That brings the total to 38,000 workers in eight states, Canada  
and Australia with access to four interconnected computer systems 
that are replacing more than 450 separate and sometimes 
incompatible networks in Boeing Commercial Airplane Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Material from one computer system sometimes had to be printed  
out for reinput into another, and even top managers had access only 
to some of the systems, said Garnet Hizzey, deputy director of the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest change should cut the time required for design and  
production of airplane parts by roughly 75 percent, Hizzey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cristina McHugh, a company spokeswoman, said no jobs are in  
jeopardy from the program: Define and Control Airplane 
Configuration-Manufacturing Resource Management, or DCAC-MRM. 
</P>
<P>
	``These initiatives are for eliminating waste, not people,'' she  
said. ``Hopefully, they'll be effective in reducing costs and make 
our jobs more secure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first seven phases of the overhaul, which began in February  
1996, covered production workers who built parts and assemblies. 
</P>
<P>
	This phase covers engineers who design parts. The next phase  
covers engineers who make design drawings for parts in basic 
assemblies and more complex installations, and the last two phases 
are for production workers in Boeing airplane factories in Everett, 
Renton and Long Beach, Calif. Completion is scheduled for the first 
quarter of 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent change covers parts as simple as a bracket for  
an overhead panel in a 747 jumbojet, speeding the arrival of the 
product definition and specifications into the factory. 
</P>
<P>
	With the new system, that bracket can now be in the hands of  
assembly crews within 20 days after the need for it is determined, 
compared with 80 days under the old system, Hizzey said. 
</P>
<P>
	For a rush order, it might be five days instead of 20.  
</P>
<P>
	Even parts as basic as brackets frequently are redesigned to  
satisfy airline demands for custom interior cabins, Hizzey 
explained. 
</P>
<P>
	One goal of the program is to make information on each  
custom-made part, component and assembly more widely available so 
more can be reused, rather than redesigned each time a request is 
made, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We endeavor to use as many common parts as possible,'' he  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	With more standardized assembly, Hizzey said, ``we could pump  
out airplanes like beer cans.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:37:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Win Tightens Ratings Race / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Futurama'' may really have a future.  
</P>
<P>
	The new animated comedy from Matt Groening, creator of ``The  
Simpsons,'' scored solid ratings Sunday during an encouraging week 
for new shows. The Fox cartoon set in the year 3000 tied for 11th 
place in the Nielsen Media Research ratings last week -- 
outdistancing even ``The Simpsons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC won the week's prime-time competition with a 9.0 rating and  
15 share, tightening its race with CBS for the season's top spot by 
doing well on Tuesday and Wednesday nights, not normally its 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS was second with an 8.7 rating and 15 share, ABC had a 7.0  
rating and 12 share and Fox was at 6.5 and 11. The WB had a 3.0 
rating and 5 share, UPN was at 1.8 and 3 and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not as impressive as ``Futurama,'' two new ABC comedies  
also had strong weeks. ``The Norm Show,'' the new comedy starring 
Norm McDonald, finished in 20th place and ``It's Like, You Know'' 
came in 33rd. 
</P>
<P>
	``ER'' was the week's most-watched show, as it has been for each  
of the 17 original episodes this year. However, it had the lowest 
rating for an ``ER'' original since 1994, perhaps an indication 
viewers are confused by the midseason reruns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nickelodeon cable network celebrated a Nielsen milestone --  
with milk and cookies, of course. It was the top-rated cable 
network, on an all-day basis, for the first three months of the 
year, Nielsen said Tuesday. It is Nick's 14th straight quarterly 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, Fox News Channel defeated its rival MSNBC in  
the prime-time quarterly ratings. Fox's average prime-time audience 
has increased from 79,000 households in early 1998 to 223,000 
households this year. MSNBC's prime-time average was 201,000 
households. Both news networks trailed CNN, whose ratings were 
slightly down at 747,000 households. 
</P>
<P>
	MSNBC points out that it leads during all-day ratings, and has  
seen more of a boost than Fox over the past week in ratings because 
of the Yugoslavian bombings. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Nightly News'' and ABC's ``World News Tonight'' finished  
in a dead heat in last week's evening news race with 8.2 ratings 
and 17 shares. The ``CBS Evening News'' had a 7.0 rating and 15 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC won for the quarter in nightly news. All three networks had  
lower ratings than last year, however. CBS's slip was the steepest. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of March 22-28, the top 10 shows, their networks  
and ratings were ``ER,'' NBC, 18.6; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 16.2; ``60 
Minutes,'' CBS, 14.3; ``Friends,'' NBC, 14.1; ``Touched By an 
Angel,'' CBS, 13.7, ``Veronica's Closet,'' NBC, 13.4; ``Jesse,'' 
NBC, 12.9; ``Dateline NBC-Tuesday,'' NBC, 12.1; ``CBS Sunday Movie: 
Holy Joe,'' CBS, 11.3; ``Law and Order,'' NBC, 11.3. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 14:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Rail Disruptions Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Railroad disruptions are inevitable following  
the June 1 split of Conrail, but their impact is likely to be 
minor, the head of one of Conrail's new owners said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Snow, chairman and chief executive officer of CSX Corp.,  
said slowdowns will occur in the first several hours of the 
transition as computers are shut down and reprogrammed, forcing a 
temporary shift to manual operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The $10.3 billion takeover of Conrail by CSX and Norfolk  
Southern Corp. has come under scrutiny in light of a major service 
meltdown that followed the 1996 merger of Union Pacific Railroad 
with Southern Pacific Rail Corp. in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow likened the adverse effects from the computer shutdown and  
other, unforeseen problems to those of ``a freak ice storm that 
slows the railroads for a little while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We work out of those in a few days,'' he told reporters. ``We  
just don't see anything that is going to create a ... replay of the 
Western sorts of problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Union Pacific gridlock lasted several months and caused  
major delivery delays. It spawned several lawsuits by shippers and 
a drive in Congress to give federal regulators more oversight over 
the rail industry, something rail companies believe would hinder 
their ability to invest and grow. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Conrail takeover date approaches, rail executives are  
seeking to play down the significance of any problems by suggesting 
that disruptions are inevitable. At the same time, they seek to 
bolster confidence among shippers by stressing lessons learned from 
the Union Pacific disruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	CSX will keep most of the Conrail management teams in place and  
will test its computer networks to make sure the computers from the 
various railroads can to talk to one another after the split, Snow 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the company also has increased its workforce and  
locomotive holdings to limit the impact of any problems. That, he 
said, came at considerable expense to the company, whose earnings 
and incomes dropped in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect things will go bump in the night, so we have  
contingencies ... and more assets and people than you really 
need,'' he said. ``Will there be some difficulties? Yes. You have 
to anticipate some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, approved by the federal Surface Transportation Board  
last summer, is the most complex and most extensive rail 
transaction in U.S. history, covering nearly 45,000 miles of tracks 
among the three railroads. 
</P>
<P>
	Although each company is spending $1 million a day on interest  
payments, executives have proceeded cautiously toward reaping the 
benefits of the deal in order to avoid repeating the Union Pacific 
mishaps. The companies could have implemented the deal as early as 
last August. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we fail, there's no doubt about the fact that we will set  
railroading back a long way and will invite enormous government 
attention,'' Snow said. 
</P>
<P>
	The restructuring will introduce competition to several  
Northeastern markets for the first time since 1976, when 
Philadelphia-based Conrail began operating as a monopoly that 
Congress created out of six bankrupt railroads. CSX operates out of 
Richmond, Va., and Norfolk Southern is based in Norfolk, Va. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
