<DOCNO> APW19990331.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 02:24:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jenny Jones' Civil Trial To Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A waitress, a machinist, a retiree and a  
decorator are among the jury members chosen to hear a $50 million 
lawsuit filed against ``The Jenny Jones Show'' over a guest's 
shooting death. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening statements were to begin today.  
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed by the family of Scott Amedure, 32. He was  
killed three days after after taping a 1995 episode of the show in 
which he revealed he had a crush on a heterosexual friend, Jonathan 
Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was found guilty of second-degree murder in 1996, but  
the conviction was overturned last fall due to an error in jury 
selection. His retrial is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure's family contends the show's producers lied to Schmitz  
about the gender of his admirer, disregarded warnings about the 
dangers of surprising guests and had no concern about Schmitz's 
mental state. The suit names the show, distributor Warner Bros. and 
producer Telepictures Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Warner Bros. have said they will present testimony  
to show Schmitz was never lied to and repeatedly was told his 
secret admirer might be a man or woman. Lawyers have indicated they 
also will argue that the show's responsibility ended when the two 
men walked out of the studio. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is listed as a witness in the case, and defense attorney  
Jim Feeney said it was likely she would testify early next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine jury members were selected Tuesday. Six will consider a  
verdict and the other three will be designated alternates at the 
end of the trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bayer Boosts Investment in U.S. R&AMP;D </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Bayer Corp., the U.S. subsidiary of  
Germany-based Bayer Group, said Wednesday it would add $6 billion 
through 2004 to research and development and capital spending for 
its U.S. operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The additional investment would bring to $15 billion the total  
the company is investing in developing U.S. businesses since 
announcing a $9 billion investment in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending is part of a major effort to increasing Bayer's  
share of the North American consumer market, said Helge H. 
Wehmeier, president and chief executive of the Pittsburgh-based 
Bayer Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayer believes it can grab more of the U.S. market for consumer  
drugs, medical diagnostic equipment and chemicals, but that it is 
not likely to grow much in Europe, Wehmeier said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that raw materials and energy cost less in the United  
States. Low inflation, exporting ease and access to top-shelf 
biotech research talent also influenced the added U.S. investment, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boost in U.S. investment does not immediately translate into  
new jobs for Bayer Corp., which employs 23,400 people at 50 
manufacturing and research sites in the United States, Wehmeier 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wehmeier said the company's marketing plan emphasizes the  
effects on people rather than the ingredients, hoping consumers 
will care more about what a compound will do for them than what it 
is made of. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Bayer said in 1995 it would invest $9 billion on growing  
its U.S. businesses through 2000, the company has spent $5.7 
billion, leaving more than $9 billion left to spend through 2004 
with the new investment announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Of that $9 billion, Bayer intends to spend $5.1 billion in the  
next five years in research and development on its life sciences 
businesses -- consumer care, pharmaceuticals, diagnostics -- and $3 
billion on capital investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
