<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Denies Victim Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT, N.C. (AP) -- By any measure, Sylvia Cassidy was a  
victim, shot in the head by the man she lived with because she 
wouldn't tag along to the local mall. 
</P>
<P>
	But her family has been denied victim's compensation for funeral  
expenses because the 24-year-old woman, in death, is considered a 
lawbreaker. By living with her killer, she violated a 194-year-old 
statute against cohabitation. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a victim from top to bottom, and now the state comes  
along and says she was a criminal,'' says her mother, Diana 
Zambory. She is appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Victims Compensation Fund Commission has no choice,  
says director Gary Eichelberger. North Carolina law requires a 
claim be rejected if the victim was participating in a felony or 
nontraffic misdemeanor, even ``fishing without a license,'' he 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wrestle with this every time we get a claim like this,  
especially when the victim is otherwise innocent,'' Eichelberger 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	All states offer some form of victims' compensation for medical  
bills, lost work, funeral expenses or other financial losses. Most 
bar payments if criminal activity by the victims contributed to 
their injuries or deaths. At least two, Ohio and Arkansas, deny 
claims if victims committed crimes in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	But a 50-state survey by The Associated Press found North  
Carolina the only state with laws banning adultery, fornication or 
cohabitation to cite those crimes as reasons to withhold 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina toughened its compensation law in 1994 after a  
judge ruled that a man who was shot and paralyzed while committing 
a robbery was entitled to victim's benefits upon parole. Through 
June 30, 1998, the state commission has denied 47 claims on the 
basis of cohabitation alone, Eichelberger says. 
</P>
<P>
	One came from a Greenville woman and her fiance, who were  
attacked and beaten while walking their dog one night in February 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only problem I see with this victim is that she was living  
with her fiance and they were not married,'' an investigator wrote 
Jan. 20. ``They still live together and are not married. I 
recommend denial -- criminal activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another dealt with a man shot 14 times and killed by his  
girlfriend. ``Although an unfortunate situation,'' an investigator 
wrote in December 1997, ``because victim and suspect were live-in 
girlfriend and boyfriend, recommendation is to deny for criminal 
activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 47 cases denied are a small portion of all cases considered.  
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, for example, the commission distributed 
almost $3.7 million among 914 cases and denied 771. 
</P>
<P>
	But they stand out because they seem so unfair, says Joe  
Stewart, spokesman for the state agency that oversees the victims 
commission. Furthermore, he says, 39 of the rejected cases involved 
domestic violence victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the most vulnerable -- physically, psychologically and  
economically -- are denied their claim because of this quirk in the 
law that we are seeking to change,'' Stewart says. The Legislature 
is considering a measure to allow more leeway in considering claims 
from victims who have committed misdemeanors. 
</P>
<P>
	Compensation rules on crimes are not intended to judge morality  
but to protect boards from compensating real criminals, says David 
Beatty of the National Center for Victims of Crime in Arlington, 
Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``If two guys are involved in a shootout over a drug deal gone  
bad,'' Beatty says, ``the one with the poorer shot shouldn't be 
rewarded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio has one of the nation's toughest laws. It denies  
compensation if crime victims committed a felony within the prior 
10 years, even if the felony has no connection to their injury. One 
claim involving a violent crime was denied because the victim had 
written bad checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, Arkansas rejects claims if victims were previously  
convicted of crimes in which they injured another person. 
</P>
<P>
	Most states, however, consider claims on a case-by-case basis.  
And even those that outlaw adultery, fornication or cohabitation 
say those crimes would not affect decisions on victims' benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``A woman committing adultery should not expect to be beaten  
up,'' says Everett Mayhew Jr. of the New York State Crime Victims 
Board. ``It has to be conduct that contributes to the injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Promiscuous behavior ``is not a standard that the state of  
Wisconsin has attempted to impose on crime victims,'' says James 
Haney of the state Justice Department. ``They have a tough enough 
road as it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adultery is a crime, but ``having a relationship with someone  
other than a spouse would not be an automatic disqualifier,'' Haney 
says. ``People may not approve of the fact that she is having that 
relationship, but that does not make her any less the victim of a 
crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina's cohabitation law is rarely enforced, and Sylvia  
Cassidy's living arrangement with Marcquan McMillian provoked no 
official concern until Mrs. Zambory filed for compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassidy's cremation and flowers cost $1,750. Her mother seeks an  
additional $2,000 to clear private land and get it properly deeded 
to allow burial of the ashes. 
</P>
<P>
	She acknowledges her daughter had a messy personal life.  
</P>
<P>
	By age 21, Cassidy had three sons with a man she never married.  
She gave the father custody of the two older boys when she married 
a second man. In late 1997, she angered her husband by telling 
police he was breaking into houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after, McMillian showed up at her rented trailer.  
</P>
<P>
	A friend of her husband and the brother of an old boyfriend,  
McMillian offered to protect her from her husband, who was 
threatening to kill her and her youngest son, according to Mrs. 
Zambory. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassidy let him move in because ``Marcquan was the only one (her  
husband) was scared of,'' Mrs. Zambory says. 
</P>
<P>
	McMillian moved in Dec. 3, 1997, and promptly invited others,  
including a brother, the brother's girlfriend and at least one 
other woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Their relationship was stormy from the beginning. The sheriff  
reported several occasions in which the two were ``involved in some 
serious domestic differences.'' At McMillian's trial, one of 
Cassidy's sons and a former girlfriend of the defendant testified 
they had seen McMillian point a gun at Cassidy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 28, 1998, Cassidy and McMillian were arguing about going  
to the mall. A friend tried to persuade Cassidy to leave with him. 
She declined, saying she was moving to her mother's home and had 
already packed two bags. 
</P>
<P>
	McMillian shot Cassidy over her right eye from two feet away. He  
was convicted March 6 of voluntary manslaughter and sentenced to 
five to seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Zambory wears two small charms her daughter had locked away  
from McMillian and his associates -- a tiny cow and a Dallas Cowboys 
helmet. She has little else. She keeps her daughter's ashes in a 
metal box atop a stereo stand, watched over by a wax angel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I asked for was enough to bury her, $2,000 to  
get a place cleared,'' Mrs. Zambory says. ``That's all we need. I 
didn't think it was a very big thing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
