<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi To Cut 14,500 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Mitsubishi Electric Corp. plans to reduce  
its work force by 14,500, or about 10 percent, over the next three 
years to improve its group profitability. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi had already planned to decrease its workforce by  
2,600 people this year. It will slash 8,400 jobs in Japan by the 
end of March 2002 and cut 6,100 jobs at overseas subsidiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, one of Japan's largest consolidated electronics  
manufacturers, makes everything from semiconductors to nuclear 
power plants. Mitsubishi currently employs 146,000 people 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement today came on the last day of the fiscal year  
and is the latest in a series of similar reform plans that are part 
of corporate Japan's efforts to ride out the worst economic slump 
since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Electronics giants NEC Corp. and Sony Corp. recently announced  
job cuts on a similar scale. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Electric has been struggling with huge losses due to  
falling semiconductor prices and weak demand for consumer products 
like refrigerators in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects a group pretax loss of 80 billion yen, or  
$667 million, for the fiscal year which closed on Wednesday. The 
company hopes the cost-cutting measures will help it boost its 
group pretax profit to 120 billion yen, of $1 billion, by March 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Layoffs have become more common in Japan due to the long  
economic slump but are still rare at top firms like Mitsubishi, 
where employees are hired with an implicit guarantee of a job for 
life. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi said the job cuts at its parent company in Japan will  
come mostly through ``large reductions'' in new hiring rather than 
layoffs. The Mitsubishi Electric parent company in Japan employs 
46,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said it will cut nine positions from its  
33-member board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fiscal year beginning Thursday, Mitsubishi Electric will  
cut capital spending by 20 percent and research and development 
expenditures by 10 percent, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi will also reduce the number of domestic subsidiaries  
to 140 from 180. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
