<DOCNO> APW19990331.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Takes Over Yugoslav Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Yugoslav diplomats were escorted from their  
embassy Wednesday as the U.S. government took over the building in 
another blow to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to fulfill its obligations ... to protect diplomatic  
properties of states with which relations are broken, the U.S. 
government took formal custody of the former Yugoslav chancery and 
ambassador's residence,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	An hour after the midnight deadline the United States had given  
Yugoslavia to vacate the premise, State Department and Secret 
Service agents arrived to clear and secure the two buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, Yugoslavia's U.N. representative Vladislav  
Jovanovic said State Department officials came to the door of the 
embassy and asked for the key, ``and of course the key was given.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia announced March 25 it had severed diplomatic  
relations with the United States, Britain, France and Germany 
because of the NATO attack on the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Although America no longer has formal ties with Belgrade,  
Yugoslavia's pro-Western state of Montenegro retains a trade office 
in Washington. It is working to secure humanitarian assistance for 
the tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees pouring into 
Montenegro from Serbia's neighboring province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States will respect and protect the properties  
without prejudice to the eventual settlement of property issues 
among all the successor states to the former Yugoslavia,'' said Lee 
McClenny, a State Department spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past seven years, the five nations of the former  
Yugoslav union have been locked in a dispute over how to divide the 
assets left by the federation that dissolved in 1991-92. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia, which dominates the current Yugoslavia, insists it is  
the sole successor state and has refused to turn over diplomatic 
missions and hundreds of millions of dollars in joint funds. 
</P>
<P>
	With Wednesday's takeover, the government of Yugoslav  
effectively lost control over the two properties in Washington, 
whose fate will be decided by a future claims settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of the buildings -- both located just off Washington's  
main embassy row on Massachusetts Avenue -- unofficially has been 
estimated at between $4 million and $6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Jovanovic said his government asked China to represent its  
interests in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``China accepted and officially informed the State Department  
about its acceptance to represent and defend our interests in the 
United States,'' he said. ``But the host country should give its 
consent. Without that, you cannot proceed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden is the ``protecting power'' over the vast U.S. embassy  
complex in Belgrade. It was emptied last week when remaining U.S. 
diplomats were evacuated prior to NATO airstrikes. Serb protesters 
have thrashed the embassy's facade, but the building has not been 
taken over by the Yugoslavs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:11:49 </DATE_TIME>
