<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:25:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling Ready To Pitch for Phils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- Curt Schilling made his last spring  
training start on Wednesday. Yes, he was still pitching for the 
Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Surprise, surprise, the reigning NL strikeout leader hasn't been  
traded yet. And despite his occasional proclamations that he'd like 
to play for a winner, the 32-year-old right-hander says he's more 
optimistic about the season than he's been in a long time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to score more runs. I don't think there's any  
question about that,'' said Schilling, who struck out seven in six 
innings and got plenty of run support in a 10-4 victory over the 
Cincinnati Reds on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be a good defensive club. I think the same  
question since '93 is going to be the same one this year: How good 
is our starting pitching going to be?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every fifth day, it should be marvelous. But behind Schilling,  
the Phillies are counting on four relatively unproven starters to 
bridge the gap. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad Ogea, who never stayed in the majors for a full season  
before the Indians traded him, is the No. 2 starter. Carlton 
Loewer, Paul Byrd and Paul Spoljaric finish out the rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, coming off consecutive seasons with 300 or more  
strikeouts, frequently is the subject of trade rumors -- especially 
involving the Indians. He refuses to set any goals for this season 
besides winning 20 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Come July, Schilling hopes the Phillies are one player away from  
contending for the playoffs -- not on the verge of finally caving in 
to all the trade demands for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``A couple of clubs are a trade away or an injury away from  
being good or bad,'' said Schilling, who walked one and allowed 
three runs and seven hits, including a solo homer by Greg Vaughn. 
``We'll just try to compete, win more than we lose and get better 
as the season goes. Who knows? Maybe in July, something happens and 
we go out and get a player who puts us in the mix.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, who threw 108 pitches, is scheduled to start opening  
day in Atlanta against defending NL Cy Young award winner Tom 
Glavine. Manager Terry Francona said Schilling looks ready to throw 
about 120 pitches in the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's very, very strong,'' Phillies manager Terry  
Francona said. 
</P>
<P>
	He allowed four straight hits in the first inning after striking  
out leadoff batter Mike Cameron. Barry Larkin's double was followed 
by singles from Sean Casey, Vaughn and Dmitri Young. Schilling was 
ahead in the count or even on each batter. 
</P>
<P>
	The hits by Casey and Young each drove in a run, and Schilling  
got out of the inning on Brian Johnson's double-play grounder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd venture to guess that on all seven of my hits I was ahead  
with one strike or ahead with two,'' Schilling said. ``... What 
irked me was, I was getting ahead in the count, I thought I was 
making good pitches and I wasn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling struck out the side and walked one in the fourth and  
got out of a first-and-third, one-out jam in the fifth. Vaughn 
flied to the wall in center, and Young struck out looking. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling struck out swinging at a curveball from Brett Tomko in  
the fifth, taking exception to Tomko's pitch selection. Schilling 
glared at Tomko as the two walked back to the dugout, but didn't 
get to face him. Schilling retired the side in order in the sixth, 
blowing away Pokey Reese for his seventh strikeout with Tomko 
waiting on deck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, I was laughing,'' Schilling said. ``Did you see the  
swing? You can hurt yourself swinging like that. Every time I think 
I'm an athlete, I change my mind when I take a swing like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's OK, Curt. It's usually the other way around.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
