<DOCNO> APW19990331.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:52:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Upset in Calif. State Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- A teacher was poised Wednesday to become  
the first Green Party member to win state office after she shocked 
a Democratic political veteran who outspent her 20-1. 
</P>
<P>
	With almost all the votes counted, Audie Elizabeth Bock -- whose  
last bid for office was a run for high school class secretary -- 
appeared to have beaten former Oakland Mayor Elihu Harris in a 
special election for the California Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Bock held a whisper-thin margin of about 300 votes in the runoff  
election held Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a message from the voters to the Democratic Party  
machine that they aren't happy with what they've been offered,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	County officials said the vote would not be official until as  
late as Thursday, after 600 provisional and absentee ballots are 
counted. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris, who was mayor for eight years and before that had served  
12 years in the Legislature, blamed his apparent loss on low 
turnout. Only about 29,000 voters cast ballots -- 15 percent of the 
registered 190,000 voters in the district. 
</P>
<P>
	Bock, 53, teaches at a community college and runs a small  
foreign language film distribution business from her home in 
Piedmont, a small city next to Oakland. She campaigned on a promise 
of more school funding, universal health care and closing corporate 
tax loopholes. 
</P>
<P>
	Her party is similar in philosophy to Green parties in various  
European countries, sharing goals such as feminism, decentralized 
authority, nonviolence and environmental consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you're going to seen a lot more Greens running for  
office in the year 2000,'' said Nancy Marmol, spokeswoman for the 
Green Party of California. She said Greens have won city and county 
offices in various states, mostly in nonpartisan races, but have 
never captured state office. 
</P>
<P>
	Emily Stoper, a political science professor at California State  
University, Hayward, said the election surprise had more to do with 
the low turnout -- and Bock's high-energy, grass-roots campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that this indicates that the political winds are  
blowing in a different direction,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
