<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Verdict Against Michelin Thrown Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A $30 million verdict against  
Michelin Tire Co. for a truck driver who lost his legs in a crash 
has been thrown out by an appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	Michelin should have been able to remove a woman from the jury  
pool whose daughter had been involved in a Michelin tire blowout 
similar to the one suffered by Julian Lovett, the 4th District 
Court of Appeals said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ordered a new trial.  
</P>
<P>
	Lovett was hauling 21 tons of fertilizer when his left front  
tire blew in 1989. The 18-wheel truck swerved into a ditch and the 
trailer tore the cab in half. Rescuers dragged Lovett from the 
burning wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	His legs were amputated above the knees.  
</P>
<P>
	Lovett sued Michelin, the world's largest tire maker, saying the  
tire's flawed design allowed water to creep into the rubber, eating 
it away. 
</P>
<P>
	During jury selection, prospective juror Shirley Meeks mentioned  
her daughter's Michelin tire had blown out as she drove on a 
highway because of a flaw in the tire. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Michelin wanted Ms. Meeks dismissed based on how  
she was affected by her daughter's close-call. But Joe Reiter, an 
attorney for Lovett, claimed Michelin wanted her removed because 
she was black. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Meeks went on to be one of the six jurors who awarded $30.4  
million to Lovett and found Michelin 90 percent at fault for his 
crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 09:55:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	March 30  
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles Times, on Kosovo atrocities and refugees:  
</P>
<P>
	The State Department calls what's occurring on the ground in  
Kosovo an ``abhorrent and criminal action on a massive scale.'' 
Even that falls short of describing the savage war that Yugoslav 
troops are waging against their countrymen. Tens of thousands of 
Kosovars are fleeing along snow-covered mountain roads for the 
chance of safety across the borders of Macedonia, Albania or the 
Yugoslav province of Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90,000 have already reached sanctuary and have immediate  
needs for food, clothing and shelter. The United States, its NATO 
allies and international relief agencies ought to be acting now to 
provide for them, in part to preserve the refugees' welcome in the 
poor areas into which they are crowding. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayhem that Serbian soldiers and police units have waged  
against the Kosovars for daring to demand a return to the high 
level of autonomy they once enjoyed within the Yugoslav federation 
has mounted for months. What started as harassment, beatings and 
some political killings has turned in the past week to unbridled 
fratricide. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, a Serb, bears  
responsibility for this violence and for the NATO attacks on 
Belgrade, his capital, and on his soldiers in Kosovo. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Kansas City Star, on Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia has kicked its ghastly ethnic-cleansing operation  
into high gear in Kosovo, hoping to produce a tidal wave of 
international refugees before the Yugoslav forces have suffered the 
full impact of NATO air strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. and its allies must now pull out all the stops in the  
air campaign. If there is blood to be shed in Kosovo, it should be 
the blood of Slobodan Milosevic's rampaging troops rather than the 
Albanian civilians who are their intended victims. Unfortunately 
for the Albanians, NATO air power alone may not be enough to save 
them. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It is one thing to unleash high-tech air attacks against  
Yugoslavia, attacks where the NATO casualties are expected to be 
light. It would be a far different thing to send NATO ground forces 
in to protect the Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Clinton administration and other NATO governments have  
previously ruled out the use of ground troops to hold back the 
Yugoslav onslaught. But those governments should have been aware 
from the start of a fundamental rule of warfare: Conventional air 
power alone cannot do everything. 
</P>
<P>
	It appears that Clinton and other NATO leaders launched their  
air campaign without a solid backup plan. If so, they need to start 
thinking fast. 

</P>
<P>
	March 26  
</P>
<P>
	Naples (Fla.) Daily News, on Yugoslavia:  
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's speech to the nation on Kosovo was very much  
of a piece with the man. Rather than the cold calculations of great 
power politics, he dwelled on the humanitarian aspects of the 
mission and his comassion for ``innocent people taken from their 
homes, forced to kneel in the dirt and sprayed with bullets ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the policy that's wrong; it's making the constraints  
public. Clearly, the president was trying to reassure the public 
and especially the Republican-led Congress where there is 
substantial opposition to American troops serving in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Yugoslavia began violently fragmenting in 1991, the United  
States has been too public about its reservations and doubts in the 
Balkans. Our insincere threats and self-imposed deadlines have only 
given the warring parties incentives to step up the fighting and 
try to grab even more territory. ... 
</P>
<P>
	By saying NATO and ... U.S. troops would only enter Kosovo if  
invited and not fight once they got there, Clinton in a sense is 
ceding the initiative to Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	The implication is that if he hangs on until NATO tires of the  
air strikes, he can resume his bloody suppression of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Make Milosevic sweat our intentions, not vice versa.  

</P>
<P>
	March 22  
</P>
<P>
	Albany (Ore.) Democrat-Herald, on the Kosovo crisis:  
</P>
<P>
	Americans have been given no convincing reason why U.S.  
warplanes are bombing the Kosovo province of Serbia, one of the 
parts of the Yugoslav federation. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton says we have to do it. That's not a persuasive  
argument. The more he says it, the more Americans have reason to 
doubt it. Remember the way he wags his finger. 
</P>
<P>
	The news from Washington and the other capitals sounds very much  
like the saber rattling and propaganda that precedes all other 
wars, the just and good ones as well as the aggresive and bad ones. 
</P>
<P>
	It is frightening that at the end of the 20th Century we seem to  
have regressed to the way countries and alliances acted at the 
start. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO is a defensive alliance. Its mission now, without an avowed  
enemy, is very murky. But that hardly justifies launching bombing 
raids in support of diplomacy against a country that has not raised 
a finger against any member of the alliance. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 25  
</P>
<P>
	The Index-Journal, Greenwood, S.C., on American involvement in  
Kosovo: 
</P>
<P>
	It never works. Getting into somebody else's civil war is a  
bottomless pit, and that's just what this nation faces now that 
we've joined the bombing of Serb forces in Yugoslavia. ... 
</P>
<P>
	We should know better. It's not like we don't know what to  
expect. It is indeed a civil war we've jumped into, one that has 
been going on for centuries. It's unlikely that any amount of 
outside pressure, military or otherwise, will change how people 
there feel. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Long-term stability of Europe and our national interest, we are  
told, require military action. President Clinton called the 
confrontation with Serb President Slobodan Milosevic a stand 
against ``destructive racial, ethnic, religious and cultural'' 
aggression. 
</P>
<P>
	If that be the case, you have to wonder why we haven't mounted  
similar campaigns in other troubled areas of the world, such as 
Rwanda, for instance, where mass murder between the Hutus and 
Tutsis has been of genocidal proportions. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 26  
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio Express-News, on hate crimes resolution:  
</P>
<P>
	It should be a bipartisan no- brainer, a unanimous vote in the  
House of Representatives condemning bigotry in its many guises. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet House Democrats defeated a resolution offered by Rep. J.C.  
Watts, R-Okla., reaffirming the House's opposition to ``any 
individuals or organizations which seek to divide Americans on the 
grounds of race, religion or ethnic prejudice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As noble as Watt's resolution sounds, Democrats saw it for what  
it was: a disingenuous attempt to deflect criticism from Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Watt's bill was in response to a measure introduced by Reps.  
Robert Wexler, D-Fla., and Michael P. Forbes, R- N.Y., that 
condemned ``the racism and bigotry espoused by the Council of 
Conservative Citizens,'' a white supremacist group whom Barr and 
Lott have addressed. Both condemned the group's racism when their 
appearances became publicly known. 
</P>
<P>
	Watts contends it is wrong to single out a group for bigotry  
when racism is more widespread. He's right, except when members of 
Congress have given the organization credibility it does not 
deserve. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 25  
</P>
<P>
	Cape Cod Times, Hyannis, Mass., on northern right whale:  
</P>
<P>
	Despite government efforts to protect the species, the northern  
right whale, the world's rarest and most endangered large whale, 
may be headed for extinction. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the word from researchers at the Woods Hole Oceanographic  
Institution and the University of Massachusetts at Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about 300 of the northern species remain. Another  
population of right whales, numbering a few thousand, lives in the 
Southern Hemisphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current conditions, the researchers said, the species  
could become extinct in less than 200 years. Long a symbol of the 
maritime heritage of Massachusetts, the northern right whale must 
be saved. 
</P>
<P>
	While other whales, such as humpbacks, have rebounded since  
federal protections were put in place decades ago, the right whale 
population has been declining by a few whales each year since the 
1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The main culprit seems to be collisions with ships and fishing  
gear entanglements. In other words, the problem is us. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 30  
</P>
<P>
	The Sacramento (Calif.) Bee, on medicinal marijuana:  
</P>
<P>
	A new report on marijuana by the Institutes of Medicine offers a  
rational approach to one of the nation's most controversial 
substances. In the most comprehensive review to date by a panel of 
distinguished medical experts, the IOM has concluded that certain 
chemicals inside marijuana known as THC and cannabinoids are, 
indeed, medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The medical challenge now is to isolate all of marijuana's  
helpful ingredients from the harmful ones in some new form, such as 
a pill or vapor that is inhaled. The political challenge is how to 
handle marijuana in the coming years (and they may be many) before 
a real alternative to the joint is on the market. ... 

</P>
<P>
	March 23  
</P>
<P>
	Vindicator, Youngstown, Ohio, on balloon adventure:  
</P>
<P>
	Jules Verne had fantasized about it in his book ``Five Weeks in  
a Balloon.'' Adventurers Steve Fossett and Richard Branson had 
failed in their attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bertrand Piccard, a Swiss psychiatrist, and Brian Jones, an  
English pilot, have become the first to circumnavigate the Earth in 
a balloon. 
</P>
<P>
	Their achievement is a tribute to their indomitable spirits and  
to the technological achievements that made it possible for the two 
men to remain aloft -- at times, close to an altitude of 40,000 feet 
-- for nearly 20 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps breaking the sought-after record was meant to be  
accomplished by men who were quieter and more introspective than 
the flamboyant Fossett and Branson, men who were less aware of 
their own fame and fortune and more aware of their having literally 
and figuratively transcended the intolerance that divided the 
people of the earth beneath them. 
</P>
<P>
	Being closer to God, it seems, was as important to Piccard as  
the glory of the record books and the million-dollar prize offered 
by Anheuser-Busch. Humankind needs more such men. 

</P>
<P>
	March 26  
</P>
<P>
	Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal, on U.S.-Cuban exhibition baseball  
game: 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. hardball diplomacy with Fidel Castro's Cuba takes on a  
whole new form Sunday. It's being described by the Clinton 
administration as part of the effort to reach out to the Cuban 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The American League's Baltimore Orioles are traveling to Havana  
to play an exhibition baseball game against a Cuban all-star team. 
It will be the first major league exhibition game in Cuba since 
1959 when the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers played Cuban 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubans are among the hemisphere's most avid baseball fans, and  
over the years a number of Cubans have been star major league 
players. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's game might be the start of a ``baseball diplomacy''  
between the United States and Cuba similar to the ``ping pong 
diplomacy'' that helped ease tensions between the United States and 
China during the Nixon administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty years of enmity must have made it clear to Cubans that the  
U.S. government is fundamentally opposed to Castro. Nine innings of 
baseball legitimizes nothing more than love of a game shared by 
Cubans and Americans. 

</P>
