<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buttafuoco Supports Fisher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher has won the support of  
prosecutors in her motion to vacate her assault conviction -- and 
also the backing of the woman she shot in the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Jo Buttafuoco joined prosecutors in the motion on behalf of  
Ms. Fisher, who said she was denied effective legal advice when she 
pleaded guilty to first-degree assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher has been in jail for almost seven years for shooting  
Mrs. Buttafuoco, the wife of her lover. The case drew national 
attention and she was dubbed the ``Long Island Lolita.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Buttafuoco said in a letter that she forgave her attacker  
after meeting with her mother and corresponding with Ms. Fisher, 
now 24, for several months. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher said she was duped by her former lawyer into  
believing that if she pleaded guilty, prosecutors would help her 
enter a work release program and earn parole within three years. 
</P>
<P>
	She was sentenced to five to 15 years in prison. District  
Attorney Denis Dillon said his office had never promised a work 
release sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	A ruling on the motion was expected on April 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
