<DOCNO> APW19990331.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 07:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Seeks To Ban 'Pay-to-Play' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The financial comptroller of a large state  
raises $1.8 million for his campaign coffers from investment 
companies, many of them from other states, seeking pension fund 
business. A treasurer of a small state raises nearly all his 
campaign donations from money managers for pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	These anecdotes are being cited by Arthur Levitt, chairman of  
the Securities and Exchange Commission, as examples of a practice 
he is seeking to stamp out: money managers making campaign 
donations to state and local officials who oversee public-employee 
pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake: the management of such funds, which hold more than $2  
trillion in assets nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The donations by money managers seeking pension business can  
tilt the political playing field, Levitt and other critics say. 
Thousands of police, firefighters, teachers and other public 
employees may be unwittingly entrusting their retirement savings to 
financial companies with the strongest political ties rather than 
those most qualified to manage the funds, they argue. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign contributions, while legal, create an ethical  
problem when they are used to influence the selection of money 
managers in a practice known as pay-to-play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time we move to put an end to the culture of pay-to-play  
in the area of municipal money management,'' Levitt said in a 
speech Tuesday to the Council of Institutional Investors, a group 
of public, corporate and labor-union pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tremendous importance of public (pension) funds demands  
that they be managed with complete honesty and integrity and for 
the sole benefit'' of their retirees, Levitt said. He decried 
pay-to-play as a form of ``backroom deal'' that ``breeds cynicism 
(toward) government officials and contempt for the political 
process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Stamping out this behavior is difficult and may be possibly  
disruptive. But it is absolutely necessary,'' he said. ``Old ways 
of doing business must give way when they jeopardize the trust of 
the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt, as the government's top securities regulator, and the  
SEC have authority over the money managers and brokerage firms that 
advise pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the agency will consider in April or May a new rule that  
would restrict pay-to-play payments by money managers to the 
pension funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC did that in 1994 with regard to the $1.3 trillion  
municipal bond market, restricting how much money bond underwriting 
firms can contribute to state and local officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been effective with respect to municipals, and I'd expect  
it would be effective with respect to advisers,'' Levitt said after 
his speech Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the SEC's 1994 action, many bond underwriters have gotten  
around the municipal pay-to-play restrictions by making donations 
to political parties rather than particular state and local 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	And the new proposal for public pension funds is likely to face  
resistance. 
</P>
<P>
	In California, the state public-employee retirement fund -- the  
nation's largest with more than $150 billion in assets -- put a rule 
in place last year barring its directors from getting campaign 
contributions from money managers seeking business. 
</P>
<P>
	But after State Controller Kathleen Connell sued the retirement  
fund, known as Calpers, claiming the restriction was hurting her 
re-election effort, a state judge threw out the rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Chicago City Treasurer Miriam Santos was indicted  
for alleged attempted extortion in fundraising for her 1998 
campaign for Illinois attorney general. Ms. Santos pleaded innocent 
to the charges, which include pressuring brokerage firms for 
donations of $10,000 each and cutting off firms that wouldn't 
contribute from city business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990331.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 05:35:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Rice Swim Coach Sues Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A former Rice University swimming coach is suing  
14 student-athletes she blames for bad-mouthing her coaching 
ability until she lost her job. 
</P>
<P>
	Kris Wingenroth, 45, coached men's and women's swimming teams at  
Rice for 15 years until her contract was not renewed last summer. 
Her tenure included five coach of the year awards in the Southwest 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingenroth claims students were on a mission to oust her,  
complaining that she was too soft. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice was stunned by the lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is not another single reported case in the world of a  
coach suing the athletes who criticized the coach,'' attorney Rusty 
Hardin, hired by the school to represent the students, told the 
Houston Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rice's position is the students have to feel free to express  
their opinions. If they can't do that, then the whole idea of a 
university as a place to freely exchange ideas will go down the 
tubes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardin said the school decided not to renew the coach's contract  
after looking into the students' concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingenroth, who Hardin said is now in Ecuador studying Spanish,  
initially sued two swimmers, Cory Teague and Christian 
Selchau-Hansen, in state court in December. She added 12 more to 
the list earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The former coach is seeking unspecified actual and punitive  
damages for several legal claims, including defamation, conspiracy 
to interfere with her contract and intentional infliction of 
emotional distress. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 7, her attorney filed a 75-paragraph document outlining  
what the swimmers allegedly did to get her fired. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the lawsuit, Wingenroth's first confrontation with  
swimmers occurred in March 1995, after she reported to university 
officials that several swimmers had used illegal drugs at a party. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials met with the students but did not punish  
them, the lawsuit says, and soon afterward swimmer Carrell 
Covington allegedly told Wingenroth she would make it her 
``mission'' to get the coach fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardin declined to comment on specific allegations in the  
lawsuit, but said it was ``replete with inaccuracies,'' designed to 
embarrass the students and to intimidate their parents into 
settling. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingenroth was replaced by Doug Boyd, the NCAA Division III  
Coach of the Year in 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	All but four defendants in the case still attend Rice, officials  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
