<DOCNO> APW19990331.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parties Work Together in Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From Jesse Helms to Ted Kennedy, Republicans  
and Democrats are finding that in this age of political distrust, 
they still need each other to get things done in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Measures on such touchy subjects as tobacco, taxes and health  
care are being offered jointly by Republicans and Democrats who 
know that without a soulmate from the other party, their bills are 
likely to go nowhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign finance reform, mainly a Democratic priority, made  
headway last year and is back again this year, in part because two 
Republicans, Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Sen. John 
McCain of Arizona, joined two Democrats, Rep. Marty Meehan of 
Massachusetts and Sen. Russ Feingold of Wisconsin, in sponsoring 
the House and Senate bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Reining in government regulations, long a goal of Republicans,  
has some chance of advancing this year because Sen. Fred Thompson, 
R-Tenn., has a Democrat, Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan, as his 
legislative partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes a long time to get the credibility to pass a bill  
like campaign finance reform,'' Meehan said. ``With Republicans in 
the majority, having Chris Shays being the lead on this bill was 
extremely important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeastern Democrat is also working with a Western  
Republican, Rep. James Hansen of Utah, on a bill requiring states 
to set aside a quarter of tobacco settlement money on smoking 
health and awareness programs. ``We don't agree on very many 
issues, but we do on tobacco,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, Republicans holding a slim 11-seat majority need  
all the Democratic help they can get. In the Senate, where the 
minority holds more sway because of filibuster rules, there's long 
been a tradition of reaching across the aisle. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it's a controversial bill, it is almost a necessity if  
you are going to get beyond the filibuster,'' said Sen. Charles 
Grassley, R-Iowa, who is teaming this year with Sen. Bob Graham, 
D-Fla., on a bill making it easier to carry pensions from one job 
to another and with Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., on a bankruptcy 
overhaul bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate historian Donald Ritchie recalled how liberal Robert  
Wagner, a New York Democrat, joined with conservative Robert Taft, 
an Ohio Republican, to bring opposing sides together on a major 
public housing legislation after World War II. ``There's historical 
precedent for bipartisanship,'' he said. ``Perhaps they are now 
reverting to form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GOP-Democratic cooperation was even evident during the Senate  
impeachment trial. Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Joseph 
Lieberman, D-Conn., unsuccessfully pushed a plan to limit the trial 
to one week, and Sens. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, and Dianne 
Feinstein, D-Calif., joined later, again unsuccessfully, on a 
resolution to censure President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Moderates such as Feinstein are the most apt to work with the  
opposition. Last year she and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, backed one 
of the big anti-tobacco bills. This year she has proposed a crime 
victims constitutional amendment with Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., a Y2K 
liability bill with Hatch, a money-laundering bill with Sen. Paul 
Coverdell, R-Ga., and a bill involving hospital stays for 
mastectomy patients with Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometimes the partnerships span wide ideological  
differences. Conservative Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Democratic 
loyalist Torricelli are jointly behind a bill to help Taiwan better 
defend itself. 
</P>
<P>
	A Democratic-drafted HMO consumer protection plan that nearly  
passed the House last year paired Rep. John Dingell, a pro-labor 
Democrat from Michigan, with Rep. Greg Ganske, a wealthy Republican 
surgeon from Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the odder couples is Hatch and Kennedy, who have crossed  
ideological lines to co-author several bills, including an 
unsuccessful attempt in the last Congress to extend health care to 
more uninsured children. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always feel better if I can find a Democrat,'' the  
conservative Hatch said. ``I shriek for joy and jump up and down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy, D-Mass., a champion of liberal causes, is also regarded  
as a master of the political compromise. He has sponsored bills 
with such conservatives as Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., and former 
Sen. Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C., and in the 1980s pushed through a big 
jobs bill with then-Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	And after the Clinton White House failed in its attempt to  
revolutionize the health care system, it was Kennedy who stepped 
forward with then-Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., in 1996 to pass a 
more modest but still significant bill making it easier to carry 
health insurance from one job to another. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
