<DOCNO> APW19990331.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 23:53:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCord Mulls Chances in Tradition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- In Gary McCord's view, only a handful  
of players are capable of winning The Tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	``No more than 10,'' the CBS golf color analyst said. ``Hale  
Irwin is right there in the top two, and `Flasher' (Bruce 
Fleischer) is the other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The way Irwin sees it, McCord has the game to be counted if he  
wants to concentrate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's never had something,'' Irwin said. ``I don't know if it's  
desire, the intent. He's a multilayered guy -- maybe that's a nice 
way of saying a where-is-he-coming-from kind of guy, but his golf 
game has always been very, very good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The affable McCord has a new contract with the network that  
allows him a dozen weekends a year to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	He also is working on his third book about golf and is producing  
a movie about the life of gambling golfer Titanic Thompson, an 
outgrowth of his work as a technical consultant for the Kevin 
Costner film ``Tin Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his spare time, the Scottsdale resident operates a teaching  
center with Peter Kostis. And McCord focused on golf three weeks 
ago and won a senior event in Newport Beach, Calif. -- the first 
title at any level of a pro career that began in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	His path will be somewhat cleared by the withdrawal of two-time  
champion Gil Morgan, who pulled out Wednesday because of a sore 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan is the first senior since Jack Kiefer at the Canadian  
Senior Open last year who didn't attempt to defend a title. Morgan 
withdrew from last week's event after two rounds because of back 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very disappointing to have to pull out of The Tradition  
this year, especially with the opportunity to win for a third 
straight time,'' Morgan said. ``You only get a chance like this 
maybe once in a lifetime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four-time champion Jack Nicklaus also is missing, along with  
former winners Don Bies and Lee Trevino. That leaves only two 
former champions -- Tom Shaw (1993) and Raymond Floyd (1994) -- in 
the 11th Tradition, sponsored by Countrywide. 
</P>
<P>
	But there is still plenty of talent gathered on the hilly,  
arroyo-cut Cochise Course, one of five Nicklaus designed for Desert 
Mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Duval is in McCord's category, a first-time winner last week  
who hopes to add a major to his resume before his son David Duval 
does. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleischer has won twice, finished second twice and won $532,400  
in four tournaments as a rookie on the senior tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised a little by my play,'' Fleischer said. ``I don't  
feel as intimidated as I once did, especially not out here. As you 
get older, maybe the drive isn't as great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And no one can overlook Irwin, who rampaged through the Senior  
PGA for two years, winning 16 of his 20 titles, the U.S. Senior 
Open and two of his three Senior PGA Championships in that span. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin hasn't won an official event this year, though, and said  
he was due to slow down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's really attributable to the downside of what has  
been a two-year run,'' said Irwin, who has won a record $7,620,253 
in about four years on the senior tour. ``I think I lost a little 
bit of momentum over the holidays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he said, it's time to refocus and claim the title that  
eluded him in 1996 when Nicklaus made up a 1-stroke deficit in the 
final round. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me to get back, I need a tournament like this,'' Irwin  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
